{"title_page": "Radio 101.2 (Belarus)", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name               = Radio 101.2 <br /> ({{lang-be|\u0420\u0430\u0434\u044b\u0451 101,2}})\n| image              = [[File:Fm_radio101 2.png|180px|Radio 101,2 logo]]\n| city               = [[Minsk]], [[Belarus]] \n| area               = \n| branding           = \n| slogan             = \n| frequency          = {{Frequency|101.2|[[Minsk]] FM}} \n| translator         = \n| repeater           = \n| airdate            = {{Start date|1995|7|21}}\n| last airdate       = August 31, 1996\n| share              = \n| share as of        = \n| share source       = \n| format             = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Popular music|Popular]]\n| language           = [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]]\n| power              = \n| erp                = \n| haat               = \n| class              = \n| facility_id        = \n| coordinates        = <!-- {{coord|}} -->\n| callsign_meaning   = \n| former_callsigns   = \n| former_frequencies = <!-- use \u2013 -->\n| affiliations       = \n| owner              = [[Open Society Foundations]]\n| licensee           = \n| sister_stations    = \n| webcast            = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Radio 101.2''' was a radio station in the [[Belarus]]ian capital of [[Minsk]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://radio.tut.by/articles/art/1012fm.shtml|title=\u0420\u0430\u0434\u044b\u0451 101 \u0456 2, \u0413\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0456 \u043a\u0430\u043d\u0430\u043b|last=\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0435\u0432\u0456\u0447|first=\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0436|date=|website=|publisher=[[TUT.BY]]|language=be|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20050308183857/http://radio.tut.by/articles/art/1012fm.shtml|archivedate=2005-03-08|accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> In 1995 and 1996 the radio station, which is at the frequency 101.2, was broadcasting news and was not affiliated with the [[Government of Belarus|national government]].\n\n[[Open Society Foundations|Soros Foundation]] helped to buy the equipment for newly started radio in 1995.<ref>Hansjoerg Biener. [http://www.evrel.ewf.uni-erlangen.de/pesc/peaceradio-BLR.html Radio for Peace, Democracy and Human Rights]</ref> The station was closed on formally technical reasons and was transferred over to the [[Belarusian Republican Youth Union]], who still uses the radio today. The government has claimed that the station, and its frequency, was interfering with the radio communications of the Minsk police force. Independent groups claimed that this was another method by the government of [[Alexander Lukashenko]] to suppress the [[freedom of the press]] inside of Belarus.\n\n{{coord missing|Belarus}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Autoradio (Belarus)]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101107042138/http://baj.by/m-p-viewpub-tid-1-pid-8800.html 15 \u0433\u0430\u0434\u043e\u045e \u0442\u0430\u043c\u0443 \u045e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0448\u044b\u043d\u044e \u0432\u044b\u0439\u0448\u043b\u0430 \u045e \u044d\u0444\u0456\u0440 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u044b\u0451 101.2] {{in lang|be}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Media in Minsk]]\n\n\n{{Belarus-media-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name               = Radio 101.2 <br /> ({{lang-be|\u0420\u0430\u0434\u044b\u0451 101,2}})\n| image              = [[File:Fm_radio101 2.png|180px|Radio 101,2 logo]]\n| city               = [[Minsk]], [[Belarus]] \n| area               = \n| branding           = \n| slogan             = \n| frequency          = {{Frequency|101.2|[[Minsk]] FM}} \n| translator         = \n| repeater           = \n| airdate            = {{Start date|1995|7|21}}\n| last airdate       = August 31, 1996\n| share              = \n| share as of        = \n| share source       = \n| format             = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Popular music|Popular]]\n| language           = [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]]\n| power              = \n| erp                = \n| haat               = \n| class              = \n| facility_id        = \n| coordinates        = <!-- {{coord|}} -->\n| callsign_meaning   = \n| former_callsigns   = \n| former_frequencies = <!-- use \u2013 -->\n| affiliations       = \n| owner              = [[Open Society Foundations]]\n| licensee           = \n| sister_stations    = \n| webcast            = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Radio 101.2''' was a radio station in the [[Belarus]]ian capital of [[Minsk]]. In 1995 and 1996 the radio station, which is at the frequency 101.2, was broadcasting news and was not affiliated with the [[Government of Belarus|national government]].\n\n[[Open Society Foundations|Soros Foundation]] helped to buy the equipment for newly started radio in 1995.<ref>Hansjoerg Biener. [http://www.evrel.ewf.uni-erlangen.de/pesc/peaceradio-BLR.html Radio for Peace, Democracy and Human Rights]</ref> The station was closed on formally technical reasons and was transferred over to the [[Belarusian Republican Youth Union]], who still uses the radio today. The government has claimed that the station, and its frequency, was interfering with the radio communications of the Minsk police force. Independent groups claimed that this was another method by the government of [[Alexander Lukashenko]] to suppress the [[freedom of the press]] inside of Belarus.\n\n{{coord missing|Belarus}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Autoradio (Belarus)]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101107042138/http://baj.by/m-p-viewpub-tid-1-pid-8800.html 15 \u0433\u0430\u0434\u043e\u045e \u0442\u0430\u043c\u0443 \u045e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0448\u044b\u043d\u044e \u0432\u044b\u0439\u0448\u043b\u0430 \u045e \u044d\u0444\u0456\u0440 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u044b\u0451 101.2] {{in lang|be}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Media in Minsk]]\n\n\n{{Belarus-media-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pr12402", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radio_101.2_(Belarus)"}
{"title_page": "Long Beach State Beach men's volleyball", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2010}}\n{{Infobox college volleyball team|AIAW=no\n|name = Long Beach State Beach\n|logo = Beach-Big.png\n|logo_size = 175\n|university = Long Beach State University\n|conference = Mountain Pacific Sports Federation\n|conference_short = Big West\n|division =\n|city = Long Beach\n|stateabb = CA\n|state = California\n|coach = [[Alan Knipe]]\n|tenure = 16th\n|arena = [[Walter Pyramid]], 2019\n|capacity = 5,000\n|nickname = LB 49ers\n|NCAAchampion = 1991, 2018, 2019\n|NCAArunnerup = 1970, 1973, 1990, 1999, 2004\n|NCAAfinalfour = 1970, 1973, 1990, 1991, 1999, 2004, 2008, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n|NCAAtourneys = 1970, 1971, 1972, 1973, 1978, 1981, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1990, 1991, 1999, 2004, 2008, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n|conference_tournament = 1973, 1990, 1991, 2017, 2018\n|conference_season = SCIVA: 1973 <br />WIVA: 1990, 1992 <br />MPSF: 1999, 2000, 2001, 2008, 2017 <br />Big West: 2018, 2019\n}}\n\nThe '''Long Beach State Beach men's volleyball''' team is the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] Division I men's volleyball team for the [[California State University, Long Beach|Long Beach State University]]. [[Alan Knipe]] is the current head coach of 14 years, though he's been with the program since 2001.\n\n==Program record and history==\n<small>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Year\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Head Coach\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Overall <br /> Record\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Conference<br /> Record\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Conference<br /> Standing\n! style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\"|Postseason\n|-\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead|\n|name=\n|startyear=1970\n|conference=''[[SCIVA Conderence|SCIVA]]''\n|endyear=1978\n|}}\n|-\n| 1970\n| Randy Sandefur\n| 6\u20134\n| 3\u20132\n| 3rd\n| [[1970 NCAA Division I Men's Volleyball Tournament|NCAA]] Runners-up