{"title_page": "Fanzine", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Short description|Magazine published by fans}}\nA '''fanzine''' ([[blend word|blend]] of ''[[fan (person)|fan]]'' and ''magazine'' or ''-[[zine]]'') is a non-professional and non-official publication produced by [[fan (person)|enthusiasts]] of a particular cultural [[phenomenon]] (such as a literary or musical genre) for the pleasure of others who share their interest. The term was coined in an October 1940 [[science fiction fanzine]] by [[Russ Chauvenet]] and first popularized within [[science fiction fandom]], and from there it was adopted by other communities.\n\nTypically, publishers, editors, writers and other contributors of [[Article (publishing)|articles]] or [[illustration]]s to fanzines are not paid. Fanzines are traditionally circulated free of charge, or for a nominal cost to defray postage or production expenses. Copies are often offered in exchange for similar publications, or for contributions of art, articles, or letters of comment (LoCs), which are then published.\n\nSome fanzines are typed and photocopied by amateurs using standard home office equipment. A few fanzines have developed into professional publications (sometimes known as \"prozines\"), and many professional writers were first published in fanzines; some continue to contribute to them after establishing a professional reputation. The term fanzine is sometimes confused with \"[[fan magazine]]\", but the latter term most often refers to commercially produced publications ''for'' (rather than ''by'') fans.\n\n==Origin==\nThe origins of amateur [[fanac]] \"fan\" publications are obscure, but can be traced at least back to 19th century literary groups in the United States which formed [[amateur press association]]s to publish collections of amateur fiction, poetry and commentary, such as [[H.P. Lovecraft]]'s ''United Amateur''.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Myawoc_PbF4C&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=hp+lovecraft+united+amateur+amateur+press+association#v=onepage&q=hp%20lovecraft%20united%20amateur%20amateur%20press%20association&f=false |title=An H.P. Lovecraft Encyclopedia |last=Schultz |first=David E. |website=books.google.es |publisher=Hippocampus Press |year=2001 |access-date=13 October 2019|isbn=9780313315787 }}</ref>\n\nAs professional printing technology progressed, so did the technology of fanzines. Early fanzines were hand-drafted or typed on a manual typewriter and printed using primitive reproduction techniques (e.g., the [[spirit duplicator]] or even the [[hectograph]]). Only a very small number of copies could be made at a time, so circulation was extremely limited. The use of [[mimeograph machine]]s enabled greater press runs, and the photocopier increased the speed and ease of publishing once more. Today, thanks to the advent of [[desktop publishing]] and [[self-publishing|self-publication]], there is often little difference between the appearance of a fanzine and a professional magazine.\n\n==Genres==\n\n===Science fiction===\n{{Main|Science fiction fanzines}}\n{{Category see also|Science fiction fanzines}}\n\nWhen [[Hugo Gernsback]] published the first [[science fiction magazine]], ''[[Amazing Stories]]'' in 1926, he allowed for a large letter column which printed reader's addresses. By 1927 readers, often young adults, would write to each other, bypassing the magazine.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Science fiction fanzines had their beginnings in Serious & Constructive (later shortened to [[sercon]]) correspondence.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Fans finding themselves writing the same letter to several correspondents sought to save themselves a lot of typing by duplicating their letters.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nEarly efforts included simple [[carbon copy|carbon copies]] but that proved insufficient.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} The first science fiction fanzine, ''[[The Comet]]'', was published in 1930 by the [[Science Correspondence Club]] in Chicago and edited by [[Raymond A. Palmer]] and [[Walter Dennis]].<ref name=\"moskowitz\">{{cite book | first1 = Sam | last1 = Moskowitz | authorlink1 = Sam Moskowitz |first2=Joe |last2= Sanders|authorlink2=Joe Sanders | title = The Origins of Science Fiction Fandom: A Reconstruction | booktitle = Science Fiction Fandom | pages = 17\u201336 | publisher = Greenwood Press | year = 1994 | location = Westport, CT }}</ref> The term \"fanzine\" was coined by [[Russ Chauvenet]] in the October 1940 edition of his fanzine ''Detours''. \"Fanzines\" were distinguished from \"prozines,\" (a term Chauvenet also invented): that is, all professional magazines. Prior to that, the fan publications were known as \"fanmags\" or \"letterzines\".{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nScience fiction fanzines used a variety of printing methods. Typewriters, school dittos, church mimeos and (if they could afford it) multi-color letterpress or other mid-to-high level printing. Some fans wanted their news spread, others reveled in the artistry and beauty of fine printing.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} The [[hectograph]], introduced around 1876, was so named because it could produce (in theory) up to a hundred copies. Hecto used an [[aniline]] dye, transferred to a tray of gelatin, and paper would be placed on the gel, one sheet at a time, for transfer. Messy and smelly, the process could create vibrant colors for the few copies produced, the easiest aniline dye to make being purple (technically [[indigo]]). The next small but significant technological step after hecto is the [[spirit duplicator]], essentially the hectography process using a drum instead of the gelatin. Introduced by [[Ditto Corporation]] in 1923, these machines were known for the next six decades as Ditto Machines and used by fans because they were cheap to use and could (with a little effort) print in color.\n\nThe [[mimeograph]] machine, which forced ink through a wax paper stencil cut by the keys of a typewriter, was the standard for many decades. A second-hand mimeo could print hundreds of copies and (with more than a little effort) print in color. The [[electronic stencil cutter]] (shortened to \"electrostencil\" by most) could add photographs and illustrations to a mimeo stencil. A mimeo'd zine could look terrible or look beautiful, depending more on the skill of the mimeo operator than the quality of the equipment. Only a few fans could afford more professional printers, or the time it took them to print, until photocopying became cheap and ubiquitous in the 1970s. With the advent of computer printers and desktop publishing in the 1980s, fanzines began to look far more professional. The rise of the internet made correspondence cheaper and ''much'' faster, and the [[World Wide Web]] has made publishing a fanzine as simple as coding a web page.\n\nThe printing technology affected the style of writing.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} For example, there were alphanumeric contractions which are actually precursors to \"[[leet]]-speak\".{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}  (A well-known example is the \"initials\" used by [[Forrest J. Ackerman]] in his fanzines from the 30s, and 40s, namely \"4sj\".{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}  Fans around the world knew Ackerman by three letters \"4sj\" or even two: \"4e\" for \"Forry.\")  [[Fanspeak]] is rich with abbreviations and concatenations. Where teenagers labored to save typing on ditto masters, they now save keystrokes when text messaging. Ackerman invented nonstoparagraphing as a space-saving measure.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cohen|first1=Philip|title=Language of Science Fiction Fandom|journal=Word Ways|year=1975|volume=8|issue=1|pages=5\u20136}}</ref> When the typist comes to the end of a paragraph, they simply moved the platen down one line.\n\nNever commercial enterprises, most [[science fiction fanzine]]s were (and many still are) available for \"the usual,\" meaning that a sample issue will be mailed on request; to receive further issues, a reader sends a \"letter of comment\" (LoC) about the fanzine to the editor.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} The LoC might be published in the next issue; some fanzines consisted almost exclusively of letter columns, where discussions were conducted in much the same way as they are in internet [[newsgroup]]s and [[mailing list]]s today, though at a relatively glacial pace. Often fanzine editors (\"faneds\") would simply swap issues with each other, not worrying too much about matching trade for trade, somewhat like being on one another's [[LiveJournal#The word .22friend.22|friends list]]. Without being closely connected with the rest of fandom, a budding faned could read fanzine reviews in prozines, and fanzines reviewed other fanzines. Recent technology has changed the speed of communication between fans and the technology available, but the basic concepts developed by science fiction fanzines in the 1930s can be seen online today. Blogs \u2013 with their threaded comments, personalized illustrations, shorthand in-jokes, wide variety in quality and wider variety of content\u2014follow the structure developed in science fiction fanzines, without (usually) realizing the antecedent.\n\nSince 1937, science fiction fans have formed [[amateur press association]]s (APAs); the members contribute to a collective assemblage or bundle that contains contributions from all of them, called [[apazine]]s and often containing [[mailing comment]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Southard|first1=Bruce|title=The Language of Science-Fiction Fan Magazines|journal=American Speech|date=Spring 1982|volume=57|issue=1|page=23|doi=10.2307/455177|jstor=i219220}}</ref> Some APAs are still active, and some are published as virtual \"e-zines,\" distributed on the Internet.<ref name=\"That's Not Online\">{{cite web|title=Amateur Press Associations (APAs) (UPDATED)|url=http://thatsnotonline.tumblr.com/post/4313215829/amateur-press-associations-apas-updated|website=That's Not Online|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref> Specific [[Hugo Award]]s are given for [[Hugo Award for Best Fanzine|fanzines]], [[Hugo Award for Best Fan Writer|fan writing]] and [[Hugo Award for Best Fan Artist|fanart]].\n\n==== Media  ====\nMedia fanzines were originally merely a subgenre of SF fanzines, written by science fiction fans already familiar with apazines. The first media fanzine was a ''[[Star Trek]]'' fan publication called ''[[Spockanalia]]'', published in September 1967<ref name=\"verba2003\">{{cite book | title=Boldly Writing: A Trekker Fan & Zine History, 1967\u20131987 | author=Verba, Joan Marie | year=2003 | publisher=FTL Publications | location=Minnetonka MN | url=http://www.ftlpublications.com/bwebook.pdf | isbn=0-9653575-4-6 | access-date=6 October 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910042451/http://www.ftlpublications.com/bwebook.pdf | archive-date=10 September 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>{{rp|1}}<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/21/nyregion/21winston.html?pagewanted=print | work=The New York Times | title=Joan Winston, 'Trek' Superfan, Dies at 77 | first=William | last=Grimes | date=21 September 2008 | accessdate=2 April 2010}}</ref> by members of the [[Lunacon|Lunarians]].<ref name=\"cbs2000\">{{cite book | title=Science Fiction Culture | publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press | author=Bacon-Smith, Camille | pages=112\u2013113 | url=https://books.google.com/?id=oCvIZpCSRA0C&lpg=PA112&pg=PA112#v=onepage&f=false | year=2000 | isbn=978-0-8122-1530-4}}</ref> They hoped that fanzines such as ''Spockanalia'' would be recognized by the broader science-fiction fan community in traditional ways, such as a [[Hugo Award for Best Fanzine]].{{r|verba2003}}{{rp|6}} All five of its issues were published while the show was still on the air, and included letters from [[D. C. Fontana]], [[Gene Roddenberry]], and most of the cast members, and an article by future Hugo and Nebula winner [[Lois McMaster Bujold]].{{r|verba2003}}{{rp|1,2,83}}\n\nMany other Star Trek 'zines followed, then slowly zines appeared for other media sources, such as ''[[Starsky and Hutch]]'', ''[[Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'' and ''[[Blake's 7]]''. By the mid-1970s, there were enough media zines being published that [[adzines]] existed just to advertise all of the other zines available. Although ''Spockanalia'' had a mix of stories and essays, most zines were all fiction.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Like SF fanzines, these media zines spanned the gamut of publishing quality from [[digest-sized]] mimeos to offset printed masterpieces with four-color covers.\n\nMen wrote and edited most previous science fiction fanzines, which typically published articles reporting on trips to conventions, and reviews of books and other fanzines. Camille Bacon-Smith later stated that \"One thing you almost never find in a science fiction fanzine is science fiction. Rather ... fanzines were the social glue that created a community out of a worldwide scattering of readers.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Bacon-Smith|first=Camille|title=Science fiction culture|year=2000|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=978-0-8122-1530-4|url=http://www.upenn.edu/pennpress/book/13333.html}}</ref> Women published most media fanzines, which by contrast also included [[fan fiction]]. By doing so, they \"fill the need of a mostly female audience for fictional narratives that expand the boundary of the official source products offered on the television and movie screen.\"{{r|cbs2000}} In addition to long and short stories, as well as poetry, many media fanzines included illustrated stories, as well as stand alone art, often featuring portraits of the show or film's principal characters. The art could range from simple sketches, to reproductions of large elaborate works painted in oil or acrylic, though most are created in ink.\n\nIn the late 1970s, fiction that included a sexual relationship between two of the male characters of the media source (first [[Kirk/Spock]], then later Starsky/Hutch, Napoleon/Illya, and many others) started to appear in zines.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} This became known as [[Slash fiction|slash]] from the '/' mark used in adzines to differentiate a K&S story (which would have been a Kirk and Spock friendship story) from a K/S story, which would have been one with a romantic or sexual bent between the characters.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Slash zines eventually became their own sub-subgenre; in many [[fandoms]] you rarely saw slash and non-slash stories appear in the same zines.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} By 2000, when web publishing of stories became more popular than zine publishing, thousands of media fanzines had been published;<ref name=\"beyonddreamspress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beyonddreamspress.com/database.htm|title=Database over Kirk/Spock Zines published \u2013 CyberDreams|work=beyonddreamspress.com}}</ref> over 500 of them were k/s zines.<ref name=\"beyonddreamspress.com\"/>\n\nAnother popular franchise for fanzines was the \"[[Star Wars]]\" saga. By the time the film \"[[The Empire Strikes Back]]\" was released in 1980 Star Wars fanzines had surpassed Star Trek zines in sales<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.okbuy.eu/info-fanzine/#.Xoa84ogzaUk|title=Fanzine|last=Hill|first=Jemele|date=October 16, 2017|website=okbuy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref>. An unfortunate episode in fanzine history occurred in 1981 when Star Wars director [[George Lucas]] threatened to sue fanzine publishers who distributed zines featuring the Star Wars characters in sexually explicit stories or art.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n===Comics ===\nComics were mentioned and discussed as early as the late 1930s in the [[science fiction fanzines|fanzines]] of [[science fiction fandom]]. Famously, the first version of [[Superman]] (a bald-headed villain) appeared in the third issue of [[Jerry Siegel]] and [[Joe Shuster]]'s 1933 fanzine ''Science Fiction''. In 1936, [[David Kyle]] published '' The Fantasy World '', possibly the first comics fanzine.<ref>Kyle, David. [http://jophan.org/mimosa/m24/kyle.htm \"Phamous Phantasy Phan\"]. [[Mimosa (magazine)|''Mimosa'']] no. 24, pp. 25\u201328.</ref><ref name=\"powerofcomics\"/> Malcolm Willits and Jim Bradley started ''[[The Comic Collector's News]]'' in October 1947.<ref>{{Google books|QMnxCwAAQBAJ|Everyday Information: The Evolution of Information Seeking in America|page=286|keywords=The+Comic+Collector's+News|text=|plainurl=}}</ref> By 1952, [[Ted White (author)|Ted White]] had mimeographed a four-page pamphlet about [[Superman]], and [[James Taurasi]] issued the short-lived ''Fantasy Comics''. In 1953, [[Bhob Stewart]] published ''The EC Fan Bulletin'',<ref name=\"powerofcomics\">{{Google books|PA175|The Power of Comics: History, Form and Culture|page=175|keywords=EC+Fan+Bulletin|text=|plainurl=}}</ref> which launched [[EC Comics|EC]] fandom of imitative EC fanzines. A few months later, Stewart, White and [[Larry Stark]] produced ''Potrzebie'', planned as a literary journal of critical commentary about EC by Stark. Among the wave of EC fanzines that followed, the best-known was [[Ron Parker (writer)|Ron Parker]]'s ''Hoo-Hah!''. After that came fanzines by the followers of [[Harvey Kurtzman]]'s ''[[Mad (magazine)|Mad]]'', ''[[Trump (magazine)|Trump]]'' and ''[[Humbug (magazine)|Humbug]]''. Publishers of these included future [[underground comics]] stars like [[Jay Lynch]] and [[Robert Crumb]].\n\nIn 1960, [[Richard A. Lupoff|Richard and Pat Lupoff]] launched their [[science fiction fandom|science fiction]] and comics fanzine ''[[Xero (SF fanzine)|Xero]]''. In the second issue, \"The Spawn of M.C. Gaines'\" by Ted White was the first in a series of nostalgic, analytical articles about comics by Lupoff, [[Don Thompson (Comics Buyer's Guide)|Don Thompson]], [[Bill Blackbeard]], [[Jim Harmon]] and others under the heading, ''All in Color for a Dime.'' In 1961, [[Jerry Bails]]' ''[[Alter Ego (fanzine)|Alter Ego]]'', devoted to [[superhero|costumed heroes]],<ref name=\"powerofcomics\"/> f became a focal point for superhero comics fandom and is thus sometimes mistakenly cited as the first comics fanzine.\n\nContacts through these magazines were instrumental in creating the culture of modern [[comics fandom]]: conventions, collecting, etc. Much of this, like comics fandom itself, began as part of standard [[science fiction convention]]s, but comics fans have developed their own traditions. Comics fanzines often include fan artwork based on existing characters as well as discussion of the history of comics. Through the 1960s, and 1970s, comic fanzines followed some general formats, such as the industry news and information magazine (''[[The Comic Reader]]'' was one example), interview, history and review-based fanzines, and the fanzines which basically represented independent comic book-format exercises. While perceived quality varied widely, the energy and enthusiasm involved tended to be communicated clearly to the readership, many of whom were also fanzine contributors. During the 1970s, many fanzines (''[[Squa Tront]]'', as example) also became partly distributed through certain comic book distributors.\n\nAt times, the professional comics publishers have made overtures to fandom via 'prozines', in this case fanzine-like magazines put out by the major publishers. ''[[The Amazing World of DC Comics]]'' and the Marvel magazine ''[[FOOM]]'' began and ceased publication in the 1970s. Priced significantly higher than standard comics of the period (''AWODCC'' was $1.50, ''FOOM'' was 75 cents), each house-organ magazine lasted a brief period of years. Since 2001 in Britain, there have been created a number of fanzines pastiching children's comics of the 1970s, and 1980s (e.g. ''[[Solar Wind (comic)|Solar Wind]]'', ''Pony School'', etc.). These adopt a style of storytelling rather than specific characters from their sources, usually with a knowing or [[irony|ironic]] twist.\n\n===Horror film ===\n[[File:Horrors of the Screen 3 fanzine cover 1964.jpg|thumb|right|Horrors of the Screen No. 3, 1964]]\nAs with comics zines, horror film fanzines grew from related interest within science fiction fan publications.  ''Trumpet,'' edited by [[Tom Reamy]], was a 1960s SF zine that branched into horror film coverage. Alex Soma's ''Horrors of the Screen,''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/unifan2001/HotS.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027140344/http://www.geocities.com/unifan2001/HotS.html|title=Horrors of the Screen|archivedate=27 October 2009|work=archive.org}}</ref> [[Calvin T. Beck]]'s ''Journal of Frankenstein'' (later ''[[Castle of Frankenstein]]'') and Gary Svehla's ''Gore Creatures'' were the first horror fanzines created as more serious alternatives to the popular [[Forrest J Ackerman]] 1958 magazine ''[[Famous Monsters of Filmland]].''  ''Gore Creatures'' began in 1961 and continues today as the prozine (and specialty publisher) ''Midnight Marquee.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midmar.com/|title=MIDNIGHT MARQUEE PRESS \u2013 BOOKS|work=midmar.com}}</ref> ''Garden Ghouls Gazette'' \u2013 a 1960s horror title under the editorship of Dave Keil, then Gary Collins\u2014was eventually headed by the late [[Frederick S. Clarke]] (1949\u20132000) and in 1967 became the respected journal ''[[Cinefantastique]].'' It later became a prozine under journalist-screenwriter [[Mark A. Altman]] and has continued as a webzine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinefantastiqueonline.com/|title=Cinefantastique: The Website with a Sense of Wonder|work=cinefantastiqueonline.com}}</ref>\n\nMark Frank's ''Photon''\u2014notable for the inclusion of an 8x10 [[Photograph|photo]] in each issue\u2014was another 1960s zine that lasted into the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.geocities.com/unifan2001/Photon.html | title = Photon | accessdate = 8 August 2012 | last = Frank | first = Mark | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091027140404/http://www.geocities.com/unifan2001/Photon.html | archivedate = 27 October 2009}}</ref> Richard Klemensen's ''[[Little Shoppe of Horrors]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littleshoppeofhorrors.com/|title=Little Shoppe of Horrors|work=littleshoppeofhorrors.com}}</ref> having a particular focus on \"[[Hammer Film Productions|Hammer Horrors]],\" began in 1972 and is still publishing as of 2019.\n\nThe [[Baltimore]]-based ''Black Oracle'' (1969\u20131978) from writer-turned-[[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]] repertory member [[George Stover]] was a diminutive zine that evolved into the larger-format ''Cinemacabre.''  Stover's ''Black Oracle'' partner Bill George published his own short-lived zine ''The Late Show'' (1974\u20131976; with co-editor Martin Falck), and later became editor of the ''Cinefantastique'' prozine spinoff ''[[Femme Fatales (magazine)|Femme Fatales]].'' In the mid-1970s, [[North Carolina]] teenager [[Sam Irvin]] published the horror/science-fiction fanzine ''Bizarre'' which included his original interviews with UK actors and filmmakers; Irvin would later become a producer-director in his own right.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinema.usc.edu/directories/profile.cfm?id=33692&first=&last=&title=&did=1&referer=%2Fproduction%2Ffaculty.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=31|title=School of Cinematic Arts Directory Profile \u2013 USC School of Cinematic Arts|work=usc.edu}}</ref> ''Japanese Fantasy Film Journal'' (JFFJ) (1968\u20131983) from the late Greg Shoemaker (1947\u20132019) covered [[Toho]]'s ''[[Godzilla]]'' and his Asian brethren when no other publications much cared. In 1993, ''[[G-FAN]]'' picked up where JFFJ left off, and reached its 100th regularly published issue in Fall 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g-fan.com/html/gfan_index/index_100.php|title=GFAN Magazine Index|work=g-fan.com}}</ref> ''FXRH'' ([[Special effects]] by [[Ray Harryhausen]]) (1971\u20131976) was a specialized zine co-created by future [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] [[Special effect|FX]] artist [[Ernest D. Farino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0267495/bio|title=Ernest Farino|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Rock and roll ===\nBy the mid-1960s, several fans active in science fiction and comics fandom recognized a shared interest in rock music, and the rock fanzine was born. [[Paul Williams (Crawdaddy! creator)|Paul Williams]] and [[Greg Shaw]] were two such SF-fans turned rock zine editors. Williams' ''[[Crawdaddy!]]'' (1966) and Shaw's two California-based zines, ''Mojo Navigator'' (full title, \"''Mojo-Navigator Rock and Roll News''\") (1966) and ''[[Who Put the Bomp]]'', (1970), are among the most important early rock fanzines.\n\n''[[Crawdaddy!]]'' (1966) quickly moved from its fanzine roots to become one of the first rock music \"prozines,\" with paid advertisers and newsstand distribution. ''Bomp'' remained a fanzine, featuring many writers who would later become prominent music journalists, including [[Lester Bangs]], [[Greil Marcus]], Ken Barnes, [[Ed Ward (writer)|Ed Ward]], [[Dave Marsh]], [[Mike Saunders]] and [[Richard Meltzer|R. Meltzer]].  ''Bomp'' featured cover art by Jay Kinney and Bill Rotsler, both veterans of SF and Comics fandom. ''Bomp'' was not alone; an August 1970 issue of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' included an article about the explosion of rock fanzines. Other rock fanzines of this period include ''[[denim delinquent]]'' 1971, edited by Jymn Parrett, ''Flash,'' 1972, edited by Mark Shipper, ''Eurock Magazine'' (1973\u20131993) edited by Archie Patterson and ''Bam Balam,'' written and published by Brian Hogg in East Lothian, Scotland, beginning in 1974, and in the mid-1970s, ''[[Back Door Man (fanzine)|Back Door Man]]''.\n\nIn the post-punk era several well-written fanzines emerged that cast an almost academic look at earlier, neglected musical forms, including Mike Stax' ''[[Ugly Things]]'', Billy Miller and [[Miriam Linna]]'s ''Kicks'', Jake Austen's ''[[Roctober (fanzine)|Roctober]]'', Kim Cooper's ''[[Scram (fanzine)|Scram]]'', P. Edwin Letcher's ''[[Garage & Beat]]'', and the UK's [[Shindig! (magazine)|Shindig!]] and Italy's ''[[Misty Lane]]''.\n\nIn the 1980s, with the rise of stadium superstars, many home-grown rock fanzines emerged. At the peak of [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s megastardom following the ''[[Born in the U.S.A.]]'' album and [[Born in the U.S.A. Tour]] in the mid-1980s, there were no less than five Springsteen fanzines circulating at the same time in the UK alone, and many others elsewhere. Gary Desmond's ''Candy's Room'', coming from Liverpool, was the first in 1980, quickly followed by Dan French's ''Point Blank'', Dave Percival's ''The Fever'', Jeff Matthews' ''Rendezvous'', and Paul Limbrick's ''Jackson Cage''. In the US, ''[[Backstreets Magazine]]'' started in Seattle in 1980 and still continues today as a glossy publication, now in communication with Springsteen's management and official website. In the late 1990s, notorious fanzines and e-zines flourished about electronic and [[post-rock]] music. ''Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e'' fanzine was one of those that documented post-rock genre and experimental music.\n\n===Punk ===\n{{Main|Punk zine}}\n{{Category see also|Punk zines}}\n[[File:1970s fanzines (21224199545).jpg|thumb|British punk fanzines from the 1970s.]]\n\n====UK ====\n\nThe [[punk subculture]] in the United Kingdom spearheaded a surge of interest in fanzines as a countercultural alternative to established print media. The first and still best known UK 'punk zine' was ''[[Sniffin' Glue]]'', produced by [[Deptford, London|Deptford]] punk fan [[Mark Perry (musician)|Mark Perry]].  ''Sniffin' Glue'' ran for 12 photocopied issues; the first issue was produced by Perry immediately following (and in response to) the London debut of [[The Ramones]] on 4 July 1976. Other UK fanzines included ''[[Blam! (fanzine)|Blam!]]'', ''[[Bombsite (fanzine)|Bombsite]]'', Wool City Rocker, ''Burnt Offering'', ''[[Chainsaw (punk zine)|Chainsaw]]'', ''[[New Crimes]]'', ''[[Vague (fanzine)|Vague]]'', ''[[Jamming (fanzine)|Jamming]]'', [[Artcore Fanzine]], ''[[Love and Molotov Cocktails]]'', ''[[To Hell With Poverty]]'', ''[[New Youth (fanzine)|New Youth]]'', ''[[Peroxide (punk zine)|Peroxide]]'', ''[[ENZK]]'', ''[[Juniper beri-beri]]'', ''[[No Cure]]'',''[[Communication Blur]]'', ''[[Rox (fanzine)|Rox]]'', ''[[Grim Humour]]'', ''[[Spuno]]''<ref name=\"Spuno info online\">{{cite web|url=http://si-site-nogsy.blogspot.com/2011/07/spuno-3-1980.html|title=essential ephemera|author=Si|work=si-site-nogsy.blogspot.com}}</ref>\n, ''[[Cool Notes]]'' and ''[[Fumes (magazine)|Fumes]]''. Of these, Tony Fletcher's ''Jamming'' was the most far reaching, becoming a nationally distributed mainstream magazine for several years before its demise.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n\n====US ====\nIn the US, ''[[Flipside (fanzine)|Flipside]]'' and ''[[Slash (fanzine)|Slash]]'' were important punk zines for the Los Angeles scene, both debuting in 1977. In 1977 in Australia, Bruce Milne and [[Clinton Walker]] fused their respective punk zines ''Plastered Press'' and ''Suicide Alley'' to launch ''Pulp''; Milne later went on to invent the cassette zine with ''Fast Forward'', in 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://messandnoise.com/features/4331535|title=Fast Forward: A Pre-Internet Story|date=18 September 2011|website=messandnoise.com|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clintonwalker.com.au/fanzines-1970s.html|title=Fanzines (1970s)|website=Clinton Walker|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> Starting earlier, in 1976, ''[[Punk (magazine)|Punk]]'' was published in New York and played a major part in popularizing [[Punk rock#Etymology|punk rock]] (a term coined a few years earlier in ''[[Creem]]'') as the term for the music and the bands being written about.\n\nAmong later titles, ''[[Maximum RocknRoll]]'' is a major punk zine, with over 300 issues published. As a result, in part, of the popular and commercial resurgence of punk in the late 1980s, and after, with the growing popularity of such bands as [[Sonic Youth]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Fugazi (band)|Fugazi]], [[Bikini Kill]], [[Green Day]] and [[The Offspring]], a number of other punk zines have appeared, such as ''[[Punk Planet]]'', ''[[Razorcake]]'', ''[[Tail Spins]]'', ''[[Sobriquet (magazine)|Sobriquet]]'', ''[[Profane Existence]]'' and ''[[Slug and Lettuce (fanzine)|Slug and Lettuce]]''. The early American punkzine ''[[RE/Search|Search and Destroy]]'' eventually became the influential fringe-cultural magazine ''[[Re/Search]]''.\n\nSome punk fanzines from the 80s, like No Class fanzine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noclass.co.uk|title=No Class Fanzine, No Class Records, No Class Now, No Class Gigs|work=noclass.co.uk}}</ref> and Ugly American<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uglyamericanzine.com|title=The Official Ugly American Zine Archives, 1988\u20131999.|work=uglyamericanzine.com}}</ref> are experiencing a second life by placing all past content online for free and adding new content. For the past 6 years, Suburban Rebels in Northern California has been leading the Punk zine way.\n\nMany of the punk zines were printed in small quantities and promoted the local scene. They were often cheaply photocopied and many never survived beyond a few issues. Their greatest contribution was in promoting punk music, clothing and lifestyle in their local communities. Punk bands and independent labels often sent records to the zines for review and many of the people who started the zines became critical connections for punk bands on tour.\n\n====After the year 2000====\n\nIn the UK ''[[Fracture (fanzine)|Fracture]]'' and ''[[Reason To Believe (fanzine)|Reason To Believe]]'' were significant fanzines in the early 2000s, but both ended in late 2003. ''[[Rancid News]]'' filled the gap left by these two zines for a short while. On its tenth issue ''Rancid News'' changed its name to ''[[Last Hours]]'' with 7 issues published under this title before going on hiatus. ''Last Hours'' still operates as a [[webzine]] though with more focus on the anti-authoritarian movement than its original title. ''[[Artcore Fanzine]]'' (established in 1986) continues to this day, recently publishing a number of 30-year anniversary issues. There are many smaller fanzines in existence throughout the UK that focus on punk.\n\n=====Mark Wilkins and Mystic records=====\n\nMark Wilkins, the promotion director for 1982 onwards US punk/thrash label [[Mystic Records]], had over 450 US fanzines and 150 foreign fanzines he promoted to regularly. He and Mystic Records owner Doug Moody edited ''The Mystic News Newsletter'' which was published quarterly and went into every promo package to fanzines. Wilkins also published the highly successful Los Angeles punk humor zine ''Wild Times'' and when he ran out of funding for the zine syndicated some of the humorous material to over 100 US fanzines under the name of Mystic Mark.\n\n====Italy====\nIn [[Perugia]], Italy, ''Mazquerade'' ran from 1979 to 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perugiamusica.com/RIVISTE/MAZQUERADE/mazquerade.html|title=Perugiamusica.com|website=perugiamusica.com|accessdate=14 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303123957/http://www.perugiamusica.com/RIVISTE/MAZQUERADE/mazquerade.html|archive-date=3 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Basilicata]], Italy, ''Raw Art Fanzine'' ran from 1995 to 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truemetal.it/news/raw-art-fanzine-restauro-digitale-e-disponibilita-dei-numeri-degli-anni-90-89535|title=Raw Art Fanzine: restauro digitale e disponibilit\u00e0 dei numeri degli anni '90|website=truemetal.it|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Milano]], Italy, ''Gorezilla'' ran from 1988 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moviemags.com/main_g.php?title=GOREZILLA&year=%}}</ref>\n\n===Mod===\nIn the United Kingdom, the 1979 [[Mod revival]], which was inspired by the 1960s [[Mod subculture]], brought with it a burst of fresh creativity from fanzines, and for the next decade, the youth [[subculture]] inspired the production of dozens of independent publications. The most successful of the first wave was ''Maximum Speed'', which successfully captured the frenetic world of a [[Mod (subculture)|mod]] revival scene that was propelling bands like [[Secret Affair]], [[Purple Hearts (British band)|Purple Hearts]] and [[The Chords]] into the UK charts.\n\nAfter the genre had started to go out of fashion with mainstream audiences in 1981, the mod revival scene went underground and successfully reinvented itself through a series of clubs, bands and fanzines that breathed fresh life into the genre, culminating in another burst of creative acceptance in 1985. This success was largely driven by the network of underground fanzines, the most important and far reaching of which were ''Extraordinary Sensations'', produced by future radio DJ [[Eddie Piller]], and ''Shadows & Reflections'', published by future national magazine editor [[Chris Hunt]]. The latter in particular pushed back the boundaries of fanzine production, producing glossy, professionally written and printed publications at a time (1983\u201386) when most fanzines were produced via photocopier and letraset.\n\n===Local music===\nIn the UK, there were also fanzines that covered the local music scene in a particular town or city. Mainly prevalent in the 1970s, and 1980s, all music styles were covered, whether the bands were playing rock, punk, metal, futurist, ska or dance. Featured were local gig reviews and articles that were below the radar of the mainstream music press. They were produced using the technology of the time, i.e. typewriter and [[Letraset]]. Examples include ''[[Bombsite Fanzine]]'' (Liverpool 1977), Wool City Rocker (Bradford 1979 \u2013 1982), ''[[City Fun]]'' (Manchester), 1984, Spuno (Bath 1980)<ref name=\"Spuno info online\"/> ''[[No Cure]]'' (Berkshire) and ''[[Town Hall Steps (fanzine)|Town Hall Steps]]'' (Bolton) and more recently [[''mono'' (fanzine)]], (Bradford) with many more across the country, such as Premonition Tapes Tapezine on cassette (Sheffield 1987) and Crime Pays (Liverpool 1988).\n\n===Role-playing-game fanzines===\nAnother sizable group of fanzines arose in [[role-playing game]] (RPG) fandom, where fanzines allowed people to publish their ideas and views on specific games and their [[role-playing campaigns]]. In 1975, was released the apazine [[Alarums and Excursions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arielarchives.com/Brett/magazines/alarumsandexcursions.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061024220743/http://www.arielarchives.com/Brett/magazines/alarumsandexcursions.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 October 2006|title=RPG Magzine and zine Index- Alarms & Excursions Page|date=24 October 2006|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nRole-playing fanzines allowed people to communicate in the 1970s, and 1980s with complete editorial control in the hands of the players, as opposed to the game publishers. These early RPG fanzines were generally typed, sold mostly in an A5 format (in the UK) and were usually illustrated with abysmal or indifferent artwork.\n\nA fanzine community developed and was based on sale to a reading public and exchanges by editor/publishers. Many of the pioneers of RPG zinedom got their start in, or remain part of, [[science fiction fandom]]. This is also true of the small but still active [[board game]] fandom scene, the most prolific subset of which is centered around [[play-by-mail game|play-by-mail]] [[Diplomacy game|Diplomacy]].\n\nThe UK fanzine [[Aslan (fanzine)|Aslan]] (1988\u20131991)<ref>{{Google books|ix9WDwAAQBAJ|Role-Playing Game Studies: Transmedia Foundations|keywords=aslan+fanzine|text=|plainurl=}}</ref> was responsible for popularization of [[freeform role-playing game]]s in the UK.<ref name=nnbtv>{{cite web |url=http://nnbtv.org.uk/Games/History.html|title=Me and Freeforms|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Video gaming ===\nVideo game fanzines first emerged during the [[Second generation of video game consoles|second generation period]] when newsletters for computer user groups and stores were not uncommon, though not always well-known. Subscriber-based newsletters included the well-known ''[[8: 16 (UK, all things Atari, 1st issue Nov 1987)]]'',''[[The Video Game Update]]'' and later ''[[Computer Entertainer]]''. The publication, ''[[Joystick Jolter]]'' was the first actual fanzine.\n\nLater, as desktop publishing tools became more accessible, there was an increase in fanzine production. Fanzines generally emphasized either classic gaming (e.g. ''[[2600 Connection]]'' and ''[[Classic Systems & Games Monthly]]''), or current gaming (e.g. ''[[APE (fanzine)|APE]]'' and ''[[The Subversive Sprite]]''). However some fanzines covered both topics (e.g. ''[[Digital Press]]'' and ''[[Joystick & Screen]]''). The number of zines grew bigger when video game journalists including [[Arnie Katz]] and [[Chris Bieniek]] used their columns to publish reviews of fanzines that they had been sent at magazines like ''[[Video Games & Computer Entertainment]]'', ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]'', and ''[[Tips & Tricks]]''. These reviews had the effect of introducing fan editors to each other and creating a fanzine scene.\n\nThe video game fanzine diminished greatly in popularity with the rise of the web, though some zines\u2014particularly the classic gaming ones\u2014continued past the mid-90s (e.g. ''[[Classic Gamer Magazine]]'' and ''[[Video Game Collector]]''). The rise of \"on demand\" publishing has led to a new outlet for print zines, like ''[[Jumpbutton]]'' and ''[[Scroll]]''.\n\nThe video game fanzine era was biggest in the US and Canada,{{citation needed|date=November 2012}} but there were/are zines from other countries too. Video game fanzines in UK have included ''[[Retrogamer]]'', ''[[Pixel Nation]]'', ''[[Capcom Fanzine]]'', ''[[Mercury (fanzine)|Mercury]]'', and ''[[Super Famicom Mini Mag]]'' among others.<ref>Bielby, Matt, ed. \"Super Express \u2013 Fanhunter: Super Play's Fanzine Round-Up.\" ''[[Super Play]]''. Issue 9, Pg.14. July 1993. {{ISSN|0966-6192}}.</ref> In France fanzines like ''[[Revival (fanzine)|Revival]]'' we circulated, and Japan has seen the production of lavish [[doujin]] works.\n\nMore recently, there has been a mini-resurgence in video game fanzines, with the launch of HyperPlay RPG in 2015 and Switch Player in 2017. Based in part on the above-mentioned Super Play with a focus on role-playing games and \"any-bit\" Nintendo,<ref>hyperplayrpg.com</ref> popular fanzine HyperPlay RPG has been consistently well-reviewed by the mainstream video game media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/09/hyperplay_rpg_is_a_glorious_throwback_to_the_pre-internet_days_of_homemade_fanzines|title=HyperPlay RPG Is A Glorious Throwback to the Pre-Internet Days Of Homemade Fanzines|first=Nintendo|last=Life|date=27 September 2015|website=nintendolife.com|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Wargaming===\nSeveral fanzines exist within the hobby of [[wargaming]]. Among them is ''[[CHARGE! (magazine)|Charge!]]'', a leading international fanzine exclusively for [[miniature wargaming]] enthusiasts for the [[American Civil War]] period. Other fanzines support [[Warhammer Fantasy Battle|Warhammer]] and other popular rules sets.\n\n===Sport===\n{{Category see also|Football fanzines}}\nThe first association football fanzine is regarded as being [[Foul (fanzine)|Foul]], a publication that ran between 1972 and 1976.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fact Sheet 7: Fan 'Power' and Democracy in Football |url=http://www.le.ac.uk/so/css/resources/factsheets/fs7.html |work=Department of Sociology: Sports Resources |publisher=University of Leicester |access-date=25 August 2010 |author=Gavin Barber (updated by John Williams) |year=2002 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821184842/http://www.le.ac.uk/so/css/resources/factsheets/fs7.html |archive-date=21 August 2010 |df= }}</ref> In the UK, most [[Premier League]] or [[The Football League|Football League]] [[association football|football]] clubs have one or more fanzines which supplement, oppose and complement the club's official magazine or matchday programme. A reasonably priced 'zine has a guaranteed audience, as is the culture of passion in being a football fan.\n\nThe longest running fanzine is ''[[The City Gent (fanzine)|The City Gent]]'', produced by supporters of [[Bradford City FC]], which first went on sale at Valley Parade in November 1984 and is now in its 26th season. Following close on its heels was Nike, Inc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a-love-supreme.com|title=A Love Supreme \u2013 The Independent Sunderland Football Club Fanzine|author=Azure Graphic & Web Design|work=a-love-supreme.com}}</ref> which was first released in 1989. At the time it was not the first of its kind with ''Terrace Talk'' (York City), which was first published in November 1981 and ''Wanderers Worldwide'' (Bolton Wanderers) having already been established but since disappeared. In 1985 the emergent ''[[When Saturday Comes]]'' (a fanzine without a specific club focus that was subsequently launched as a mainstream magazine) promoted a 'fanzine movement' that gave birth to many more club titles during the late 1980s which was something of a glory period for fanzines.\n\nWith the widespread availability of the Internet, much of the energy that was put into football fanzines subsequently went into the development of supporters' websites. Examples of other UK football fanzines include ''[[A Love Supreme (fanzine)|A Love Supreme]]'' ([[Sunderland AFC|Sunderland]]), ''[[TOOFIF]]'' ([[Fulham FC|Fulham]]), ''[[The Square Ball]]'' ([[Leeds United]]), ''4,000 Holes'' ([[Blackburn Rovers]]) and ''[[War of the Monster Trucks]]'' (a [[Sheffield Wednesday]] fanzine named after a local TV station elected not to show the final scenes of an unlikely cup victory). The Queen's Park Rangers fanzine 'A Kick up the Rs' was first published in August 1987 and is still issuing an average of 10 issues per season.\n\nFanzines are not exclusive to the top tiers of football however, with [[Northern Counties East League]] side [[Scarborough Athletic FC]] having a fanzine titled ''[[Abandon Chip!]]'', a pun based on both the perilous situation of predecessor club [[Scarborough FC]] and that club's sponsors, [[McCain Foods Limited|McCain]].\n\nAnd also away from the world of Football there were a number of established fanzines, for example [[Rugby league]] has such notable publications as ''[[Who The Hell Was St. George Anyway?]]'' Rugby League fanzine, by supporters of Doncaster RLFC and ''Scarlet Turkey'' of [[Salford Red Devils|Salford City Reds]].However, due to pressure from the Internet etc. these publications no longer exist in printed form. The title of World's longest running Rugby League fanzine now belongs to ''[[The Aye of the Tigers]]'', by Castleford Tigers supporters. The fanzine movement has even spread to the United States, where ice hockey fans have produced several popular fanzines. In Chicago two examples include the formerly published ''Blue Line Magazine'' and currently ''The Committed Indian'', both produced by [[Chicago Blackhawks]] fans.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chitowndailynews.org/2009/05/27/The-Committed-Indian-Snark-and-in-depth-report-informs-and-entertains-27581.html | title=The Committed Indian; Snark and in-depth report informs and entertains | work=[[Chi-Town Daily News]] | date=27 May 2009 | access-date=18 October 2018 | author=Grant, Lou | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130703231147/http://www.chitowndailynews.org/2009/05/27/The-Committed-Indian-Snark-and-in-depth-report-informs-and-entertains-27581.html | archive-date=3 July 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> In [[St. Louis]] there are ''Game Night Revue'' and ''St Louis Game Time'' for the [[St. Louis Blues]].\n\nThere are also a number of fanzines to be found in Ireland of which [[Shelbourne F.C.|Shelbourne]]'s ''Red Inc.'' is the longest running.\n\nIn the United States, sports fanzines are relatively rare. In [[Boston]] they are a bit more common. There are two fanzines sold outside Fenway Park including ''Yawkey Way Report'', which is run by a former Marine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://yawkeywayreport.com/meet-the-staff/ceo-sly-egidio/|title=CEO Sly Egidio \u2013 Yawkey Way Report|newspaper=Yawkey Way Report|access-date=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/09/10/fenway-scene-war-among-rival-hawkers-game-programs/eTsR16JIvyshTp3S7tLhEJ/story.html|title=Fenway program hawkers' rivalry fuels competition|newspaper=Boston Globe|access-date=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Recent developments==\nWith the increasing availability of the Internet in the late 20th and the early 21st century, the traditional paper zine has begun to give way to the [[webzine]] (or \"e-zine\") that is easier to produce and uses the potential of the Internet to reach an ever-larger, possibly global, audience. Nonetheless, printed fanzines are still produced, either out of preference for the format or to reach people who do not have convenient Web access. Online versions of approximately 200 [[science fiction fanzine]]s will be found at Bill Burns'<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eFanzines.com|title=eFanzines.com|website=efanzines.com|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> eFanzines web site, along with links to other [[science fiction fanzine|SF fanzine]] sites. In addition zine festivals are held each year in American cities like Los Angeles,<ref>[http://boingboing.net/2012/02/10/la-zine-fest-feb-19.html \"LA Zine Fest,\" ''Boing Boing'']</ref> Chicago,<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-03-23/features/ct-prj-0324-zines-20130323_1_zine-scene-zine-collection-science-fiction \"The Zine Scene,\" ''Chicago Tribune]''</ref> and Brooklyn,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2012/apr/16/micropolis-brooklyn-zine-fest|title=Micropolis: The Brooklyn Zine Fest|publisher=WNYC}}</ref> as well as internationally in cities including Melbourne, Australia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stickyinstitute.com/fotp2016|title=Sticky Institute|website=stickyinstitute.com|access-date=18 April 2016}}</ref> and Glasgow, UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glasgowzinefest.com/|title=http://glasgowzinefest.com/|website=glasgowzinefest.com|access-date=18 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n* [[Alt.zines]]\n* [[Amateur press association]]\n* [[British small press comics]]\n* [[Desktop publishing]]\n* [[D\u014djinshi]]\n* [[Fandom]]\n* [[Hugo Award for Best Fanzine]]\n* [[Hugo Award for Best Semiprozine]]\n{{Col-2}}\n* Literature\n* [[Minicomic Co-ops]] (The United Fanzine Organization)\n* [[Minicomics]]\n* Printing\n* Publishing\n* [[Revolutionart]]\n* [[Science fiction fandom]]\n* [[Weblog]]\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Schelly, Bill. ''The Golden Age of Comic Fandom''. Introduction by Roy Thomas. Seattle, WA: Hamster Press, 1995.\n*Lupoff, Dick [Richard A.] and Don Thompson, eds. ''All in Color for a Dime''. New Rochelle, N.Y.: Arlington House, 1970.\n\n==External links==\n{{external links|date=May 2019}}\n{{Commons category|Fanzines}}\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/02/fanzine-simon-reynolds-blog How the fanzine refused to die]\n*[http://www.jessesword.com/sf/view/186 Citations for \"fanzine\" collected by the Oxford English Dictionary]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050901095834/http://rehupa.com/apa_hist.htm Origins of the amateur press associations]\n*[http://fanac.org/fanzines/ Historic science fiction fanzines at Fanac.org]\n*[http://efanzines.com/ Current and archived science fiction fanzines at eFanzines.com]\n*[http://www.asimovs.com/_issue_0501/thoughtexperiments.shtml An article by critic Roger Ebert describing his involvement with science fiction fanzines in the 1950s.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050206113212/http://www.scrammagazine.com/shaw.html An interview with Bomp! publisher Greg Shaw discussing his experience as a teenage SF fanzine and rock zine publisher, and the evolution of zines through the 1990s.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060220194048/http://www.skipwilliamson.com/UndergroundComix.html The Underground Comix movement began as a network of fanzines.]\n*[http://comicattack.net/category/cafeaturedcolumns/inkstains/ Ink Stains (column on comics fanzines of the 60s, 70s, and 80s)]\n*[http://www.lib.uiowa.edu/spec-coll/MSC/ToMsC800/MsC791/MsC791_horvatfanzines.htm M. Horvat Fanzine Collection at the U. of Iowa]\n*[http://fanlore.org/wiki/Category:Zines Fanlore includes an extensive resource of media fanzines including table of contents, awards and covers]\n*[http://fanzinoteca.it/ Zinelibrary Italy]\n*[http://www.fanzindb.org/ Fanzine Database Turkey]\n*[http://www.geocities.ws/mneko13/whoswho.htm On-File Who's Who of videogame fandom]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150430212609/http://www.1up.com/features/gaming-journalism-unplugged Gaming Journalism: Unplugged]\n*[https://www.wired.com/gamelife/2012/12/japan-gaming-doujin/ Japan's Gaming Fanzines Delve Into the Most Obsessive Topics]\n*[http://lazinefest.com/ LA Zine Fest]\n*[http://chicagozinefest.org/ Chicago Zine Fest]\n*[http://www.brooklynzinefest.com Brooklyn Zine Fest]\n*[http://fanziny.ic.cz Some Czechoslovak science fiction fanzines in digital form.]\n*[https://issuu.com/rawartfanzine Italian Raw Art Fanzine 1995\u20132000 digitally restored for free online.]\n*[http://dezskinn.com/fanzines/ Fanzines] [[Dez Skinn]]'s website\n* [http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/fanzine Fanzine] on [[The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction]]\n{{Independent production}}\n{{fandom}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Fanzines|*]]\n[[Category:Zines]]\n[[Category:Fanspeak]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1940s]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Short description|Magazine published by fans}}\nA '''fanzine''' ([[blend word|blend]] of ''[[fan (person)|fan]]'' and ''magazine'' or ''-[[zine]]'') is a non-professional and non-official publication produced by [[fan (person)|enthusiasts]] of a particular cultural [[phenomenon]] (such as a literary or musical genre) for the pleasure of others who share their interest. The term was coined in an October 1940 [[science fiction fanzine]] by [[Russ Chauvenet]] and first popularized within [[science fiction fandom]], and from there it was adopted by other communities.\n\nTypically, publishers, editors, writers and other contributors of [[Article (publishing)|articles]] or [[illustration]]s to fanzines are not paid. Fanzines are traditionally circulated free of charge, or for a nominal cost to defray postage or production expenses. Copies are often offered in exchange for similar publications, or for contributions of art, articles, or letters of comment (LoCs), which are then published.\n\nSome fanzines are typed and photocopied by amateurs using standard home office equipment. A few fanzines have developed into professional publications (sometimes known as \"prozines\"), and many professional writers were first published in fanzines; some continue to contribute to them after establishing a professional reputation. The term fanzine is sometimes confused with \"[[fan magazine]]\", but the latter term most often refers to commercially produced publications ''for'' (rather than ''by'') fans.\n\n==Origin==\nThe origins of amateur [[fanac]] \"fan\" publications are obscure, but can be traced at least back to 19th century literary groups in the United States which formed [[amateur press association]]s to publish collections of amateur fiction, poetry and commentary, such as [[H.P. Lovecraft]]'s ''United Amateur''.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Myawoc_PbF4C&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=hp+lovecraft+united+amateur+amateur+press+association#v=onepage&q=hp%20lovecraft%20united%20amateur%20amateur%20press%20association&f=false |title=An H.P. Lovecraft Encyclopedia |last=Schultz |first=David E. |website=books.google.es |publisher=Hippocampus Press |year=2001 |access-date=13 October 2019|isbn=9780313315787 }}</ref>\n\nAs professional printing technology progressed, so did the technology of fanzines. Early fanzines were hand-drafted or typed on a manual typewriter and printed using primitive reproduction techniques (e.g., the [[spirit duplicator]] or even the [[hectograph]]). Only a very small number of copies could be made at a time, so circulation was extremely limited. The use of [[mimeograph machine]]s enabled greater press runs, and the photocopier increased the speed and ease of publishing once more. Today, thanks to the advent of [[desktop publishing]] and [[self-publishing|self-publication]], there is often little difference between the appearance of a fanzine and a professional magazine.\n\n==Genres==\n\n===Science fiction===\n{{Main|Science fiction fanzines}}\n{{Category see also|Science fiction fanzines}}\n\nWhen [[Hugo Gernsback]] published the first [[science fiction magazine]], ''[[Amazing Stories]]'' in 1926, he allowed for a large letter column which printed reader's addresses. By 1927 readers, often young adults, would write to each other, bypassing the magazine.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Science fiction fanzines had their beginnings in Serious & Constructive (later shortened to [[sercon]]) correspondence.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Fans finding themselves writing the same letter to several correspondents sought to save themselves a lot of typing by duplicating their letters.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nEarly efforts included simple [[carbon copy|carbon copies]] but that proved insufficient.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} The first science fiction fanzine, ''[[The Comet]]'', was published in 1930 by the [[Science Correspondence Club]] in Chicago and edited by [[Raymond A. Palmer]] and [[Walter Dennis]].<ref name=\"moskowitz\">{{cite book | first1 = Sam | last1 = Moskowitz | authorlink1 = Sam Moskowitz |first2=Joe |last2= Sanders|authorlink2=Joe Sanders | title = The Origins of Science Fiction Fandom: A Reconstruction | booktitle = Science Fiction Fandom | pages = 17\u201336 | publisher = Greenwood Press | year = 1994 | location = Westport, CT }}</ref> The term \"fanzine\" was coined by [[Russ Chauvenet]] in the October 1940 edition of his fanzine ''Detours''. \"Fanzines\" were distinguished from \"prozines,\" (a term Chauvenet also invented): that is, all professional magazines. Prior to that, the fan publications were known as \"fanmags\" or \"letterzines\".{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\nScience fiction fanzines used a variety of printing methods. Typewriters, school dittos, church mimeos and (if they could afford it) multi-color letterpress or other mid-to-high level printing. Some fans wanted their news spread, others reveled in the artistry and beauty of fine printing.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} The [[hectograph]], introduced around 1876, was so named because it could produce (in theory) up to a hundred copies. Hecto used an [[aniline]] dye, transferred to a tray of gelatin, and paper would be placed on the gel, one sheet at a time, for transfer. Messy and smelly, the process could create vibrant colors for the few copies produced, the easiest aniline dye to make being purple (technically [[indigo]]). The next small but significant technological step after hecto is the [[spirit duplicator]], essentially the hectography process using a drum instead of the gelatin. Introduced by [[Ditto Corporation]] in 1923, these machines were known for the next six decades as Ditto Machines and used by fans because they were cheap to use and could (with a little effort) print in color.\n\nThe [[mimeograph]] machine, which forced ink through a wax paper stencil cut by the keys of a typewriter, was the standard for many decades. A second-hand mimeo could print hundreds of copies and (with more than a little effort) print in color. The [[electronic stencil cutter]] (shortened to \"electrostencil\" by most) could add photographs and illustrations to a mimeo stencil. A mimeo'd zine could look terrible or look beautiful, depending more on the skill of the mimeo operator than the quality of the equipment. Only a few fans could afford more professional printers, or the time it took them to print, until photocopying became cheap and ubiquitous in the 1970s. With the advent of computer printers and desktop publishing in the 1980s, fanzines began to look far more professional. The rise of the internet made correspondence cheaper and ''much'' faster, and the [[World Wide Web]] has made publishing a fanzine as simple as coding a web page.\n\nThe printing technology affected the style of writing.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} For example, there were alphanumeric contractions which are actually precursors to \"[[leet]]-speak\".{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}  (A well-known example is the \"initials\" used by [[Forrest J. Ackerman]] in his fanzines from the 30s, and 40s, namely \"4sj\".{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}  Fans around the world knew Ackerman by three letters \"4sj\" or even two: \"4e\" for \"Forry.\")  [[Fanspeak]] is rich with abbreviations and concatenations. Where teenagers labored to save typing on ditto masters, they now save keystrokes when text messaging. Ackerman invented nonstoparagraphing as a space-saving measure.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cohen|first1=Philip|title=Language of Science Fiction Fandom|journal=Word Ways|year=1975|volume=8|issue=1|pages=5\u20136}}</ref> When the typist comes to the end of a paragraph, they simply moved the platen down one line.\n\nNever commercial enterprises, most [[science fiction fanzine]]s were (and many still are) available for \"the usual,\" meaning that a sample issue will be mailed on request; to receive further issues, a reader sends a \"letter of comment\" (LoC) about the fanzine to the editor.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} The LoC might be published in the next issue; some fanzines consisted almost exclusively of letter columns, where discussions were conducted in much the same way as they are in internet [[newsgroup]]s and [[mailing list]]s today, though at a relatively glacial pace. Often fanzine editors (\"faneds\") would simply swap issues with each other, not worrying too much about matching trade for trade, somewhat like being on one another's [[LiveJournal#The word .22friend.22|friends list]]. Without being closely connected with the rest of fandom, a budding faned could read fanzine reviews in prozines, and fanzines reviewed other fanzines. Recent technology has changed the speed of communication between fans and the technology available, but the basic concepts developed by science fiction fanzines in the 1930s can be seen online today. Blogs \u2013 with their threaded comments, personalized illustrations, shorthand in-jokes, wide variety in quality and wider variety of content\u2014follow the structure developed in science fiction fanzines, without (usually) realizing the antecedent.\n\nSince 1937, science fiction fans have formed [[amateur press association]]s (APAs); the members contribute to a collective assemblage or bundle that contains contributions from all of them, called [[apazine]]s and often containing [[mailing comment]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Southard|first1=Bruce|title=The Language of Science-Fiction Fan Magazines|journal=American Speech|date=Spring 1982|volume=57|issue=1|page=23|doi=10.2307/455177|jstor=i219220}}</ref> Some APAs are still active, and some are published as virtual \"e-zines,\" distributed on the Internet.<ref name=\"That's Not Online\">{{cite web|title=Amateur Press Associations (APAs) (UPDATED)|url=http://thatsnotonline.tumblr.com/post/4313215829/amateur-press-associations-apas-updated|website=That's Not Online|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref> Specific [[Hugo Award]]s are given for [[Hugo Award for Best Fanzine|fanzines]], [[Hugo Award for Best Fan Writer|fan writing]] and [[Hugo Award for Best Fan Artist|fanart]].\n\n==== Media  ====\nMedia fanzines were originally merely a subgenre of SF fanzines, written by science fiction fans already familiar with apazines. The first media fanzine was a ''[[Star Trek]]'' fan publication called ''[[Spockanalia]]'', published in September 1967<ref name=\"verba2003\">{{cite book | title=Boldly Writing: A Trekker Fan & Zine History, 1967\u20131987 | author=Verba, Joan Marie | year=2003 | publisher=FTL Publications | location=Minnetonka MN | url=http://www.ftlpublications.com/bwebook.pdf | isbn=0-9653575-4-6 | access-date=6 October 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910042451/http://www.ftlpublications.com/bwebook.pdf | archive-date=10 September 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>{{rp|1}}<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/21/nyregion/21winston.html?pagewanted=print | work=The New York Times | title=Joan Winston, 'Trek' Superfan, Dies at 77 | first=William | last=Grimes | date=21 September 2008 | accessdate=2 April 2010}}</ref> by members of the [[Lunacon|Lunarians]].<ref name=\"cbs2000\">{{cite book | title=Science Fiction Culture | publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press | author=Bacon-Smith, Camille | pages=112\u2013113 | url=https://books.google.com/?id=oCvIZpCSRA0C&lpg=PA112&pg=PA112#v=onepage&f=false | year=2000 | isbn=978-0-8122-1530-4}}</ref> They hoped that fanzines such as ''Spockanalia'' would be recognized by the broader science-fiction fan community in traditional ways, such as a [[Hugo Award for Best Fanzine]].{{r|verba2003}}{{rp|6}} All five of its issues were published while the show was still on the air, and included letters from [[D. C. Fontana]], [[Gene Roddenberry]], and most of the cast members, and an article by future Hugo and Nebula winner [[Lois McMaster Bujold]].{{r|verba2003}}{{rp|1,2,83}}\n\nMany other Star Trek 'zines followed, then slowly zines appeared for other media sources, such as ''[[Starsky and Hutch]]'', ''[[Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'' and ''[[Blake's 7]]''. By the mid-1970s, there were enough media zines being published that [[adzines]] existed just to advertise all of the other zines available. Although ''Spockanalia'' had a mix of stories and essays, most zines were all fiction.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Like SF fanzines, these media zines spanned the gamut of publishing quality from [[digest-sized]] mimeos to offset printed masterpieces with four-color covers.\n\nMen wrote and edited most previous science fiction fanzines, which typically published articles reporting on trips to conventions, and reviews of books and other fanzines. Camille Bacon-Smith later stated that \"One thing you almost never find in a science fiction fanzine is science fiction. Rather ... fanzines were the social glue that created a community out of a worldwide scattering of readers.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Bacon-Smith|first=Camille|title=Science fiction culture|year=2000|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=978-0-8122-1530-4|url=http://www.upenn.edu/pennpress/book/13333.html}}</ref> Women published most media fanzines, which by contrast also included [[fan fiction]]. By doing so, they \"fill the need of a mostly female audience for fictional narratives that expand the boundary of the official source products offered on the television and movie screen.\"{{r|cbs2000}} In addition to long and short stories, as well as poetry, many media fanzines included illustrated stories, as well as stand alone art, often featuring portraits of the show or film's principal characters. The art could range from simple sketches, to reproductions of large elaborate works painted in oil or acrylic, though most are created in ink.\n\nIn the late 1970s, fiction that included a sexual relationship between two of the male characters of the media source (first [[Kirk/Spock]], then later Starsky/Hutch, Napoleon/Illya, and many others) started to appear in zines.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} This became known as [[Slash fiction|slash]] from the '/' mark used in adzines to differentiate a K&S story (which would have been a Kirk and Spock friendship story) from a K/S story, which would have been one with a romantic or sexual bent between the characters.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Slash zines eventually became their own sub-subgenre; in many [[fandoms]] you rarely saw slash and non-slash stories appear in the same zines.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} By 2000, when web publishing of stories became more popular than zine publishing, thousands of media fanzines had been published;<ref name=\"beyonddreamspress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beyonddreamspress.com/database.htm|title=Database over Kirk/Spock Zines published \u2013 CyberDreams|work=beyonddreamspress.com}}</ref> over 500 of them were k/s zines.<ref name=\"beyonddreamspress.com\"/>\n\nAnother popular franchise for fanzines was the \"[[Star Wars]]\" saga. By the time the film \"[[The Empire Strikes Back]]\" was released in 1980 Star Wars fanzines had surpassed Star Trek zines in sales{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}. An unfortunate episode in fanzine history occurred in 1981 when Star Wars director [[George Lucas]] threatened to sue fanzine publishers who distributed zines featuring the Star Wars characters in sexually explicit stories or art.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n===Comics ===\nComics were mentioned and discussed as early as the late 1930s in the [[science fiction fanzines|fanzines]] of [[science fiction fandom]]. Famously, the first version of [[Superman]] (a bald-headed villain) appeared in the third issue of [[Jerry Siegel]] and [[Joe Shuster]]'s 1933 fanzine ''Science Fiction''. In 1936, [[David Kyle]] published '' The Fantasy World '', possibly the first comics fanzine.<ref>Kyle, David. [http://jophan.org/mimosa/m24/kyle.htm \"Phamous Phantasy Phan\"]. [[Mimosa (magazine)|''Mimosa'']] no. 24, pp. 25\u201328.</ref><ref name=\"powerofcomics\"/> Malcolm Willits and Jim Bradley started ''[[The Comic Collector's News]]'' in October 1947.<ref>{{Google books|QMnxCwAAQBAJ|Everyday Information: The Evolution of Information Seeking in America|page=286|keywords=The+Comic+Collector's+News|text=|plainurl=}}</ref> By 1952, [[Ted White (author)|Ted White]] had mimeographed a four-page pamphlet about [[Superman]], and [[James Taurasi]] issued the short-lived ''Fantasy Comics''. In 1953, [[Bhob Stewart]] published ''The EC Fan Bulletin'',<ref name=\"powerofcomics\">{{Google books|PA175|The Power of Comics: History, Form and Culture|page=175|keywords=EC+Fan+Bulletin|text=|plainurl=}}</ref> which launched [[EC Comics|EC]] fandom of imitative EC fanzines. A few months later, Stewart, White and [[Larry Stark]] produced ''Potrzebie'', planned as a literary journal of critical commentary about EC by Stark. Among the wave of EC fanzines that followed, the best-known was [[Ron Parker (writer)|Ron Parker]]'s ''Hoo-Hah!''. After that came fanzines by the followers of [[Harvey Kurtzman]]'s ''[[Mad (magazine)|Mad]]'', ''[[Trump (magazine)|Trump]]'' and ''[[Humbug (magazine)|Humbug]]''. Publishers of these included future [[underground comics]] stars like [[Jay Lynch]] and [[Robert Crumb]].\n\nIn 1960, [[Richard A. Lupoff|Richard and Pat Lupoff]] launched their [[science fiction fandom|science fiction]] and comics fanzine ''[[Xero (SF fanzine)|Xero]]''. In the second issue, \"The Spawn of M.C. Gaines'\" by Ted White was the first in a series of nostalgic, analytical articles about comics by Lupoff, [[Don Thompson (Comics Buyer's Guide)|Don Thompson]], [[Bill Blackbeard]], [[Jim Harmon]] and others under the heading, ''All in Color for a Dime.'' In 1961, [[Jerry Bails]]' ''[[Alter Ego (fanzine)|Alter Ego]]'', devoted to [[superhero|costumed heroes]],<ref name=\"powerofcomics\"/> f became a focal point for superhero comics fandom and is thus sometimes mistakenly cited as the first comics fanzine.\n\nContacts through these magazines were instrumental in creating the culture of modern [[comics fandom]]: conventions, collecting, etc. Much of this, like comics fandom itself, began as part of standard [[science fiction convention]]s, but comics fans have developed their own traditions. Comics fanzines often include fan artwork based on existing characters as well as discussion of the history of comics. Through the 1960s, and 1970s, comic fanzines followed some general formats, such as the industry news and information magazine (''[[The Comic Reader]]'' was one example), interview, history and review-based fanzines, and the fanzines which basically represented independent comic book-format exercises. While perceived quality varied widely, the energy and enthusiasm involved tended to be communicated clearly to the readership, many of whom were also fanzine contributors. During the 1970s, many fanzines (''[[Squa Tront]]'', as example) also became partly distributed through certain comic book distributors.\n\nAt times, the professional comics publishers have made overtures to fandom via 'prozines', in this case fanzine-like magazines put out by the major publishers. ''[[The Amazing World of DC Comics]]'' and the Marvel magazine ''[[FOOM]]'' began and ceased publication in the 1970s. Priced significantly higher than standard comics of the period (''AWODCC'' was $1.50, ''FOOM'' was 75 cents), each house-organ magazine lasted a brief period of years. Since 2001 in Britain, there have been created a number of fanzines pastiching children's comics of the 1970s, and 1980s (e.g. ''[[Solar Wind (comic)|Solar Wind]]'', ''Pony School'', etc.). These adopt a style of storytelling rather than specific characters from their sources, usually with a knowing or [[irony|ironic]] twist.\n\n===Horror film ===\n[[File:Horrors of the Screen 3 fanzine cover 1964.jpg|thumb|right|Horrors of the Screen No. 3, 1964]]\nAs with comics zines, horror film fanzines grew from related interest within science fiction fan publications.  ''Trumpet,'' edited by [[Tom Reamy]], was a 1960s SF zine that branched into horror film coverage. Alex Soma's ''Horrors of the Screen,''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/unifan2001/HotS.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027140344/http://www.geocities.com/unifan2001/HotS.html|title=Horrors of the Screen|archivedate=27 October 2009|work=archive.org}}</ref> [[Calvin T. Beck]]'s ''Journal of Frankenstein'' (later ''[[Castle of Frankenstein]]'') and Gary Svehla's ''Gore Creatures'' were the first horror fanzines created as more serious alternatives to the popular [[Forrest J Ackerman]] 1958 magazine ''[[Famous Monsters of Filmland]].''  ''Gore Creatures'' began in 1961 and continues today as the prozine (and specialty publisher) ''Midnight Marquee.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midmar.com/|title=MIDNIGHT MARQUEE PRESS \u2013 BOOKS|work=midmar.com}}</ref> ''Garden Ghouls Gazette'' \u2013 a 1960s horror title under the editorship of Dave Keil, then Gary Collins\u2014was eventually headed by the late [[Frederick S. Clarke]] (1949\u20132000) and in 1967 became the respected journal ''[[Cinefantastique]].'' It later became a prozine under journalist-screenwriter [[Mark A. Altman]] and has continued as a webzine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinefantastiqueonline.com/|title=Cinefantastique: The Website with a Sense of Wonder|work=cinefantastiqueonline.com}}</ref>\n\nMark Frank's ''Photon''\u2014notable for the inclusion of an 8x10 [[Photograph|photo]] in each issue\u2014was another 1960s zine that lasted into the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.geocities.com/unifan2001/Photon.html | title = Photon | accessdate = 8 August 2012 | last = Frank | first = Mark | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091027140404/http://www.geocities.com/unifan2001/Photon.html | archivedate = 27 October 2009}}</ref> Richard Klemensen's ''[[Little Shoppe of Horrors]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littleshoppeofhorrors.com/|title=Little Shoppe of Horrors|work=littleshoppeofhorrors.com}}</ref> having a particular focus on \"[[Hammer Film Productions|Hammer Horrors]],\" began in 1972 and is still publishing as of 2019.\n\nThe [[Baltimore]]-based ''Black Oracle'' (1969\u20131978) from writer-turned-[[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]] repertory member [[George Stover]] was a diminutive zine that evolved into the larger-format ''Cinemacabre.''  Stover's ''Black Oracle'' partner Bill George published his own short-lived zine ''The Late Show'' (1974\u20131976; with co-editor Martin Falck), and later became editor of the ''Cinefantastique'' prozine spinoff ''[[Femme Fatales (magazine)|Femme Fatales]].'' In the mid-1970s, [[North Carolina]] teenager [[Sam Irvin]] published the horror/science-fiction fanzine ''Bizarre'' which included his original interviews with UK actors and filmmakers; Irvin would later become a producer-director in his own right.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinema.usc.edu/directories/profile.cfm?id=33692&first=&last=&title=&did=1&referer=%2Fproduction%2Ffaculty.cfm&startpage=1&startrow=31|title=School of Cinematic Arts Directory Profile \u2013 USC School of Cinematic Arts|work=usc.edu}}</ref> ''Japanese Fantasy Film Journal'' (JFFJ) (1968\u20131983) from the late Greg Shoemaker (1947\u20132019) covered [[Toho]]'s ''[[Godzilla]]'' and his Asian brethren when no other publications much cared. In 1993, ''[[G-FAN]]'' picked up where JFFJ left off, and reached its 100th regularly published issue in Fall 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g-fan.com/html/gfan_index/index_100.php|title=GFAN Magazine Index|work=g-fan.com}}</ref> ''FXRH'' ([[Special effects]] by [[Ray Harryhausen]]) (1971\u20131976) was a specialized zine co-created by future [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] [[Special effect|FX]] artist [[Ernest D. Farino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0267495/bio|title=Ernest Farino|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Rock and roll ===\nBy the mid-1960s, several fans active in science fiction and comics fandom recognized a shared interest in rock music, and the rock fanzine was born. [[Paul Williams (Crawdaddy! creator)|Paul Williams]] and [[Greg Shaw]] were two such SF-fans turned rock zine editors. Williams' ''[[Crawdaddy!]]'' (1966) and Shaw's two California-based zines, ''Mojo Navigator'' (full title, \"''Mojo-Navigator Rock and Roll News''\") (1966) and ''[[Who Put the Bomp]]'', (1970), are among the most important early rock fanzines.\n\n''[[Crawdaddy!]]'' (1966) quickly moved from its fanzine roots to become one of the first rock music \"prozines,\" with paid advertisers and newsstand distribution. ''Bomp'' remained a fanzine, featuring many writers who would later become prominent music journalists, including [[Lester Bangs]], [[Greil Marcus]], Ken Barnes, [[Ed Ward (writer)|Ed Ward]], [[Dave Marsh]], [[Mike Saunders]] and [[Richard Meltzer|R. Meltzer]].  ''Bomp'' featured cover art by Jay Kinney and Bill Rotsler, both veterans of SF and Comics fandom. ''Bomp'' was not alone; an August 1970 issue of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' included an article about the explosion of rock fanzines. Other rock fanzines of this period include ''[[denim delinquent]]'' 1971, edited by Jymn Parrett, ''Flash,'' 1972, edited by Mark Shipper, ''Eurock Magazine'' (1973\u20131993) edited by Archie Patterson and ''Bam Balam,'' written and published by Brian Hogg in East Lothian, Scotland, beginning in 1974, and in the mid-1970s, ''[[Back Door Man (fanzine)|Back Door Man]]''.\n\nIn the post-punk era several well-written fanzines emerged that cast an almost academic look at earlier, neglected musical forms, including Mike Stax' ''[[Ugly Things]]'', Billy Miller and [[Miriam Linna]]'s ''Kicks'', Jake Austen's ''[[Roctober (fanzine)|Roctober]]'', Kim Cooper's ''[[Scram (fanzine)|Scram]]'', P. Edwin Letcher's ''[[Garage & Beat]]'', and the UK's [[Shindig! (magazine)|Shindig!]] and Italy's ''[[Misty Lane]]''.\n\nIn the 1980s, with the rise of stadium superstars, many home-grown rock fanzines emerged. At the peak of [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s megastardom following the ''[[Born in the U.S.A.]]'' album and [[Born in the U.S.A. Tour]] in the mid-1980s, there were no less than five Springsteen fanzines circulating at the same time in the UK alone, and many others elsewhere. Gary Desmond's ''Candy's Room'', coming from Liverpool, was the first in 1980, quickly followed by Dan French's ''Point Blank'', Dave Percival's ''The Fever'', Jeff Matthews' ''Rendezvous'', and Paul Limbrick's ''Jackson Cage''. In the US, ''[[Backstreets Magazine]]'' started in Seattle in 1980 and still continues today as a glossy publication, now in communication with Springsteen's management and official website. In the late 1990s, notorious fanzines and e-zines flourished about electronic and [[post-rock]] music. ''Cr\u00e8me Br\u00fbl\u00e9e'' fanzine was one of those that documented post-rock genre and experimental music.\n\n===Punk ===\n{{Main|Punk zine}}\n{{Category see also|Punk zines}}\n[[File:1970s fanzines (21224199545).jpg|thumb|British punk fanzines from the 1970s.]]\n\n====UK ====\n\nThe [[punk subculture]] in the United Kingdom spearheaded a surge of interest in fanzines as a countercultural alternative to established print media. The first and still best known UK 'punk zine' was ''[[Sniffin' Glue]]'', produced by [[Deptford, London|Deptford]] punk fan [[Mark Perry (musician)|Mark Perry]].  ''Sniffin' Glue'' ran for 12 photocopied issues; the first issue was produced by Perry immediately following (and in response to) the London debut of [[The Ramones]] on 4 July 1976. Other UK fanzines included ''[[Blam! (fanzine)|Blam!]]'', ''[[Bombsite (fanzine)|Bombsite]]'', Wool City Rocker, ''Burnt Offering'', ''[[Chainsaw (punk zine)|Chainsaw]]'', ''[[New Crimes]]'', ''[[Vague (fanzine)|Vague]]'', ''[[Jamming (fanzine)|Jamming]]'', [[Artcore Fanzine]], ''[[Love and Molotov Cocktails]]'', ''[[To Hell With Poverty]]'', ''[[New Youth (fanzine)|New Youth]]'', ''[[Peroxide (punk zine)|Peroxide]]'', ''[[ENZK]]'', ''[[Juniper beri-beri]]'', ''[[No Cure]]'',''[[Communication Blur]]'', ''[[Rox (fanzine)|Rox]]'', ''[[Grim Humour]]'', ''[[Spuno]]''<ref name=\"Spuno info online\">{{cite web|url=http://si-site-nogsy.blogspot.com/2011/07/spuno-3-1980.html|title=essential ephemera|author=Si|work=si-site-nogsy.blogspot.com}}</ref>\n, ''[[Cool Notes]]'' and ''[[Fumes (magazine)|Fumes]]''. Of these, Tony Fletcher's ''Jamming'' was the most far reaching, becoming a nationally distributed mainstream magazine for several years before its demise.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n\n====US ====\nIn the US, ''[[Flipside (fanzine)|Flipside]]'' and ''[[Slash (fanzine)|Slash]]'' were important punk zines for the Los Angeles scene, both debuting in 1977. In 1977 in Australia, Bruce Milne and [[Clinton Walker]] fused their respective punk zines ''Plastered Press'' and ''Suicide Alley'' to launch ''Pulp''; Milne later went on to invent the cassette zine with ''Fast Forward'', in 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://messandnoise.com/features/4331535|title=Fast Forward: A Pre-Internet Story|date=18 September 2011|website=messandnoise.com|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clintonwalker.com.au/fanzines-1970s.html|title=Fanzines (1970s)|website=Clinton Walker|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> Starting earlier, in 1976, ''[[Punk (magazine)|Punk]]'' was published in New York and played a major part in popularizing [[Punk rock#Etymology|punk rock]] (a term coined a few years earlier in ''[[Creem]]'') as the term for the music and the bands being written about.\n\nAmong later titles, ''[[Maximum RocknRoll]]'' is a major punk zine, with over 300 issues published. As a result, in part, of the popular and commercial resurgence of punk in the late 1980s, and after, with the growing popularity of such bands as [[Sonic Youth]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Fugazi (band)|Fugazi]], [[Bikini Kill]], [[Green Day]] and [[The Offspring]], a number of other punk zines have appeared, such as ''[[Punk Planet]]'', ''[[Razorcake]]'', ''[[Tail Spins]]'', ''[[Sobriquet (magazine)|Sobriquet]]'', ''[[Profane Existence]]'' and ''[[Slug and Lettuce (fanzine)|Slug and Lettuce]]''. The early American punkzine ''[[RE/Search|Search and Destroy]]'' eventually became the influential fringe-cultural magazine ''[[Re/Search]]''.\n\nSome punk fanzines from the 80s, like No Class fanzine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noclass.co.uk|title=No Class Fanzine, No Class Records, No Class Now, No Class Gigs|work=noclass.co.uk}}</ref> and Ugly American<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uglyamericanzine.com|title=The Official Ugly American Zine Archives, 1988\u20131999.|work=uglyamericanzine.com}}</ref> are experiencing a second life by placing all past content online for free and adding new content. For the past 6 years, Suburban Rebels in Northern California has been leading the Punk zine way.\n\nMany of the punk zines were printed in small quantities and promoted the local scene. They were often cheaply photocopied and many never survived beyond a few issues. Their greatest contribution was in promoting punk music, clothing and lifestyle in their local communities. Punk bands and independent labels often sent records to the zines for review and many of the people who started the zines became critical connections for punk bands on tour.\n\n====After the year 2000====\n\nIn the UK ''[[Fracture (fanzine)|Fracture]]'' and ''[[Reason To Believe (fanzine)|Reason To Believe]]'' were significant fanzines in the early 2000s, but both ended in late 2003. ''[[Rancid News]]'' filled the gap left by these two zines for a short while. On its tenth issue ''Rancid News'' changed its name to ''[[Last Hours]]'' with 7 issues published under this title before going on hiatus. ''Last Hours'' still operates as a [[webzine]] though with more focus on the anti-authoritarian movement than its original title. ''[[Artcore Fanzine]]'' (established in 1986) continues to this day, recently publishing a number of 30-year anniversary issues. There are many smaller fanzines in existence throughout the UK that focus on punk.\n\n=====Mark Wilkins and Mystic records=====\n\nMark Wilkins, the promotion director for 1982 onwards US punk/thrash label [[Mystic Records]], had over 450 US fanzines and 150 foreign fanzines he promoted to regularly. He and Mystic Records owner Doug Moody edited ''The Mystic News Newsletter'' which was published quarterly and went into every promo package to fanzines. Wilkins also published the highly successful Los Angeles punk humor zine ''Wild Times'' and when he ran out of funding for the zine syndicated some of the humorous material to over 100 US fanzines under the name of Mystic Mark.\n\n====Italy====\nIn [[Perugia]], Italy, ''Mazquerade'' ran from 1979 to 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perugiamusica.com/RIVISTE/MAZQUERADE/mazquerade.html|title=Perugiamusica.com|website=perugiamusica.com|accessdate=14 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303123957/http://www.perugiamusica.com/RIVISTE/MAZQUERADE/mazquerade.html|archive-date=3 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Basilicata]], Italy, ''Raw Art Fanzine'' ran from 1995 to 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truemetal.it/news/raw-art-fanzine-restauro-digitale-e-disponibilita-dei-numeri-degli-anni-90-89535|title=Raw Art Fanzine: restauro digitale e disponibilit\u00e0 dei numeri degli anni '90|website=truemetal.it|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Milano]], Italy, ''Gorezilla'' ran from 1988 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moviemags.com/main_g.php?title=GOREZILLA&year=%}}</ref>\n\n===Mod===\nIn the United Kingdom, the 1979 [[Mod revival]], which was inspired by the 1960s [[Mod subculture]], brought with it a burst of fresh creativity from fanzines, and for the next decade, the youth [[subculture]] inspired the production of dozens of independent publications. The most successful of the first wave was ''Maximum Speed'', which successfully captured the frenetic world of a [[Mod (subculture)|mod]] revival scene that was propelling bands like [[Secret Affair]], [[Purple Hearts (British band)|Purple Hearts]] and [[The Chords]] into the UK charts.\n\nAfter the genre had started to go out of fashion with mainstream audiences in 1981, the mod revival scene went underground and successfully reinvented itself through a series of clubs, bands and fanzines that breathed fresh life into the genre, culminating in another burst of creative acceptance in 1985. This success was largely driven by the network of underground fanzines, the most important and far reaching of which were ''Extraordinary Sensations'', produced by future radio DJ [[Eddie Piller]], and ''Shadows & Reflections'', published by future national magazine editor [[Chris Hunt]]. The latter in particular pushed back the boundaries of fanzine production, producing glossy, professionally written and printed publications at a time (1983\u201386) when most fanzines were produced via photocopier and letraset.\n\n===Local music===\nIn the UK, there were also fanzines that covered the local music scene in a particular town or city. Mainly prevalent in the 1970s, and 1980s, all music styles were covered, whether the bands were playing rock, punk, metal, futurist, ska or dance. Featured were local gig reviews and articles that were below the radar of the mainstream music press. They were produced using the technology of the time, i.e. typewriter and [[Letraset]]. Examples include ''[[Bombsite Fanzine]]'' (Liverpool 1977), Wool City Rocker (Bradford 1979 \u2013 1982), ''[[City Fun]]'' (Manchester), 1984, Spuno (Bath 1980)<ref name=\"Spuno info online\"/> ''[[No Cure]]'' (Berkshire) and ''[[Town Hall Steps (fanzine)|Town Hall Steps]]'' (Bolton) and more recently [[''mono'' (fanzine)]], (Bradford) with many more across the country, such as Premonition Tapes Tapezine on cassette (Sheffield 1987) and Crime Pays (Liverpool 1988).\n\n===Role-playing-game fanzines===\nAnother sizable group of fanzines arose in [[role-playing game]] (RPG) fandom, where fanzines allowed people to publish their ideas and views on specific games and their [[role-playing campaigns]]. In 1975, was released the apazine [[Alarums and Excursions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arielarchives.com/Brett/magazines/alarumsandexcursions.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061024220743/http://www.arielarchives.com/Brett/magazines/alarumsandexcursions.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 October 2006|title=RPG Magzine and zine Index- Alarms & Excursions Page|date=24 October 2006|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nRole-playing fanzines allowed people to communicate in the 1970s, and 1980s with complete editorial control in the hands of the players, as opposed to the game publishers. These early RPG fanzines were generally typed, sold mostly in an A5 format (in the UK) and were usually illustrated with abysmal or indifferent artwork.\n\nA fanzine community developed and was based on sale to a reading public and exchanges by editor/publishers. Many of the pioneers of RPG zinedom got their start in, or remain part of, [[science fiction fandom]]. This is also true of the small but still active [[board game]] fandom scene, the most prolific subset of which is centered around [[play-by-mail game|play-by-mail]] [[Diplomacy game|Diplomacy]].\n\nThe UK fanzine [[Aslan (fanzine)|Aslan]] (1988\u20131991)<ref>{{Google books|ix9WDwAAQBAJ|Role-Playing Game Studies: Transmedia Foundations|keywords=aslan+fanzine|text=|plainurl=}}</ref> was responsible for popularization of [[freeform role-playing game]]s in the UK.<ref name=nnbtv>{{cite web |url=http://nnbtv.org.uk/Games/History.html|title=Me and Freeforms|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Video gaming ===\nVideo game fanzines first emerged during the [[Second generation of video game consoles|second generation period]] when newsletters for computer user groups and stores were not uncommon, though not always well-known. Subscriber-based newsletters included the well-known ''[[8: 16 (UK, all things Atari, 1st issue Nov 1987)]]'',''[[The Video Game Update]]'' and later ''[[Computer Entertainer]]''. The publication, ''[[Joystick Jolter]]'' was the first actual fanzine.\n\nLater, as desktop publishing tools became more accessible, there was an increase in fanzine production. Fanzines generally emphasized either classic gaming (e.g. ''[[2600 Connection]]'' and ''[[Classic Systems & Games Monthly]]''), or current gaming (e.g. ''[[APE (fanzine)|APE]]'' and ''[[The Subversive Sprite]]''). However some fanzines covered both topics (e.g. ''[[Digital Press]]'' and ''[[Joystick & Screen]]''). The number of zines grew bigger when video game journalists including [[Arnie Katz]] and [[Chris Bieniek]] used their columns to publish reviews of fanzines that they had been sent at magazines like ''[[Video Games & Computer Entertainment]]'', ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]'', and ''[[Tips & Tricks]]''. These reviews had the effect of introducing fan editors to each other and creating a fanzine scene.\n\nThe video game fanzine diminished greatly in popularity with the rise of the web, though some zines\u2014particularly the classic gaming ones\u2014continued past the mid-90s (e.g. ''[[Classic Gamer Magazine]]'' and ''[[Video Game Collector]]''). The rise of \"on demand\" publishing has led to a new outlet for print zines, like ''[[Jumpbutton]]'' and ''[[Scroll]]''.\n\nThe video game fanzine era was biggest in the US and Canada,{{citation needed|date=November 2012}} but there were/are zines from other countries too. Video game fanzines in UK have included ''[[Retrogamer]]'', ''[[Pixel Nation]]'', ''[[Capcom Fanzine]]'', ''[[Mercury (fanzine)|Mercury]]'', and ''[[Super Famicom Mini Mag]]'' among others.<ref>Bielby, Matt, ed. \"Super Express \u2013 Fanhunter: Super Play's Fanzine Round-Up.\" ''[[Super Play]]''. Issue 9, Pg.14. July 1993. {{ISSN|0966-6192}}.</ref> In France fanzines like ''[[Revival (fanzine)|Revival]]'' we circulated, and Japan has seen the production of lavish [[doujin]] works.\n\nMore recently, there has been a mini-resurgence in video game fanzines, with the launch of HyperPlay RPG in 2015 and Switch Player in 2017. Based in part on the above-mentioned Super Play with a focus on role-playing games and \"any-bit\" Nintendo,<ref>hyperplayrpg.com</ref> popular fanzine HyperPlay RPG has been consistently well-reviewed by the mainstream video game media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2015/09/hyperplay_rpg_is_a_glorious_throwback_to_the_pre-internet_days_of_homemade_fanzines|title=HyperPlay RPG Is A Glorious Throwback to the Pre-Internet Days Of Homemade Fanzines|first=Nintendo|last=Life|date=27 September 2015|website=nintendolife.com|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Wargaming===\nSeveral fanzines exist within the hobby of [[wargaming]]. Among them is ''[[CHARGE! (magazine)|Charge!]]'', a leading international fanzine exclusively for [[miniature wargaming]] enthusiasts for the [[American Civil War]] period. Other fanzines support [[Warhammer Fantasy Battle|Warhammer]] and other popular rules sets.\n\n===Sport===\n{{Category see also|Football fanzines}}\nThe first association football fanzine is regarded as being [[Foul (fanzine)|Foul]], a publication that ran between 1972 and 1976.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fact Sheet 7: Fan 'Power' and Democracy in Football |url=http://www.le.ac.uk/so/css/resources/factsheets/fs7.html |work=Department of Sociology: Sports Resources |publisher=University of Leicester |access-date=25 August 2010 |author=Gavin Barber (updated by John Williams) |year=2002 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821184842/http://www.le.ac.uk/so/css/resources/factsheets/fs7.html |archive-date=21 August 2010 |df= }}</ref> In the UK, most [[Premier League]] or [[The Football League|Football League]] [[association football|football]] clubs have one or more fanzines which supplement, oppose and complement the club's official magazine or matchday programme. A reasonably priced 'zine has a guaranteed audience, as is the culture of passion in being a football fan.\n\nThe longest running fanzine is ''[[The City Gent (fanzine)|The City Gent]]'', produced by supporters of [[Bradford City FC]], which first went on sale at Valley Parade in November 1984 and is now in its 26th season. Following close on its heels was Nike, Inc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a-love-supreme.com|title=A Love Supreme \u2013 The Independent Sunderland Football Club Fanzine|author=Azure Graphic & Web Design|work=a-love-supreme.com}}</ref> which was first released in 1989. At the time it was not the first of its kind with ''Terrace Talk'' (York City), which was first published in November 1981 and ''Wanderers Worldwide'' (Bolton Wanderers) having already been established but since disappeared. In 1985 the emergent ''[[When Saturday Comes]]'' (a fanzine without a specific club focus that was subsequently launched as a mainstream magazine) promoted a 'fanzine movement' that gave birth to many more club titles during the late 1980s which was something of a glory period for fanzines.\n\nWith the widespread availability of the Internet, much of the energy that was put into football fanzines subsequently went into the development of supporters' websites. Examples of other UK football fanzines include ''[[A Love Supreme (fanzine)|A Love Supreme]]'' ([[Sunderland AFC|Sunderland]]), ''[[TOOFIF]]'' ([[Fulham FC|Fulham]]), ''[[The Square Ball]]'' ([[Leeds United]]), ''4,000 Holes'' ([[Blackburn Rovers]]) and ''[[War of the Monster Trucks]]'' (a [[Sheffield Wednesday]] fanzine named after a local TV station elected not to show the final scenes of an unlikely cup victory). The Queen's Park Rangers fanzine 'A Kick up the Rs' was first published in August 1987 and is still issuing an average of 10 issues per season.\n\nFanzines are not exclusive to the top tiers of football however, with [[Northern Counties East League]] side [[Scarborough Athletic FC]] having a fanzine titled ''[[Abandon Chip!]]'', a pun based on both the perilous situation of predecessor club [[Scarborough FC]] and that club's sponsors, [[McCain Foods Limited|McCain]].\n\nAnd also away from the world of Football there were a number of established fanzines, for example [[Rugby league]] has such notable publications as ''[[Who The Hell Was St. George Anyway?]]'' Rugby League fanzine, by supporters of Doncaster RLFC and ''Scarlet Turkey'' of [[Salford Red Devils|Salford City Reds]].However, due to pressure from the Internet etc. these publications no longer exist in printed form. The title of World's longest running Rugby League fanzine now belongs to ''[[The Aye of the Tigers]]'', by Castleford Tigers supporters. The fanzine movement has even spread to the United States, where ice hockey fans have produced several popular fanzines. In Chicago two examples include the formerly published ''Blue Line Magazine'' and currently ''The Committed Indian'', both produced by [[Chicago Blackhawks]] fans.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chitowndailynews.org/2009/05/27/The-Committed-Indian-Snark-and-in-depth-report-informs-and-entertains-27581.html | title=The Committed Indian; Snark and in-depth report informs and entertains | work=[[Chi-Town Daily News]] | date=27 May 2009 | access-date=18 October 2018 | author=Grant, Lou | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130703231147/http://www.chitowndailynews.org/2009/05/27/The-Committed-Indian-Snark-and-in-depth-report-informs-and-entertains-27581.html | archive-date=3 July 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> In [[St. Louis]] there are ''Game Night Revue'' and ''St Louis Game Time'' for the [[St. Louis Blues]].\n\nThere are also a number of fanzines to be found in Ireland of which [[Shelbourne F.C.|Shelbourne]]'s ''Red Inc.'' is the longest running.\n\nIn the United States, sports fanzines are relatively rare. In [[Boston]] they are a bit more common. There are two fanzines sold outside Fenway Park including ''Yawkey Way Report'', which is run by a former Marine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://yawkeywayreport.com/meet-the-staff/ceo-sly-egidio/|title=CEO Sly Egidio \u2013 Yawkey Way Report|newspaper=Yawkey Way Report|access-date=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/09/10/fenway-scene-war-among-rival-hawkers-game-programs/eTsR16JIvyshTp3S7tLhEJ/story.html|title=Fenway program hawkers' rivalry fuels competition|newspaper=Boston Globe|access-date=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Recent developments==\nWith the increasing availability of the Internet in the late 20th and the early 21st century, the traditional paper zine has begun to give way to the [[webzine]] (or \"e-zine\") that is easier to produce and uses the potential of the Internet to reach an ever-larger, possibly global, audience. Nonetheless, printed fanzines are still produced, either out of preference for the format or to reach people who do not have convenient Web access. Online versions of approximately 200 [[science fiction fanzine]]s will be found at Bill Burns'<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eFanzines.com|title=eFanzines.com|website=efanzines.com|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> eFanzines web site, along with links to other [[science fiction fanzine|SF fanzine]] sites. In addition zine festivals are held each year in American cities like Los Angeles,<ref>[http://boingboing.net/2012/02/10/la-zine-fest-feb-19.html \"LA Zine Fest,\" ''Boing Boing'']</ref> Chicago,<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-03-23/features/ct-prj-0324-zines-20130323_1_zine-scene-zine-collection-science-fiction \"The Zine Scene,\" ''Chicago Tribune]''</ref> and Brooklyn,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2012/apr/16/micropolis-brooklyn-zine-fest|title=Micropolis: The Brooklyn Zine Fest|publisher=WNYC}}</ref> as well as internationally in cities including Melbourne, Australia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stickyinstitute.com/fotp2016|title=Sticky Institute|website=stickyinstitute.com|access-date=18 April 2016}}</ref> and Glasgow, UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glasgowzinefest.com/|title=http://glasgowzinefest.com/|website=glasgowzinefest.com|access-date=18 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n* [[Alt.zines]]\n* [[Amateur press association]]\n* [[British small press comics]]\n* [[Desktop publishing]]\n* [[D\u014djinshi]]\n* [[Fandom]]\n* [[Hugo Award for Best Fanzine]]\n* [[Hugo Award for Best Semiprozine]]\n{{Col-2}}\n* Literature\n* [[Minicomic Co-ops]] (The United Fanzine Organization)\n* [[Minicomics]]\n* Printing\n* Publishing\n* [[Revolutionart]]\n* [[Science fiction fandom]]\n* [[Weblog]]\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Schelly, Bill. ''The Golden Age of Comic Fandom''. Introduction by Roy Thomas. Seattle, WA: Hamster Press, 1995.\n*Lupoff, Dick [Richard A.] and Don Thompson, eds. ''All in Color for a Dime''. New Rochelle, N.Y.: Arlington House, 1970.\n\n==External links==\n{{external links|date=May 2019}}\n{{Commons category|Fanzines}}\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/02/fanzine-simon-reynolds-blog How the fanzine refused to die]\n*[http://www.jessesword.com/sf/view/186 Citations for \"fanzine\" collected by the Oxford English Dictionary]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050901095834/http://rehupa.com/apa_hist.htm Origins of the amateur press associations]\n*[http://fanac.org/fanzines/ Historic science fiction fanzines at Fanac.org]\n*[http://efanzines.com/ Current and archived science fiction fanzines at eFanzines.com]\n*[http://www.asimovs.com/_issue_0501/thoughtexperiments.shtml An article by critic Roger Ebert describing his involvement with science fiction fanzines in the 1950s.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050206113212/http://www.scrammagazine.com/shaw.html An interview with Bomp! publisher Greg Shaw discussing his experience as a teenage SF fanzine and rock zine publisher, and the evolution of zines through the 1990s.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060220194048/http://www.skipwilliamson.com/UndergroundComix.html The Underground Comix movement began as a network of fanzines.]\n*[http://comicattack.net/category/cafeaturedcolumns/inkstains/ Ink Stains (column on comics fanzines of the 60s, 70s, and 80s)]\n*[http://www.lib.uiowa.edu/spec-coll/MSC/ToMsC800/MsC791/MsC791_horvatfanzines.htm M. Horvat Fanzine Collection at the U. of Iowa]\n*[http://fanlore.org/wiki/Category:Zines Fanlore includes an extensive resource of media fanzines including table of contents, awards and covers]\n*[http://fanzinoteca.it/ Zinelibrary Italy]\n*[http://www.fanzindb.org/ Fanzine Database Turkey]\n*[http://www.geocities.ws/mneko13/whoswho.htm On-File Who's Who of videogame fandom]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150430212609/http://www.1up.com/features/gaming-journalism-unplugged Gaming Journalism: Unplugged]\n*[https://www.wired.com/gamelife/2012/12/japan-gaming-doujin/ Japan's Gaming Fanzines Delve Into the Most Obsessive Topics]\n*[http://lazinefest.com/ LA Zine Fest]\n*[http://chicagozinefest.org/ Chicago Zine Fest]\n*[http://www.brooklynzinefest.com Brooklyn Zine Fest]\n*[http://fanziny.ic.cz Some Czechoslovak science fiction fanzines in digital form.]\n*[https://issuu.com/rawartfanzine Italian Raw Art Fanzine 1995\u20132000 digitally restored for free online.]\n*[http://dezskinn.com/fanzines/ Fanzines] [[Dez Skinn]]'s website\n* [http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/fanzine Fanzine] on [[The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction]]\n{{Independent production}}\n{{fandom}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Fanzines|*]]\n[[Category:Zines]]\n[[Category:Fanspeak]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1940s]]\n", "name_user": "YanN2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMedia:Added 1 citiation for \"By the time the film \"The Empire Strikes Back\" was released in 1980 Star Wars fanzines had surpassed Star Trek zines in sales\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fanzine"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal", "text_new": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{short description|COVID-19 disease pandemic in Nepal}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal\n| map1            = Nepal COVID-19 outbreak map (29 March 2020).svg\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in Nepal (as of 29 March) {{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = Nepal\n| first_case      = [[Kathmandu District]]\n| arrival_date    = 5 January 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 6\n| recovery_cases  = 1\n| active_cases    = 5\n| deaths          = 0\n| territories     = [[Kathmandu District|Kathmandu]], [[Kailali District|Kailali]], [[Baglung District|Baglung]]\n| website         = {{official|url=https://heoc.mohp.gov.np/|name=Health Emergency Operation Centre (HEOC)}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global COVID-19 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to Nepal when its first case was confirmed in Kathmandu on 24 January 2020. The patient only showed mild symptoms and had been discharged a week earlier with instructions to self-quarantine at home; he was subsequently confirmed to have completely recovered. Between January and March, Nepal took steps to prevent a widespread outbreak of the disease, while preparing for it by procuring essential supplies, equipment and medicine, upgrading health infrastructure, training medical personnel, and spreading public awareness. The second case was confirmed on 23 March 2020. {{As of|2020|03|29}}, three additional cases have been confirmed, including one each in Kailali and Baglung districts. All five confirmed cases have been in people who had recently returned from abroad. The four patients under treatment are reported to be in \"normal\" condition. A country-wide lockdown came into effect on 24 March, and is scheduled to end on 8 April.\n\nNepal established health-desks at the international airport as well as on border checkpoints with India, starting in mid-January. Land borders with India as well as China were later completely sealed off, and all international flights suspended. All academic examinations were cancelled, and schools and colleges were closed. Quarantine centres and temporary hospitals are being setup across the country. Laboratory facilities are being upgraded and expanded. Hospitals have been setting up [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] units and [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] beds. The [[SAARC]] countries have pledged to cooperate in controlling the disease in the region. India, the United States and Germany have increased their support to Nepali health sector.\n\nNepal cancelled its international promotional activities related to ''Visit Nepal Year 2020''. Its economy is expected to be severely affected by the pandemic due its impact on foreign employment, tourism, manufacturing, construction and trade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/govt-to-carry-out-impact-assessment-of-coronavirus-on-economy/|title=Govt to carry out impact assessment of coronavirus on economy|date=2020-03-06|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n===COVID-19 pandemic===\nThe ongoing [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) is caused by <!--NO DEFINITE ARTICLE (\"THE\") AS PER VIRUS'S ARTICLE--> [[SARS-COV-2|severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2).<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 |url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> The outbreak was first identified in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei, China]], in December 2019 and recognised as a pandemic by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) on 11 March 2020.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020|title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11 March 2020|date=11 March 2020|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|3|29}}, more than 708,000 cases of COVID-19 have been reported in over 190 countries and territories, resulting in approximately 33,500 deaths.<ref name=\"WOM\" /> More than 150,000 people have since recovered.<ref name=\"WOM\" >{{cite web |url= https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus Update (Live) |work=Worldometer |date=2020 |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"JHU CSSE2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases|publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]]|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe virus primarily [[Transmission (medicine)|spreads]] between people in a way similar to [[influenza]], via [[respiratory droplets]] from coughing or sneezing.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url= https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/getting-workplace-ready-for-covid-19.pdf |title=Getting your workplace ready for COVID-19 |date=27 February 2020 |work=World Health Organization |url-status=live}}</ref><!--Quote=In other words, COVID-19 spreads in a similar way to flu--><ref name=\"WHO2020QA\">{{cite web |url= https://www.who.int/news-room/q-a-detail/q-a-coronaviruses |title=Q&A on coronaviruses |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |work=WHO.int |date=11 February 2020 |access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref><!--Quote=The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing.--><ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\">{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/symptoms.html |title=Symptoms of Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |date=10 February 2020 |work=CDC.gov |publisher=US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]) |access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n<!--Quote=The virus is thought to spread mainly from person-to-person&nbsp;.... Via respiratory droplets produced when an infected person coughs or sneezes.-->The time between [[Incubation period|exposure and symptom onset]] is typically five days, but may range from two to fourteen days.<ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{cite journal |last1=Rothan |first=H. A. |last2=Byrareddy |first2=S. N. |title=The epidemiology and pathogenesis of coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak |journal=Journal of Autoimmunity |page=102433 |date=February 2020 |pmid=32113704 |doi=10.1016/j.jaut.2020.102433 |url= http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896841120300469}}</ref> Symptoms are most often fever, dry cough, and shortness of breath.<ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Complications may include [[pneumonia]] and [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]]. There is no [[vaccine]] or specific [[antiviral treatment]], but research is ongoing. Efforts are aimed at managing symptoms and [[supportive therapy]].<!-- Quote=There is currently no vaccine to prevent coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19)&nbsp;.... There is no specific antiviral treatment recommended for COVID-19 --> Recommended preventive measures include [[handwashing]], covering the mouth when coughing, [[Social distancing|maintaining distance from other people]] (particularly those who are unwell), and monitoring and [[self-isolation]] for fourteen days for people who suspect they are infected.<ref name=\"WHO2020QA\" /><ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\" /><ref name=CDC2020SocialSpacing>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url= https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/specific-groups/high-risk-complications.html |work=CDC.gov |publisher=US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |access-date=9 March 2020 |date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\nNepal is a landlocked country with China in the northern side and India in the east, west and south. Nepal shares a {{convert|1414|km|mi}} border with China's autonomous region of Tibet, in the Himalayas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85919/|title=Nepal-China Rasuwagadhi border point to be sealed for 15 days from Wednesday|last=DEVKOTA|first=HIMNATH|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> China is Nepal's second-largest trading partner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2015/09/09/nepal-has-trade-surplus-with-32-countries|title=Nepal has trade surplus with 32 countries|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Nepal has an 1,800-km open border with India in the east, west and south. Nepal lies in South Asia, one of the least developed and most densely populated world regions, that performs poorly in education as well as health care and sanitation metrics, and is therefore considered one of the highest risk areas for the pandemic, and also one of the least prepared.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ranks-111th-in-health-security-index/|title=Nepal ranks 111th in health security index|date=2020-02-08|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/28/south-asia-prepared-wuhan-virus-china-nepal-india-health/|title=Is South Asia Prepared for the Wuhan Virus?|last=Salam|first=Ravi Agrawal, Kathryn|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref name=tht116>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-vulnerable-to-new-china-virus-warn-doctors/|title=Nepal vulnerable to new China virus, warn doctors|date=2020-01-16|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21150529/italy-coronavirus-south-korea|title=How to travel during the international coronavirus outbreak|last=Belluz|first=Julia|date=2020-02-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ill-prepared-for-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Nepal ill-prepared for coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-02-26|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'', before the pandemic, hospitals in Nepal had few ICU beds (just three in Teku Hospital) which were almost always occupied, with people in critical condition usually having to wait for the beds to become empty. It reported doctors as saying that it would be next to impossible to admit new patients to ICU as soon as they need them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/12/nepal-s-hospitals-have-no-icus-to-treat-coronavirus-patients-doctors-say|title=Nepal's hospitals have no ICUs to treat coronavirus patients, doctors say|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Teku Hospital, the only one designated for handling infectious disease, had built an isolation ward during the [[avian influenza]] outbreak a decade ago, but had never brought it into use, as it did not have experts to evaluate or maintain the required standards.<ref name=two/>\n\nAs news of a new infectious disease in China broke, concerns were raised in Nepal over the high potential risk, the need to implement preventive measures and a severe lack of necessary medical equipment and infrastructure. According to Baburam Marasini, former director of [[Epidemiology and Disease Control Division]], Nepal does not have any double cab ambulances to transport highly infectious patients safely, isolation wards in hospitals, or biosafety level-3 or better laboratories needed to test for highly infectious diseases.<ref name=tht116/>\n\n==Epidemiological overview==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatright\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n{{nowrap|Confirmed COVID-19 cases in Nepal by district}}\n! rowspan=2; |District\n! rowspan=2; |Cases\n! colspan=2; |Recovered\n! colspan=2; |Deaths\n|-\n! #\n! %\n! #\n! %\n|-\n!Baglung\n|'''2'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|-\n!Kailali\n|'''1'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|-\n!Kathmandu\n|'''3'''\n|1\n|33%\n|0\n|0%\n|-\n!Total\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''6'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''1'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''16.67%'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''0'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''0%'''\n|}\nAs of 29 March 2020, Nepal has confirmed five cases of COVID-19 disease, all of them in persons who had recently returned from abroad. The first case was confirmed on 24 January in a 32-year-old man who had recently returned from China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=India Times |first1=The Economic Times |title=Nepal confirms first case of deadly coronavirus |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms |accessdate=Jan 24, 2020 |publisher=The Economic Times}}</ref> The patient had shown mild symptoms, and was completely cured by the end of January.<ref name=paper/> The second case was confirmed on 23 March in a 19-year-old woman who had recently returned from France via Qatar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/|title=One imported case of coronavirus confirmed in Nepal|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> She is being treated in Teku hospital, Kathmandu. Her family has been put in quarantine at home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/23/15849466024353731.html|title=Second confirmed case of covid-19 in Nepal|url-status=live|language=ne}}</ref> The third case was confirmed on 25 March, in a person who had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Third person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The fourth case, the first outside Kathmandu, was confirmed on 27 March, in a 34-year-old man who had recently returned from the Middle East. He is being treated in Seti Provincial Hospital in [[Dhangadhi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fourth-covid-19-positive-case-confirmed-by-health-ministry/|title=Fourth case of Covid-19 in Nepal|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The fifth case was confirmed in Baglung on 28 March, in a 19-year-old woman who had returned from Belgium via Qatar. She had shared a flight from Doha to Kathmandu with the patient who was confirmed on 23 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Fifth case of covid-19 cofirmed in Nepal|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> All four patients undergoing treatment are reported to be in \"normal\" condition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/166VA-CyCkujymP6NhdViM6EcjP95MKwy/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=SitRep#49_COVID-19_29-03-2020_NP.pdf|website=Google Docs|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nSukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital is the designated primary hospital for the treatment of COVID-19. A temporary hospital, named Bharatpur Corona Special Hospital, has been established in Chitwan District. [[Nepal Public Health Laboratory]] in Kathmandu was the only laboratory capable of testing for the disease {{as of|lc=y|2020|03|15}}; it was capable of conducting 500 tests a week and had a stock of 1,000 viral transport media (VTM) kits for transporting samples to be tested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/stock-of-kits-to-transport-coronavirus-samples-limited/|title=Stock of kits to transport coronavirus samples limited|date=2020-03-16|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/03/12/central-laboratory-is-equipped-to-test-500-covid-19-cases-a-week-but-that-is-far-too-low-say-public-health-experts|title=Central laboratory is equipped to test 500 Covid-19 cases a week, but that is far too low, say public health experts|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It had conducted a total of 917 tests {{as of|2020|03|29|lc=y}}.{{efn|The actual number of individuals tested is thought to be much lower.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/22/test-test-test-says-who-but-nepal-has-neither-the-means-nor-the-matter|title=Test, test, test, says WHO but Nepal has neither the means nor the matter|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heoc.mohp.gov.np/|title=Health Emergency Operation Center \u2013 Health Emergency Operation Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===Nepalis abroad===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatright\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n{{nowrap|COVID-19 cases in Nepalis abroad}}\n! Country/Territory\n! Cases\n! Deaths\n|-\n!Australia\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!Bahrain\n|3\n|0\n|-\n!Portugal\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!United Arab Emirates\n|2\n|0\n|-\n!United Kingdom\n|1\n|1\n|-\n!United States\n|1\n|1\n|-\n!Total\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''9'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''2'''\n|}\nA Nepali student who had recently reached [[Tasmania]] via Singapore tested positive for COVID-19 on 8 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepali-in-australia-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/|title=Nepali in Australia tests positive for coronavirus|date=2020-03-09|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> On 9 March, the UAE's Health Ministry confirmed that two Nepalis in the country had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/two-nepalis-test-positive-for-coronavirus-in-uae/|title=Two Nepalis test positive for coronavirus in UAE|date=2020-03-10|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> On 16 March, it was reported that seventy four Nepali migrant workers were put into 14-day quarantine in Faro City, Portugal, after one of them tested positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/74-nepalis-quarantined-in-portugal/|title=74 Nepalis quarantined in Portugal|date=2020-03-17|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Later, it was reported that only three of the quarantined were Nepalis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/miscellany/three-nepalis-in-quarantine-in-portugal-for-covid-19|title=Three Nepalis in quarantine in Portugal for COVID-19|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Three Nepalis tested positive in Bahrain, two of them on 21 March and one on 22 March; three more were put into 14-day quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-nepalis-contract-covid-19/|title=Three nepalis contract covid-19|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nA 66-year-old former [[British Gorkha|British Gurkha]] soldier of Nepali origin died from COVID-19 in the United Kingdom on 17 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/elderly-nepali-origin-man-dies-of-virus-in-uk/|title=Elderly Nepali-origin man dies of virus in UK|date=2020-03-22|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> A 50-year-old man of Nepali origin died of the disease in the United States on 24 March.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/25/uber-driver-who-stopped-working-to-avoid-coronavirus-dies-from-disease/ |title = Uber driver who stopped working to avoid coronavirus dies from disease|date = 25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===January===\nA 31-year-old student of [[Wuhan University of Technology|Wuhan University]] who had returned home on 5 January,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms|title=Nepal confirms first case of deadly coronavirus|date=2020-01-24|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> was admitted with mild symptoms on 13 January and discharged on 17 January with instructions to self-quarantine at home after preliminary tests showed he may not be infected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-test-on-china-returnee-shows-negative-result.html|title=Coronavirus test on China returnee shows negative result \u2013 OnlineKhabar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Although Nepal had the laboratories and the skilled manpower to test for the disease, Nepal did not have the [[reagent]]s required. The reagents cost around [[Nepalese rupee|Rs]] 17,000 per test and need to be bought in bulk, sufficient for about 200 tests. As there were no other suspected cases needing testing, the officials decided to send the samples to [[Hong Kong]] instead of buying the reagents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/corona-virus-infection-suspected-in-capital/|title=Corona virus infection suspected in capital|date=2020-01-18|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The samples were sent to Hong Kong on 21 January.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/blood-throat-swab-sent-to-hk-for-diagnosis-2/|title=Blood, throat swab sent to HK for diagnosis|date=2020-01-22|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> On 24 January, the [[Health ministry (Nepal)|Health ministry]] confirmed that the test had come back positive. The ministry said the patient was under surveillance, those who came into close contact with him were being investigated, and health information on all passengers returning from China was being sought.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-nepal-idUSKBN1ZN1S2|title=Nepal confirms first case of new coronavirus|date=2020-01-24|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205163702/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-nepal-idUSKBN1ZN1S2|archive-date=5 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' quoted officials at the Epidemiology and Disease Control Division as saying that no one knew of the patient's activity since he was discharged and that they were looking for him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/01/24/officials-confirm-novel-coronavirus-in-nepali-man-who-returned-from-wuhan-earlier-this-month|title=Officials confirm coronavirus in Nepali man who returned from Wuhan|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Later, they said that they had only spoken to the patient on phone; he had reported being in good health and was not asked to come in for check-up or monitoring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|title=Doctors released two more patients suspected of having coronavirus without waiting for test results|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The patient was confirmed completely treated when [[Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction|RT-PCR]] throat swabs returned negative for [[COVID-19]] in followup assessments of 29 and 31 January.<ref name=paper>{{Cite journal|last=Bastola|first=Anup|last2=Sah|first2=Ranjit|last3=Rodriguez-Morales|first3=Alfonso J.|last4=Lal|first4=Bibek Kumar|last5=Jha|first5=Runa|last6=Ojha|first6=Hemant Chanda|last7=Shrestha|first7=Bikesh|last8=Chu|first8=Daniel K. W.|last9=Poon|first9=Leo L. M.|last10=Costello|first10=Anthony|last11=Morita|first11=Kouichi|date=2020-03-01|title=The first 2019 novel coronavirus case in Nepal|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(20)30067-0/abstract|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|language=English|volume=20|issue=3|pages=279\u2013280|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(20)30067-0|issn=1473-3099|pmid=32057299}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/17/chinese-man-quarantined-with-coronavirus-under-observation-in-kathmandu-officials-confirm|title=Nepali man suspected to have been infected with the new strain of coronavirus discharged|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128151035/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/17/chinese-man-quarantined-with-coronavirus-under-observation-in-kathmandu-officials-confirm|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> None of the people known to have come in contact with the patient showed any symptoms after three weeks of the patient's return to Nepal, and it was therefore presumed that he had not transmitted the disease to anyone else in Nepal.<ref name=two/>\n\nOn 17 January, urged by the WHO, Nepal began screening passengers arriving in [[Tribhuvan International Airport]] from China, Thailand and Japan, the three countries with multiple confirmed cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/sri-lankan-president-thanks-pm-modi-for-saarc-conference-promises-colombos-support-to-combat-covid-1920200316075726/|title=Sri Lankan President thanks PM Modi for SAARC conference; promises Colombo's support to combat COVID-19|website=ANI News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Eight persons manned the health desk. The airport did not have infrared scanners and was therefore using thermal scanners as preparations were being made to install the infrared ones. The passengers who showed fever were being asked to remain in contact and contact the hospitals if they showed additional symptoms.<ref name=thermal>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-has-no-boundaries-says-minister-of-health-and-population-bhanubhakta-dhakal/|title=Coronavirus has no boundaries, says Health Minister Dhakal|date=2020-01-25|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, Dr. Bashudev Pandey, director of Teku Hospital, was quoted as saying that the hospital was on high alert, while three other hospitals \u2013 Nepal Police Hospital, [[Patan Hospital]] and [[Tribhuvan University Teaching Hospital]] \u2013 would also treat the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85487/|title=Nepal is untouched by coronavirus so far, say govt authorities|last=Hyolmo|first=Kunga|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Six beds in Teku Hospital had been allocated for isolation of suspected patients.<ref name=thermal/>\n\nOn 25 January, a day after the first case was confirmed, the Health Ministry informed that two other suspected patients were in [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] at Teku Hospital.<ref name=two>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/25/after-one-confirmed-case-officials-suspect-coronavirus-infection-in-two-more-nepalis|title=Two more coronavirus cases suspected but government agencies are woefully prepared to combat its spread|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201130018/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/25/after-one-confirmed-case-officials-suspect-coronavirus-infection-in-two-more-nepalis|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The hospital discharged them in the morning of 27 January without waiting for test results even though the results were due later that same day, raising concerns over its handling of the crisis. The tests which confirmed a negative result for both patients were conducted at the bio-safety level-2 labs of the National Public Health Laboratory, the first such tests to be performed in Nepal. Reagents sufficient for 100 tests were borrowed from the Centre for Molecular Dynamics and test kits were provided by the World Health Organisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|title=Doctors released two more patients suspected of having coronavirus without waiting for test results|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> A woman was in isolation awaiting test results as of 27 January.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/testing-for-coronavirus-starts-in-nepal/|title=Testing for coronavirus starts in Nepal|date=2020-01-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January, Nepal closed down the [[Rasuwagadhi]] border with China, bringing Nepal-China trade to a complete halt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-hits-nepal-china-trade/|title=Coronavirus hits Nepal-China trade|date=2020-02-03|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Bordering districts of India were reported to be in high alert, and medical personnel had been deployed to various entry points along the Indo-Nepal border.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/news/indo-nepal-border-put-on-high-alert-due-to-corona-virus/videoshow/73683956.cms|title=Indo-Nepal border put on high alert due to corona virus {{!}} News - Times of India Videos|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===February===\nBy the first week of February, Nepal reported a shortage of face masks, as people hurried to buy them following reports of the first confirmed case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/03/nepalis-rush-to-buy-face-masks-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-but-there-are-none-available|title=Nepalis rush to buy face masks amidst coronavirus outbreak but there are none available|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Districts bordering India began setting up health desks at border crossings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86597/|title='Corona health desk' set up in Mahottari|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86513/|title=Corona virus prevention health desk set up at Jamunaha|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Epidemiology and Disease Control Division reported that it had devised its own treatment protocol based on the one developed by UN Health Agency and directed all private hospitals to strictly follow the guidelines in handling any suspected new cases.<ref name=two/> By 1 February, Teku Hospital had handled five suspected cases all of whom tested negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/five-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative|title=Five coronavirus suspects test negative|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 4 February, the Minister for Health informed that three hospitals had been made capable of testing for the virus, and 43 beds had been made available for patients of the possible outbreak. He also informed that health desks had been setup in Pokhara, Chitwan and Bhairahawa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86669/|title=Coronavirus not yet seen in Nepal, government preparing for high alertness|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> On 5 February, Nepal donated 100,000 protective masks to China as a gesture of friendship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-crisis-nepal-donates-100000-masks-to-china.html|title=Coronavirus crisis: Nepal donates 100,000 masks to China \u2013 OnlineKhabar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nA village in [[Sindhupalchok District]] reported hundreds of cases with fever, cough and difficulty breathing, starting on 10 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/government-allays-fear-of-coronavirus-in-sindhupalchowk/|title=Govt allays fear of coronavirus in Sindhupalchowk|date=2020-02-13|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 12 February, the district ruled out the possibility that it could be COVID-19 based on travel history of people in the village.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/87396/|title=Coronavirus infection ruled out in Sindhupalchowk|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/gumba-village-not-affected-by-coronavirus|title=Gumba village not affected by coronavirus|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Laboratory testing later confirmed that the outbreak was influenza but not COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/sindhupalchowk-patients-suffer-from-influenza-test-negative-for-covid-19/|title=Sindhupalchowk patients suffer from influenza, test negative for COVID-19|date=2020-02-17|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nAs of 13 February, Nepal had conducted tests on 19 suspected patients. A [[Saudi Arabia]]n national who only spoke Arabic and appeared to object to being kept in the hospital, fled from isolation, and could not be located. The health ministry said it would start using police to guard suspected patients at the hospital.<ref name=fled>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-suspect-goes-missing/|title=Coronavirus suspect goes missing|date=2020-02-13|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215183546/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-suspect-goes-missing/|archive-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, the government was reported to have devised contingency plans to tackle the virus. Under Plan A, the government was preparing to evacuate Nepali citizens stranded in Hubei and keep them in isolation in Bhaktapur. Plan B included educating the people and distributing protective kits. The details of Plan C which would be implemented in case the disease actually spread and started killing people were not shared.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative/|title=Three coronavirus suspects test negative|date=2020-02-14|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311200934/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative/|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNepal evacuated 175, mostly students, who had been stranded across Hubei,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/17/nasal-throat-swabs-collected-from-nepalis-evacuated-from-china-s-wuhan-tests-to-be-conducted-today|title=Nasal, throat swabs collected from Nepalis evacuated from China's Wuhan; tests to be conducted today|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> on 16 February 2020, using a Nepal Airlines chartered aeroplane<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/na-plane-carrying-175-nepalis-enroute-to-ktm-from-wuhan/|title=NA plane carrying 175 Nepalis enroute to Ktm from Wuhan|date=2020-02-15|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and placed them in a 14-day quarantine at Kharipati in [[Bhaktapur]]. Six other Nepalis were prevented from leaving by the Chinese government, while four of the applicants who had requested rescue later changed their minds. Although 180 Nepalis had applied for immediate evacuation from China by 2 February; the effort took almost two weeks, as the government struggled to meet WHO's evacuation standards, and find a suitable venue for quarantine. The government was criticised for its slow response; a [[Public interest litigation]] was filed at the Supreme Court demanding immediate action,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/pil-filed-against-govt-demanding-nepalis-in-china-be-brought-home/|title=PIL filed against govt demanding Nepalis in China be brought home|date=2020-02-11|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> while the locals around the designated quarantine site in Bhaktapur protested the government's decision which the viewed as endangering to the local community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepalis-in-china-make-frantic-pleas-to-return-home/|title=Nepalis in China make frantic pleas to return home|date=2020-02-08|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/immediately-evacuate-nepalis-from-china-national-human-rights-commission/|title=Immediately evacuate Nepalis from China: NHRC|date=2020-02-10|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/mps-flay-laxity-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-china/|title=MPs flay laxity to evacuate Nepalis from China|date=2020-02-05|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-likely-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-chinas-hubei-on-saturday/|title=Govt likely to evacuate Nepalis from China's Hubei on Saturday|date=2020-02-11|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 19 February, the Health Ministry reported that all of the evacuees had tested negative.<ref name=evac>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88095/|title=Initial tests show Wuhan evacuees free of coronavirus|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88049/|title=175 Nepali nationals evacuated from China tested negative for coronavirus, says MoHP|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February, the Chinese Embassy in Nepal criticised ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' for republishing a ''[[The Korea Herald|Korea Herald]]'' piece critical of China's handling of the pandemic, accusing editor-in-chief Anup Kaphle of anti-China bias. In response, 17 editors from Nepalese mainstream press released a joint statement expressing concern about the singling out of the editor, and reminding the Chinese Embassy of diplomatic norms and constitutionally guaranteed freedom of the Press in Nepal; ''The Kathmandu Post'' published an editorial criticising the Embassy's actions. The Chinese embassy's actions were seen as uncharacteristic and surprising as China is known for non-interference in Nepal's internal matters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/south-asia/article/3051648/nepalese-newspaper-accuses-china-veiled-threats-against-editor|title=Nepalese newspaper accuses China of 'veiled threats against editor'|date=2020-02-20|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/nepal-media-feels-chinas-wrath-in-coronavirus-fallout/|title=Nepal media feels China's wrath in coronavirus fallout|last=Dixit|first=Kunda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/china-cannot-dictate-terms-to-a-free-media-in-nepal-can-pm-oli-resist-analysis/story-F4KTSO7XH5dqcrObjPYtsN.html|title=China cannot dictate terms to a free media in Nepal. Can PM Oli resist?{{!}} Analysis|date=2020-02-26|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of February, the health desk at Tribhuvan International Airport was screening passengers from China, South Korea, Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia, Japan and Saudi Arabia, but did not have sufficient manpower and equipment to screen all new arrivals. A total of six infrared scanners had been setup; the only thermal scanner had yet to be repaired, but plans were underway to purchase three more.<ref name=thtscan>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/samples-collected-for-second-time-from-quarantined-nepalis/|title=Samples collected for second time from quarantined Nepalis|date=2020-03-01|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Passengers were not being asked to fill locator forms that would make it possible to track them down later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/01/as-un-health-agency-raises-covid-19-outbreak-risk-to-the-highest-level-nepal-scrambles-go-step-up-measures|title=As UN health agency raises Covid-19 outbreak risk to the highest level, Nepal scrambles to step up measures|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It was also reported that the government was seeking help from the UN having failed to procure masks and protective gear due to global shortages.<ref name=tkp227/> On 29 February, the government formed a high level committee to prevent and control the spread of COVID-19 under the leadership of Deputy Prime Minister [[Ishwor Pokhrel]].<ref name=thtscan/> The government also decided to suspend promotional activities for Visit Nepal 2020.<ref name=mr31>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89188/|title=Govt urges one and all to avoid public gathering to prevent outbreak of coronavirus|last=Subedi|first=Kamal|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Nepal suspended labour migration to South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/07/as-covid-19-spreads-to-malaysia-and-the-persian-gulf-countries-uncertainty-looms-over-nepal-s-labour-migration|title=As Covid-19 spreads to Malaysia and the Persian Gulf countries, uncertainty looms over Nepal's labour migration|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> India started screening passengers from Nepal and making masks compulsory for all visiting Nepalis.<ref name=tkp227>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/27/as-covid-19-spreads-public-health-officials-consider-plans-for-a-worst-case-scenario|title=As Covid-19 spreads, public health officials consider plans for a worst-case scenario|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It was also screening Nepalis travelling into India by land, at various checkpoints at the border.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88395/|title=India to start screening all air passengers from KTM starting from Monday|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n[[File:20200326 - United Nations in Nepal - CORONA PSA.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:24|Gudelines from the United Nations.]]\n\n'''1 March:''' Nepal announced suspension of [[Visa on arrival|visa-on-arrival]] service for nationals of five countries badly affected by COVID-19 \u2013 China, South Korea, Japan,Italy and Iran \u2013 to be enforced from 7 to 30 March.{{efn|The implementation date was later reported to be 10 March.<ref name=tkp33/>}}<ref name=\"Nepal suspends visa-on-arrival\">{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends visa-on-arrival for nationals of countries badly affected by COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/02/c_138836161.htm |website=Xinhua|accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89193/|title=Nepal announces temporary suspension of visa on arrival from March 7 to prevent coronavirus outbreak|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=tkp32>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/02/all-175-nepalis-evacuated-from-hubei-province-test-negative-for-covid-19|title=All 175 Nepalis evacuated from Hubei Province test negative for Covid-19|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It also urged the general public to avoid large gatherings.<ref name=mr31/> The passengers and crew involved in the evacuation of Nepalis from Hubei were released from quarantine after all tests again came back negative following a two-week quarantine.<ref name=tkp32/>\n\n'''2 March:''' The Supreme Court issued an interim order to suspend flights to and from countries affected by the disease, in response to a public interest litigation. The government issued a travel advisory against non-essential travel to countries hardest hit by the disease, including China, Iran, South Korea, Japan and Italy.<ref name=tkp33>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/03/aviation-authority-urges-government-to-implement-stringent-travel-restrictions|title=Aviation authority urges government to implement stringent travel restrictions|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The visitors coming from or via these countries would be required to submit a health certificate. Health checkpoints were to be established at all major entry points from India and third country citizens would be allowed to cross from select border check-points only. The [[Sagarmatha Sambaad|Sagarmatha Sambad]] programme scheduled for April was also postponed.<ref name=tkp33/>\n\n'''4\u20135 March:''' Due to a severe shortage of face-masks and protective gear as well as increase in price following a ban on export in China and India, some hospitals were reported to be sewing plain clothes masks as a precaution.<ref name=tkp34>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/03/04/hospitals-urge-ministry-to-arrange-for-face-masks-gloves-and-other-protective-gear|title=Hospitals urge ministry to arrange for face masks, gloves and other protective gear|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> A shortage of hand sanitisers was also reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/04/hand-sanitisers-in-short-supply-due-to-buying-rush-sparked-by-outbreak-fears|title=Hand sanitisers in short supply due to buying rush sparked by outbreak fears|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> [[Everest Premier League]], the domestic T20 cricket tournament was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fallout-everest-premier-league-postponed|title=COVID-19 fallout: Everest Premier League postponed|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''8 March:''' Qatar imposed a temporary ban on arrivals from Nepal and other countries, affecting almost 40,000 labour migrants with valid work permits who were yet to leave.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/09/qatar-places-temporary-ban-on-entry-of-people-from-14-countries-including-nepal|title=Thousands of Nepali workers affected as Qatar imposes temporary entry ban amidst Covid-19 outbreak|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Nepal Airlines and Himalaya Airlines suspended their flights to Doha indefinitely following the ban.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/nac-and-himalaya-airlines-suspend-flights-to-doha/|title=NAC and Himalaya Airlines suspend flights to Doha|date=2020-03-11|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''9 March:''' The government expanded the suspension of visa-on-arrival service to include three additional countries \u2014 France, Germany and Spain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89928/|title=Nepal temporarily suspends on-arrival visa for nationals of France, Germany and Spain|last=Subedi|first=Kamal|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''10 March:''' Seventy one Chinese workers employed in the construction of Pokhara Airport who had returned from China after undergoing a 14-day quarantine were put into quarantine for another 14 days. They were being closely monitored and everyone was reported to be in normal health. Previously, 36 Chinese workers working for the project had also gone through a similar quarantine upon return to work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/71-chinese-workers-in-pokhara-quarantined/|title=71 Chinese workers in Pokhara quarantined|date=2020-03-11|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n'''12\u201315 March:''' Nepal decided to suspend on-arrival tourist visa for all countries, with an exception to diplomatic and official visas, to last from 14 March till 30 April. The government closed land border entry points for third country nationals, and cancelled all mountain climbing expeditions including on [[Mount Everest]], to be enforced from 14 March to 30 April. It also declared two-week mandatory self- and home-quarantines for everyone visiting Nepal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends on arrival tourist visa, closes land routes and cancels mountain climbing expeditions |url=https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/12/nepal-government-puts-all-tourist-visas-on-hold-and-cancels-all-spring-climbing-expeditions |website=Kathmandu Post |accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-announces-sweeping-travel-restrictions/|title=Govt announces sweeping travel restrictions|date=2020-03-13|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Labour permits for all countries were suspended indefinitely, including to workers who were only back home on holiday. The government also suspended issuance of no objection letters to students going for abroad study until 30 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/on-arrival-visas-scrapped-till-april-30/|title=On-arrival visas scrapped till April 30|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The [[Province No. 1]] government unveiled plans for two quarantine sites in the province, including one on a [[Koshi River]] island. It also assured plans were underway to provide additional equipment to health personnel, to set up health desks on border-crossings with India, to keep ambulances in standby and to maintain isolation wards in three major hospitals \u2013 [[B.P. Koirala Memorial Cancer Hospital|BP Koirala Institute Of Health Science]] in [[Dharan]], Koshi Hospital in [[Biratnagar]] and Mechi Hospital in [[Jhapa District|Jhapa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/two-quarantine-centres-to-be-established-in-province-1/|title=Two quarantine centres to be established in Province 1|date=2020-03-13|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/28-isolation-wards-prepared-in-province-1/|title=28 isolation wards prepared in Province 1|date=2020-03-05|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> BP Koirala Institute of Health sciences in Dharan reported that a suspected patient had refused to remain in hospital and returned home. He had promised to return the following day for testing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/14/man-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-refuses-to-stay-in-isolation-ward-and-returns-home|title=Man suspected of having coronavirus refuses to stay in isolation ward and returns home|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The same day, Bihar transport department suspended Patna-Nepal bus services with immediate effect, to be enforced until 31 March, in an effort to contain the virus, after many cases emerged throughout India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/15/operation-of-patna-nepal-buses-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak-2116837.html|title=Operation of Patna-Nepal buses postponed due to coronavirus outbreak|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> India declared a suspension of all passenger movement through Indo-Nepal border, except a few designated checkpoints \u2013 Banbasa, Raxaul, Ranigunj and Sunauli<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90832/|title=Govt mulls complete closure of border with India|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> \u2013 with intensified health inspections, effective from 15 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/coronavirus-passenger-movements-through-pak-bdesh-nepal-bhutan-myanmar-border-points-suspended-55426|title=Coronavirus: Passenger movements through Pak, B'desh, Nepal, Bhutan, Myanmar border points suspended|last=Tribune News Service |website=Tribuneindia News Service |access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The land-border checkpoints with China began releasing imported goods following quarantine procedures as cases in China began to drop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/containers-stalled-at-rasuwagadi-start-entering-nepal/|title=Containers stalled at Rasuwagadi start entering Nepal|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi proposed starting the COVID-19 Emergency Fund for the SAARC region; he also said India could share a Disease Surveillance Software with SAARC partners, and hinted at the possibility of conducting coordinated research on controlling epidemic diseases in the SAARC region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90492/|title=Indian PM Modi proposes COVID-19 Emergency Fund to combat coronavirus in South Asia|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''17 March:''' A meeting of the high-level coordination committee for prevention and control of COVID-19 decided to add 115 ICU and 1,000 isolation beds in the Kathmandu Valley. It also instructed the provincial governments to setup a total of 120 ICU beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90596/|title=Govt to set up 235 ICU beds amid coronavirus fears|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''18\u201319 March:''' The government declared suspension of all classes<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90755/|title=Govt takes sweeping measures to contain spread of COVID-19|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and postponement of all academic examinations including the [[Secondary Education Examination (Nepal)|Secondary Education Examination]] until 12 April, the end of the Month of [[Chaitra]], the last month of Nepali calendar year when all schools hold the [[final examination]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/govt-postpones-all-examinations-till-12-april|title=Govt postpones all examinations till 12 April|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Tribhuvan University and the Public Service Commission also postponed all their examinations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90797/|title=Amid COVID-19 fears, PSC halts scheduled exams until further notice|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The government banned all passengers, including Nepalis, from EU and the UK, West Asia and the Middle East as well as Malaysia, South Korea and Japan, effective from 20 March until 15 April. It also decided to shut down all cinema halls, gymnasiums,museums and cultural centres, and ban gathering of more than 25 people in any public spaces including at places of worship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/18/government-bans-entry-of-all-passengers|title=Government bans entry of all passengers, including Nepalis, from midnight March 20|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Nepal began to see a significant influx of people from India to Nepal as India saw increase in new cases throughout the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/sudurpaschim-province/2020/03/18/amid-covid-19-threat-banbasa-border-sees-a-sudden-influx-of-people-returning-home-from-india|title=Amid Covid-19 threat, Banbasa border sees a sudden influx of people returning home from India|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> A noticeable outflux of people from the Kathmandu Valley was reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/number-of-people-leaving-kathmandu-valley-increases/|title=Number of people leaving Kathmandu Valley increases|date=2020-03-19|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The House of Representatives meeting was postponed until 26 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/govts-measures-to-fight-covid-19-inadequate-say-mps/|title=Govt's measures to fight COVID-19 inadequate, say MPs|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Province No. 1 government established quarantine centres throughout the province with a total capacity of 440 beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/440-bed-quarantine-centres-in-province-1/|title=440-bed quarantine centres in Province 1|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20200320 - UNDP Nepal - How to protect yourself from Coronavirus.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:02|The actress [[Rekha Thapa]] spreading precaution measures.]]\n\n'''20 March:''' The National Assembly was suspended indefinitely.<ref name=mr319>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90872/|title=National Assembly put off until further notice|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Health Ministry instructed public employees to report on weekends as well, and not leave the Kathmandu Valley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/health-ministry-bars-employees-from-leaving-kathmandu-valley|title=Health ministry bars employees from leaving Kathmandu valley|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> All weekly newspapers published from the Kathmandu Valley ceased their print editions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90891/|title=COVID-19 fear: Weekly newspapers from Kathmandu cease their print version|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The US government pledged $1.8&nbsp;million to Nepal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/us-government-pledges-1-8-million/|title=US government pledges $1.8&nbsp;million|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Prime Minister Oli addressed the nation for the first time since the start of the pandemic and announced a list of preventative measures. All international flights would be stopped from 22 March to 31 March and vehicular movement on long routes would be closed from 23 March. All government services and private offices except those providing essential services would be closed until 3 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-southasia-idUSKBN217117|title=Sri Lanka imposes curfew as South Asia steps up coronavirus battle|date=2020-03-20|agency=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0926\u0947\u0936\u092d\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092f\u093e\u0924\u093e\u092f\u093e\u0924 \u092c\u0928\u094d\u0926, \u092d\u093e\u0930\u0924\u0940\u092f \u0938\u0940\u092e\u093e \u0928\u093e\u0915\u093e \u0916\u0941\u0932\u094d\u0932\u093e !036 |url=https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846036 |website=Onlinekhabar |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=ne |trans-title=Indian border crossing open, traffic closed within country}}</ref> A notice from Nepal Tourism Board announced the suspension of issuance of trekking permits for tourists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends issuance of trekking permits for foreign trekkers |url=http://www.china.org.cn/world/Off_the_Wire/2020-03/20/content_75840039.htm |website=China.org.cn |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> The outflux of people from the Kathmandu Valley intensified; almost 300,000 people had left in the preceding three days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/people-leaving-kathmandu-on-the-rise-photo-feature|title=People leaving Kathmandu on the rise (Photo Feature)|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Health Ministry decided to halt non-urgent health check-ups and surgeries until 12 April in hospitals in the Kathmandu Valley with 50 or more beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/miscellany/big-hospitals-to-stop-non-urgent-health-check-up-surgeries|title=Big hospitals to stop non-urgent health check-up, surgeries|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> A full bench meeting of the Supreme Court presided over by the Chief Justice decided to halt all non-urgent proceedings in courts across the country until 4 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/supreme-court-to-halt-non-urgent-proceedings/|title=Supreme Court to halt non-urgent proceedings|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90877/|title=Courts across the country to be closed for two weeks|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Nepal government pledged Rs 100 Million to the [[SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90907/|title=Nepal to contribute Rs 100 million to SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''21 March:''' Kathmandu city launched a central help desk and a toll-free 24-hour hotline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/dial-1180-in-case-of-covid-19-suspicion-kmc/|title=Dial 1180 in case of COVID-19 suspicion: KMC|date=2020-03-22|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Germany pledged an additional one million Euros to its existing health programmes in Nepal to help combat the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/german-aid-to-nepal/|title=German aid to Nepal|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Around sixty passengers from COVID-19 affected countries that landed on Tribhuvan Interantional Airport were sent to quarantine at Kharipati, Bhaktapur; they had not presented any symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/63-people-sent-to-kharipati-quarantine|title=63 people sent to Kharipati Quarantine|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It was reported that Gandaki Province had set up 111 isolation beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/111-isolation-beds-in-gandaki-province|title=111 isolation beds in Gandaki province|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Metropolitan Traffic Police Division suspended breathalyser tests as well as educational classes for drivers found breaking traffic rules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/police-put-off-drink-and-drive-operation|title=Police put off 'drink and drive' operation|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It also deployed 200 of its personnel to display placards with awareness messages about the disease by the roadside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/traffic-police-generate-awareness-about-covid-19|title=Traffic police generate awareness about Covid-19|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> [[Nepal Police]] established coronavirus response units in all its stations and decided not to make arrests for minor offences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/21/police-set-up-coronavirus-response-unit-at-every-station|title=Police set up coronavirus response unit at every station|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Health Ministry informed that private hospitals with more than 100 beds would not be allowed to refer patients to other hospitals; they were required to treat suspected patients, wait for test results and provide free treatment if the disease were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/21/158475695256349344.html|title=\u0938\u092f \u092c\u0947\u0921\u092e\u093e\u0925\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0905\u0938\u094d\u092a\u0924\u093e\u0932\u0932\u0947 \u092c\u093f\u0930\u093e\u092e\u0940 \u0930\u0947\u092b\u0930 \u0917\u0930\u094d\u0928 \u0928\u092a\u093e\u0909\u0928\u0947 |website=ekantipur.com |language=ne|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''22 March:''' Nepal decided to close its land border with India and China for a week effective from 23 March. The government also declared a Rs 500 million fund with contributions of a month's salary from government ministers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/22/government-to-close-down-border-with-india-and-china-for-a-week|title=Government to close down border with India and China for a week|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It also increased the allowances for health workers working at the front desks of hospitals by 50\u2013100%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846585 |title=\u0938\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0938\u094d\u0925\u094d\u092f\u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0932\u093e\u0908 \u092a\u0940\u092a\u0940\u0908 \u0930 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u094b\u0924\u094d\u0938\u093e\u0939\u0928 \u092d\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093e \u0926\u093f\u0928\u0947 \u0928\u093f\u0930\u094d\u0923\u092f |work=onlinekhabar.com |access-date=22 March 2020 |language=ne}}</ref> [[Kanchanpur District|Kanchanpur]] and [[Banke District]]s declared lockdowns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/kanchanpur-nepalgunj-under-indefinite-lockdown/|title=Kanchanpur, Nepalgunj under indefinite lockdown|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''23 March:''' COVID-19 was confirmed in a 19-year-old woman who had returned from France on 17 March via Qatar, the first case in two months, second overall. She was admitted into isolation at Teku Hospital. Her family is said to be in quarantine at home.<ref>{{cite web |title=One imported case of coronavirus confirmed in Nepal |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/ |website=The Himalayan Times |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> The Office of the attorney General was reported to have asked the Police to release people held for minor crimes under bail or parole to reduce crowding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/opinion/editorial-inadequate-testing/|title=EDITORIAL: Inadequate testing|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Minister of Health declared that all patients of COVID-19 would be rescued as necessary and provided free treatment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/govt-will-rescue-provide-free-treatment-to-infected-people-health-minister-dhakal|title=Govt will rescue, provide free treatment to infected people: Health minister Dhakal|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> [[Kailali District]] was reported to have declared an indefinite lock-down effective from 2&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/91136/|title=Curfew clamped in Kailali to prevent COVID-19|last=RSS|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> [[Arghakhanchi District]] also declared an indefinite lock-down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/arghakhanchi-district-to-be-locked-down-from-midnight|title=Arghakhanchi district to be locked down from midnight|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''24 March:''' The country-wide lockdown came into effect.<ref name=four/>\n\n'''25 March:''' The third case in Kathmandu was confirmed. The patient had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates and was staying in a hotel in Kathmandu. They are being treated in Teku Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Third person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|date=2020-03-25|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n'''26 March:''' Rescue of tourists stranded throughout Nepal was initiated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/more-stranded-tourists-evacuated-from-nepal/|title=More stranded tourists evacuated from Nepal|last=Times|first=Nepali|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> By 28 March, hundreds of tourists had been rescued and brought to Kathmandu; many were being repatriated via chartered flights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/rescue-flights-continue-on-saturday/|title=Rescue flights continue on Saturday|date=2020-03-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n'''27 March:''' Fourth case nationally, the first outside Kathmandu, was confirmed. It involved a 34-year-old man who had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates. He is being treated at Seti Provincial Hospital in Dhangadhi.<ref name=four>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/27/fourth-nepali-tests-positive-for-covid-19-case|title=Fourth Nepali tests positive for Covid-19|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n'''28 March:''' A 19-year-old woman who had recently travelled to Kathmandu from Belgium via Doha tested positive, bringing the total to five in the country. She had shared a flight from Doha with the patient who was confirmed on 23 March. She had since travelled to her home in Baglung; she was admitted for treatment at Dhaulagiri Zonal Hospital after the test came back positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fifth-patient-moved-freely-in-her-village-for-5-days-got-admitted-to-dhaulagiri-hospital-7-hours-after-being-confirmed|title=COVID-19 fifth patient moved freely in her village for 5 days, got admitted to Dhaulagiri hospital 7 hours after being confirmed !|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Fifth person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|date=2020-03-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n'''29 March:''' The government decided to extend the suspension of international flights to until 15 April. The country-wide lockdown was extended to until 8 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/29/nationwide-lockdown-extended-until-april-8-ban-on-international-flights-until-april-15|title=Nationwide lockdown extended until April 8, ban on international flights until April 15|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n'''2 April:''' A 65-year-old woman who recently travelled to Kathmandu from Belgium who accompanied the 19-year-old woman on 17 March tested positive bringing the total to six in the country. confirmed that she was staying at her home in Baglung. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-more-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-nepals-sixth-confirmed-case/|title=One more person tests positive for Covid-19, Nepal\u2019s sixth confirmed case|website=himalayantimes.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/04/02/health-ministry-confirms-sixth-covid-19-case|title=Health Ministry confirms sixth Covid-19 case|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Impact and response==\nThe tourism sector has been reported to be suffering due to the absence of Chinese tourists, as well as the various travel restrictions imposed on travel globally. Manufacturing sector is experiencing a shortage of raw materials, most of which used to come from China. The situation is exacerbated by spread of the pandemic to the Middle-east which is the main source of remittance that makes up more than half of Nepal's [[GDP]]. Remittances were expected to sharply drop after Nepal suspended issuance of workers permit to Nepalis for all countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/15/nepal-s-remittance-dependent-economy-braces-for-upheaval-amid-covid-19-pandemic|title=Nepal's remittance-dependent economy braces for upheaval amid Covid-19 pandemic|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The wholesale and retail sector has also been affected due to fall of imports from China. The construction sector which imports most of its building materials from China has slowed down. As the Chinese contractors and workers who went home for the Chinese new year could not return, the public construction projects have also been affected.<ref name=econ>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/04/nepali-economy-starts-to-feel-the-pinch-as-coronavirus-spreads|title=Nepali economy starts to feel the pinch as coronavirus spreads|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/48830-coronavirus-chills-nepal-infrastructure-construction?v=preview|title=Coronavirus Chills Nepal Infrastructure Construction|website=www.enr.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-outbreak-could-shave-off-nepals-economy-by-36-78-million/|title=Coronavirus outbreak could shave off Nepal's economy by $36.78&nbsp;million|date=2020-03-07|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The domestic airlines were reported to be struggling for survival as ticket prices dropped to half or a third of normal following a sharp decline in demand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/11/domestic-airfares-hit-rock-bottom-amidst-coronavirus-travel-advisory|title=Domestic airfares hit rock bottom amidst coronavirus travel advisory|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Number of international flights to and from Nepal had decreased by more than 50% by 13 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/international-flights-drop-significantly-at-tia/|title=International flights drop significantly at TIA|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Nepal's import-dependent economy is also vulnerable to depreciation of Indian currency to which its currency is permanently pegged, as Indian economy suffers the impact of the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/weakening-nepali-currency-to-hit-economy/|title=Weakening Nepali currency to hit economy|date=2020-03-12|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> 20,000 tour, trek and mountaineering guides lost their livelihood when mountaineering was suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/14/suspension-of-climbing-permits-and-on-arrival-visas-entails-losses-of-thousands-of-jobs-and-millions-of-dollars|title=Suspension of climbing permits and on-arrival visas entails losses of thousands of jobs and millions of dollars|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/18/experts-call-for-measures-to-ease-the-impact-of-coronavirus-on-the-economy|title=Experts call for measures to ease the impact of coronavirus on the economy|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nThe annual [[Holi]] celebrations, which fell on 9 and 10 March in 2020 saw decreased activities, low business and cancellation of organised celebrations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-scare-dampens-holi-spirit-businesses-hit/|title=Coronavirus scare dampens Holi spirit, businesses hit|date=2020-03-10|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\nNepal had declared 2020 as the Visit Nepal Year and aimed to bring in two million foreign tourists, almost double the figure from previous year. As the pandemic spread and Nepal had to suspend air travel to and from China, the biggest source of international tourists arriving by air, Nepal suspended its promotional campaigns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/01/c_138831984.htm|title=Nepal postpones int'l tourism promotion amid coronavirus outbreak - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nThe temporary blanket ban on animal markets imposed by China as a response to the pandemic is expected to curb wildlife poaching and trafficking through Nepal, as the Chinese traditional medicine which uses various body parts of endangered animals as its ingredients has been the biggest challenge to wildlife conservation in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/banner/coronavirus-outbreak-may-curb-wildlife-trafficking/|title=Coronavirus outbreak may curb wildlife trafficking|last=Awale|first=Sonia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211183345/https://www.nepalitimes.com/banner/coronavirus-outbreak-may-curb-wildlife-trafficking/|archive-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Market regulation===\nThe department of Commerce, Supplies and Consumer Protection conducted raids on 161 firms and fined 57 of them, a total of around four million Rupees in the month of [[Falgun]] (February\u2013March).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/20/government-launches-coordinated-inspections-to-curb-black-marketeering-of-essential-goods|title=Government launches coordinated inspections to curb black marketeering of essential goods|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It inspected multiple pharmacies and surgical shops in Kathmandu on 5 March and fined a total of Rs 430,000 for hiking prices and other offences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/05/government-cracks-down-on-price-gouging-by-pharmacies-and-surgical-shops|title=Government cracks down on price-gouging by pharmacies and surgical shops|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 10 March, four pharmacies were fined a total of Rs 800,000 after they were caught charging 1000% of normal price for surgical masks. Some groceries and LPG stores were also inspected. One million units of face masks were confiscated from a warehouse in Kathmandu and the owner arrested on 18 March, bringing the total of masks confiscated in the week past to 2.3&nbsp;million. Around 50,000 units of hand-sanitisers were also confiscated from the black market. Around two dozen black marketeers had been arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/police-seize-one-million-masks/|title=Police seize one million masks|date=2020-03-19|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> As the outflux of people from Kathmandu intensified, 23 transport entrepreneurs and workers were arrested on 20 March for overcharging the passengers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/23-persons-held-for-fleecing-passengers/|title=23 persons held for fleecing passengers|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Essential drugs===\nNepal's pharmaceutical industry has been impacted due to lack of raw materials as a number of essential ingredients were previously imported from Hubei.<ref name=econ/> Nepal faced the prospect of a potential shortage of essential medicines when India imposed restrictions on export of 26 types of raw materials including of essential medicine citing disruption in the supply chain from Hubei; however India later agreed to relax restrictions in case of Nepal, and asked the Nepalese government to provide a list of names and quantities of essential medicines that it needed to supply to Nepal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/india-seeks-list-of-essential-drugs-that-nepal-needs/|title=India seeks list of essential drugs that Nepal needs|date=2020-03-06|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307141100/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/india-seeks-list-of-essential-drugs-that-nepal-needs/|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation===\nOn 21 March a 20-year-old man was arrested on charges of spreading misinformation online through an unregistered [[fake news website]] and causing public fear, after audio tapes alleging cover-up of COVID-19 cases were found circulating online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/youth-arrested-for-spreading-romours-of-covid-19-cases/|title=Youth arrested for spreading romours of COVID-19 cases|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The same day, [[Nepal Army]] dispelled rumours circulating in social media that claimed Army helicopters were being used to spray disinfectants over settlements at midnight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/army-dismisses-helicopter-spraying-disifectant-at-midnight-rumours/|title=Army dismisses 'helicopter spraying disinfectant at midnight' rumours|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Nepal|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Nepal]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Nepal]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Nepal]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{short description|COVID-19 disease pandemic in Nepal}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal\n| map1            = Nepal COVID-19 outbreak map (29 March 2020).svg\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in Nepal (as of 29 March) {{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = Nepal\n| first_case      = [[Kathmandu District]]\n| arrival_date    = 5 January 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 6\n| recovery_cases  = 1\n| active_cases    = 5\n| deaths          = 0\n| territories     = [[Kathmandu District|Kathmandu]], [[Kailali District|Kailali]], [[Baglung District|Baglung]]\n| website         = {{official|url=https://heoc.mohp.gov.np/|name=Health Emergency Operation Centre (HEOC)}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global COVID-19 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to Nepal when its first case was confirmed in Kathmandu on 24 January 2020. The patient only showed mild symptoms and had been discharged a week earlier with instructions to self-quarantine at home; he was subsequently confirmed to have completely recovered. Between January and March, Nepal took steps to prevent a widespread outbreak of the disease, while preparing for it by procuring essential supplies, equipment and medicine, upgrading health infrastructure, training medical personnel, and spreading public awareness. The second case was confirmed on 23 March 2020. {{As of|2020|03|29}}, three additional cases have been confirmed, including one each in Kailali and Baglung districts. All five confirmed cases have been in people who had recently returned from abroad. The four patients under treatment are reported to be in \"normal\" condition. A country-wide lockdown came into effect on 24 March, and is scheduled to end on 8 April.\n\nNepal established health-desks at the international airport as well as on border checkpoints with India, starting in mid-January. Land borders with India as well as China were later completely sealed off, and all international flights suspended. All academic examinations were cancelled, and schools and colleges were closed. Quarantine centres and temporary hospitals are being setup across the country. Laboratory facilities are being upgraded and expanded. Hospitals have been setting up [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] units and [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] beds. The [[SAARC]] countries have pledged to cooperate in controlling the disease in the region. India, the United States and Germany have increased their support to Nepali health sector.\n\nNepal cancelled its international promotional activities related to ''Visit Nepal Year 2020''. Its economy is expected to be severely affected by the pandemic due its impact on foreign employment, tourism, manufacturing, construction and trade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/govt-to-carry-out-impact-assessment-of-coronavirus-on-economy/|title=Govt to carry out impact assessment of coronavirus on economy|date=2020-03-06|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n===COVID-19 pandemic===\nThe ongoing [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) is caused by <!--NO DEFINITE ARTICLE (\"THE\") AS PER VIRUS'S ARTICLE--> [[SARS-COV-2|severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2).<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 |url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> The outbreak was first identified in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei, China]], in December 2019 and recognised as a pandemic by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) on 11 March 2020.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020|title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11 March 2020|date=11 March 2020|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|3|29}}, more than 708,000 cases of COVID-19 have been reported in over 190 countries and territories, resulting in approximately 33,500 deaths.<ref name=\"WOM\" /> More than 150,000 people have since recovered.<ref name=\"WOM\" >{{cite web |url= https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus Update (Live) |work=Worldometer |date=2020 |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"JHU CSSE2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases|publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]]|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe virus primarily [[Transmission (medicine)|spreads]] between people in a way similar to [[influenza]], via [[respiratory droplets]] from coughing or sneezing.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url= https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/getting-workplace-ready-for-covid-19.pdf |title=Getting your workplace ready for COVID-19 |date=27 February 2020 |work=World Health Organization |url-status=live}}</ref><!--Quote=In other words, COVID-19 spreads in a similar way to flu--><ref name=\"WHO2020QA\">{{cite web |url= https://www.who.int/news-room/q-a-detail/q-a-coronaviruses |title=Q&A on coronaviruses |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |work=WHO.int |date=11 February 2020 |access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref><!--Quote=The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing.--><ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\">{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/symptoms.html |title=Symptoms of Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |date=10 February 2020 |work=CDC.gov |publisher=US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]) |access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n<!--Quote=The virus is thought to spread mainly from person-to-person&nbsp;.... Via respiratory droplets produced when an infected person coughs or sneezes.-->The time between [[Incubation period|exposure and symptom onset]] is typically five days, but may range from two to fourteen days.<ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{cite journal |last1=Rothan |first=H. A. |last2=Byrareddy |first2=S. N. |title=The epidemiology and pathogenesis of coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak |journal=Journal of Autoimmunity |page=102433 |date=February 2020 |pmid=32113704 |doi=10.1016/j.jaut.2020.102433 |url= http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896841120300469}}</ref> Symptoms are most often fever, dry cough, and shortness of breath.<ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Complications may include [[pneumonia]] and [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]]. There is no [[vaccine]] or specific [[antiviral treatment]], but research is ongoing. Efforts are aimed at managing symptoms and [[supportive therapy]].<!-- Quote=There is currently no vaccine to prevent coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19)&nbsp;.... There is no specific antiviral treatment recommended for COVID-19 --> Recommended preventive measures include [[handwashing]], covering the mouth when coughing, [[Social distancing|maintaining distance from other people]] (particularly those who are unwell), and monitoring and [[self-isolation]] for fourteen days for people who suspect they are infected.<ref name=\"WHO2020QA\" /><ref name=\"CDC2020Over222\" /><ref name=CDC2020SocialSpacing>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url= https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/specific-groups/high-risk-complications.html |work=CDC.gov |publisher=US [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |access-date=9 March 2020 |date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\nNepal is a landlocked country with China in the northern side and India in the east, west and south. Nepal shares a {{convert|1414|km|mi}} border with China's autonomous region of Tibet, in the Himalayas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85919/|title=Nepal-China Rasuwagadhi border point to be sealed for 15 days from Wednesday|last=DEVKOTA|first=HIMNATH|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> China is Nepal's second-largest trading partner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2015/09/09/nepal-has-trade-surplus-with-32-countries|title=Nepal has trade surplus with 32 countries|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Nepal has an 1,800-km open border with India in the east, west and south. Nepal lies in South Asia, one of the least developed and most densely populated world regions, that performs poorly in education as well as health care and sanitation metrics, and is therefore considered one of the highest risk areas for the pandemic, and also one of the least prepared.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ranks-111th-in-health-security-index/|title=Nepal ranks 111th in health security index|date=2020-02-08|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/28/south-asia-prepared-wuhan-virus-china-nepal-india-health/|title=Is South Asia Prepared for the Wuhan Virus?|last=Salam|first=Ravi Agrawal, Kathryn|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref name=tht116>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-vulnerable-to-new-china-virus-warn-doctors/|title=Nepal vulnerable to new China virus, warn doctors|date=2020-01-16|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/26/21150529/italy-coronavirus-south-korea|title=How to travel during the international coronavirus outbreak|last=Belluz|first=Julia|date=2020-02-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepal-ill-prepared-for-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Nepal ill-prepared for coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-02-26|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'', before the pandemic, hospitals in Nepal had few ICU beds (just three in Teku Hospital) which were almost always occupied, with people in critical condition usually having to wait for the beds to become empty. It reported doctors as saying that it would be next to impossible to admit new patients to ICU as soon as they need them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/12/nepal-s-hospitals-have-no-icus-to-treat-coronavirus-patients-doctors-say|title=Nepal's hospitals have no ICUs to treat coronavirus patients, doctors say|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Teku Hospital, the only one designated for handling infectious disease, had built an isolation ward during the [[avian influenza]] outbreak a decade ago, but had never brought it into use, as it did not have experts to evaluate or maintain the required standards.<ref name=two/>\n\nAs news of a new infectious disease in China broke, concerns were raised in Nepal over the high potential risk, the need to implement preventive measures and a severe lack of necessary medical equipment and infrastructure. According to Baburam Marasini, former director of [[Epidemiology and Disease Control Division]], Nepal does not have any double cab ambulances to transport highly infectious patients safely, isolation wards in hospitals, or biosafety level-3 or better laboratories needed to test for highly infectious diseases.<ref name=tht116/>\n\n==Epidemiological overview==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatright\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n{{nowrap|Confirmed COVID-19 cases in Nepal by district}}\n! rowspan=2; |District\n! rowspan=2; |Cases\n! colspan=2; |Recovered\n! colspan=2; |Deaths\n|-\n! #\n! %\n! #\n! %\n|-\n!Baglung\n|'''2'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|-\n!Kailali\n|'''1'''\n|0\n|0%\n|0\n|0%\n|-\n!Kathmandu\n|'''3'''\n|1\n|33%\n|0\n|0%\n|-\n!Total\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''6'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''1'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''16.67%'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''0'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''0%'''\n|}\nAs of 29 March 2020, Nepal has confirmed five cases of COVID-19 disease, all of them in persons who had recently returned from abroad. The first case was confirmed on 24 January in a 32-year-old man who had recently returned from China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=India Times |first1=The Economic Times |title=Nepal confirms first case of deadly coronavirus |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms |accessdate=Jan 24, 2020 |publisher=The Economic Times}}</ref> The patient had shown mild symptoms, and was completely cured by the end of January.<ref name=paper/> The second case was confirmed on 23 March in a 19-year-old woman who had recently returned from France via Qatar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/|title=One imported case of coronavirus confirmed in Nepal|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> She is being treated in Teku hospital, Kathmandu. Her family has been put in quarantine at home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/23/15849466024353731.html|title=Second confirmed case of covid-19 in Nepal|url-status=live|language=ne}}</ref> The third case was confirmed on 25 March, in a person who had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Third person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The fourth case, the first outside Kathmandu, was confirmed on 27 March, in a 34-year-old man who had recently returned from the Middle East. He is being treated in Seti Provincial Hospital in [[Dhangadhi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fourth-covid-19-positive-case-confirmed-by-health-ministry/|title=Fourth case of Covid-19 in Nepal|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The fifth case was confirmed in Baglung on 28 March, in a 19-year-old woman who had returned from Belgium via Qatar. She had shared a flight from Doha to Kathmandu with the patient who was confirmed on 23 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Fifth case of covid-19 cofirmed in Nepal|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> All four patients undergoing treatment are reported to be in \"normal\" condition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/166VA-CyCkujymP6NhdViM6EcjP95MKwy/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=SitRep#49_COVID-19_29-03-2020_NP.pdf|website=Google Docs|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nSukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital is the designated primary hospital for the treatment of COVID-19. A temporary hospital, named Bharatpur Corona Special Hospital, has been established in Chitwan District. [[Nepal Public Health Laboratory]] in Kathmandu was the only laboratory capable of testing for the disease {{as of|lc=y|2020|03|15}}; it was capable of conducting 500 tests a week and had a stock of 1,000 viral transport media (VTM) kits for transporting samples to be tested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/stock-of-kits-to-transport-coronavirus-samples-limited/|title=Stock of kits to transport coronavirus samples limited|date=2020-03-16|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/03/12/central-laboratory-is-equipped-to-test-500-covid-19-cases-a-week-but-that-is-far-too-low-say-public-health-experts|title=Central laboratory is equipped to test 500 Covid-19 cases a week, but that is far too low, say public health experts|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It had conducted a total of 917 tests {{as of|2020|03|29|lc=y}}.{{efn|The actual number of individuals tested is thought to be much lower.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/22/test-test-test-says-who-but-nepal-has-neither-the-means-nor-the-matter|title=Test, test, test, says WHO but Nepal has neither the means nor the matter|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heoc.mohp.gov.np/|title=Health Emergency Operation Center \u2013 Health Emergency Operation Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===Nepalis abroad===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatright\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\n{{nowrap|COVID-19 cases in Nepalis abroad}}\n! Country/Territory\n! Cases\n! Deaths\n|-\n!Australia\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!Bahrain\n|3\n|0\n|-\n!Portugal\n|1\n|0\n|-\n!United Arab Emirates\n|2\n|0\n|-\n!United Kingdom\n|1\n|1\n|-\n!United States\n|1\n|1\n|-\n!Total\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''9'''\n!style=\"text-align:right\"|'''2'''\n|}\nA Nepali student who had recently reached [[Tasmania]] via Singapore tested positive for COVID-19 on 8 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepali-in-australia-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/|title=Nepali in Australia tests positive for coronavirus|date=2020-03-09|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> On 9 March, the UAE's Health Ministry confirmed that two Nepalis in the country had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/two-nepalis-test-positive-for-coronavirus-in-uae/|title=Two Nepalis test positive for coronavirus in UAE|date=2020-03-10|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> On 16 March, it was reported that seventy four Nepali migrant workers were put into 14-day quarantine in Faro City, Portugal, after one of them tested positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/74-nepalis-quarantined-in-portugal/|title=74 Nepalis quarantined in Portugal|date=2020-03-17|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Later, it was reported that only three of the quarantined were Nepalis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/miscellany/three-nepalis-in-quarantine-in-portugal-for-covid-19|title=Three Nepalis in quarantine in Portugal for COVID-19|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Three Nepalis tested positive in Bahrain, two of them on 21 March and one on 22 March; three more were put into 14-day quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-nepalis-contract-covid-19/|title=Three nepalis contract covid-19|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nA 66-year-old former [[British Gorkha|British Gurkha]] soldier of Nepali origin died from COVID-19 in the United Kingdom on 17 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/elderly-nepali-origin-man-dies-of-virus-in-uk/|title=Elderly Nepali-origin man dies of virus in UK|date=2020-03-22|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> A 50-year-old man of Nepali origin died of the disease in the United States on 24 March.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/25/uber-driver-who-stopped-working-to-avoid-coronavirus-dies-from-disease/ |title = Uber driver who stopped working to avoid coronavirus dies from disease|date = 25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===January===\nA 31-year-old student of [[Wuhan University of Technology|Wuhan University]] who had returned home on 5 January,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/nepal-confirms-first-case-of-deadly-coronavirus/articleshow/73590302.cms|title=Nepal confirms first case of deadly coronavirus|date=2020-01-24|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> was admitted with mild symptoms on 13 January and discharged on 17 January with instructions to self-quarantine at home after preliminary tests showed he may not be infected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-test-on-china-returnee-shows-negative-result.html|title=Coronavirus test on China returnee shows negative result \u2013 OnlineKhabar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Although Nepal had the laboratories and the skilled manpower to test for the disease, Nepal did not have the [[reagent]]s required. The reagents cost around [[Nepalese rupee|Rs]] 17,000 per test and need to be bought in bulk, sufficient for about 200 tests. As there were no other suspected cases needing testing, the officials decided to send the samples to [[Hong Kong]] instead of buying the reagents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/corona-virus-infection-suspected-in-capital/|title=Corona virus infection suspected in capital|date=2020-01-18|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The samples were sent to Hong Kong on 21 January.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/blood-throat-swab-sent-to-hk-for-diagnosis-2/|title=Blood, throat swab sent to HK for diagnosis|date=2020-01-22|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> On 24 January, the [[Health ministry (Nepal)|Health ministry]] confirmed that the test had come back positive. The ministry said the patient was under surveillance, those who came into close contact with him were being investigated, and health information on all passengers returning from China was being sought.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-nepal-idUSKBN1ZN1S2|title=Nepal confirms first case of new coronavirus|date=2020-01-24|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205163702/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-nepal-idUSKBN1ZN1S2|archive-date=5 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' quoted officials at the Epidemiology and Disease Control Division as saying that no one knew of the patient's activity since he was discharged and that they were looking for him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/01/24/officials-confirm-novel-coronavirus-in-nepali-man-who-returned-from-wuhan-earlier-this-month|title=Officials confirm coronavirus in Nepali man who returned from Wuhan|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Later, they said that they had only spoken to the patient on phone; he had reported being in good health and was not asked to come in for check-up or monitoring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|title=Doctors released two more patients suspected of having coronavirus without waiting for test results|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The patient was confirmed completely treated when [[Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction|RT-PCR]] throat swabs returned negative for [[COVID-19]] in followup assessments of 29 and 31 January.<ref name=paper>{{Cite journal|last=Bastola|first=Anup|last2=Sah|first2=Ranjit|last3=Rodriguez-Morales|first3=Alfonso J.|last4=Lal|first4=Bibek Kumar|last5=Jha|first5=Runa|last6=Ojha|first6=Hemant Chanda|last7=Shrestha|first7=Bikesh|last8=Chu|first8=Daniel K. W.|last9=Poon|first9=Leo L. M.|last10=Costello|first10=Anthony|last11=Morita|first11=Kouichi|date=2020-03-01|title=The first 2019 novel coronavirus case in Nepal|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(20)30067-0/abstract|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|language=English|volume=20|issue=3|pages=279\u2013280|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(20)30067-0|issn=1473-3099|pmid=32057299}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/17/chinese-man-quarantined-with-coronavirus-under-observation-in-kathmandu-officials-confirm|title=Nepali man suspected to have been infected with the new strain of coronavirus discharged|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128151035/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/17/chinese-man-quarantined-with-coronavirus-under-observation-in-kathmandu-officials-confirm|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> None of the people known to have come in contact with the patient showed any symptoms after three weeks of the patient's return to Nepal, and it was therefore presumed that he had not transmitted the disease to anyone else in Nepal.<ref name=two/>\n\nOn 17 January, urged by the WHO, Nepal began screening passengers arriving in [[Tribhuvan International Airport]] from China, Thailand and Japan, the three countries with multiple confirmed cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/sri-lankan-president-thanks-pm-modi-for-saarc-conference-promises-colombos-support-to-combat-covid-1920200316075726/|title=Sri Lankan President thanks PM Modi for SAARC conference; promises Colombo's support to combat COVID-19|website=ANI News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Eight persons manned the health desk. The airport did not have infrared scanners and was therefore using thermal scanners as preparations were being made to install the infrared ones. The passengers who showed fever were being asked to remain in contact and contact the hospitals if they showed additional symptoms.<ref name=thermal>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-has-no-boundaries-says-minister-of-health-and-population-bhanubhakta-dhakal/|title=Coronavirus has no boundaries, says Health Minister Dhakal|date=2020-01-25|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, Dr. Bashudev Pandey, director of Teku Hospital, was quoted as saying that the hospital was on high alert, while three other hospitals \u2013 Nepal Police Hospital, [[Patan Hospital]] and [[Tribhuvan University Teaching Hospital]] \u2013 would also treat the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/85487/|title=Nepal is untouched by coronavirus so far, say govt authorities|last=Hyolmo|first=Kunga|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Six beds in Teku Hospital had been allocated for isolation of suspected patients.<ref name=thermal/>\n\nOn 25 January, a day after the first case was confirmed, the Health Ministry informed that two other suspected patients were in [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] at Teku Hospital.<ref name=two>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/25/after-one-confirmed-case-officials-suspect-coronavirus-infection-in-two-more-nepalis|title=Two more coronavirus cases suspected but government agencies are woefully prepared to combat its spread|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201130018/https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/25/after-one-confirmed-case-officials-suspect-coronavirus-infection-in-two-more-nepalis|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The hospital discharged them in the morning of 27 January without waiting for test results even though the results were due later that same day, raising concerns over its handling of the crisis. The tests which confirmed a negative result for both patients were conducted at the bio-safety level-2 labs of the National Public Health Laboratory, the first such tests to be performed in Nepal. Reagents sufficient for 100 tests were borrowed from the Centre for Molecular Dynamics and test kits were provided by the World Health Organisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/01/27/doctors-released-two-more-patients-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-without-waiting-for-test-results|title=Doctors released two more patients suspected of having coronavirus without waiting for test results|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> A woman was in isolation awaiting test results as of 27 January.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/testing-for-coronavirus-starts-in-nepal/|title=Testing for coronavirus starts in Nepal|date=2020-01-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January, Nepal closed down the [[Rasuwagadhi]] border with China, bringing Nepal-China trade to a complete halt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-hits-nepal-china-trade/|title=Coronavirus hits Nepal-China trade|date=2020-02-03|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Bordering districts of India were reported to be in high alert, and medical personnel had been deployed to various entry points along the Indo-Nepal border.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/news/indo-nepal-border-put-on-high-alert-due-to-corona-virus/videoshow/73683956.cms|title=Indo-Nepal border put on high alert due to corona virus {{!}} News - Times of India Videos|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===February===\nBy the first week of February, Nepal reported a shortage of face masks, as people hurried to buy them following reports of the first confirmed case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/03/nepalis-rush-to-buy-face-masks-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-but-there-are-none-available|title=Nepalis rush to buy face masks amidst coronavirus outbreak but there are none available|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> Districts bordering India began setting up health desks at border crossings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86597/|title='Corona health desk' set up in Mahottari|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86513/|title=Corona virus prevention health desk set up at Jamunaha|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Epidemiology and Disease Control Division reported that it had devised its own treatment protocol based on the one developed by UN Health Agency and directed all private hospitals to strictly follow the guidelines in handling any suspected new cases.<ref name=two/> By 1 February, Teku Hospital had handled five suspected cases all of whom tested negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/five-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative|title=Five coronavirus suspects test negative|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 4 February, the Minister for Health informed that three hospitals had been made capable of testing for the virus, and 43 beds had been made available for patients of the possible outbreak. He also informed that health desks had been setup in Pokhara, Chitwan and Bhairahawa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/86669/|title=Coronavirus not yet seen in Nepal, government preparing for high alertness|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> On 5 February, Nepal donated 100,000 protective masks to China as a gesture of friendship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/coronavirus-crisis-nepal-donates-100000-masks-to-china.html|title=Coronavirus crisis: Nepal donates 100,000 masks to China \u2013 OnlineKhabar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nA village in [[Sindhupalchok District]] reported hundreds of cases with fever, cough and difficulty breathing, starting on 10 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/government-allays-fear-of-coronavirus-in-sindhupalchowk/|title=Govt allays fear of coronavirus in Sindhupalchowk|date=2020-02-13|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 12 February, the district ruled out the possibility that it could be COVID-19 based on travel history of people in the village.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/87396/|title=Coronavirus infection ruled out in Sindhupalchowk|last=RSS|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/gumba-village-not-affected-by-coronavirus|title=Gumba village not affected by coronavirus|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Laboratory testing later confirmed that the outbreak was influenza but not COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/sindhupalchowk-patients-suffer-from-influenza-test-negative-for-covid-19/|title=Sindhupalchowk patients suffer from influenza, test negative for COVID-19|date=2020-02-17|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nAs of 13 February, Nepal had conducted tests on 19 suspected patients. A [[Saudi Arabia]]n national who only spoke Arabic and appeared to object to being kept in the hospital, fled from isolation, and could not be located. The health ministry said it would start using police to guard suspected patients at the hospital.<ref name=fled>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-suspect-goes-missing/|title=Coronavirus suspect goes missing|date=2020-02-13|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215183546/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-suspect-goes-missing/|archive-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, the government was reported to have devised contingency plans to tackle the virus. Under Plan A, the government was preparing to evacuate Nepali citizens stranded in Hubei and keep them in isolation in Bhaktapur. Plan B included educating the people and distributing protective kits. The details of Plan C which would be implemented in case the disease actually spread and started killing people were not shared.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative/|title=Three coronavirus suspects test negative|date=2020-02-14|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311200934/https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/three-coronavirus-suspects-test-negative/|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNepal evacuated 175, mostly students, who had been stranded across Hubei,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/02/17/nasal-throat-swabs-collected-from-nepalis-evacuated-from-china-s-wuhan-tests-to-be-conducted-today|title=Nasal, throat swabs collected from Nepalis evacuated from China's Wuhan; tests to be conducted today|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> on 16 February 2020, using a Nepal Airlines chartered aeroplane<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/na-plane-carrying-175-nepalis-enroute-to-ktm-from-wuhan/|title=NA plane carrying 175 Nepalis enroute to Ktm from Wuhan|date=2020-02-15|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and placed them in a 14-day quarantine at Kharipati in [[Bhaktapur]]. Six other Nepalis were prevented from leaving by the Chinese government, while four of the applicants who had requested rescue later changed their minds. Although 180 Nepalis had applied for immediate evacuation from China by 2 February; the effort took almost two weeks, as the government struggled to meet WHO's evacuation standards, and find a suitable venue for quarantine. The government was criticised for its slow response; a [[Public interest litigation]] was filed at the Supreme Court demanding immediate action,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/pil-filed-against-govt-demanding-nepalis-in-china-be-brought-home/|title=PIL filed against govt demanding Nepalis in China be brought home|date=2020-02-11|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> while the locals around the designated quarantine site in Bhaktapur protested the government's decision which the viewed as endangering to the local community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/nepalis-in-china-make-frantic-pleas-to-return-home/|title=Nepalis in China make frantic pleas to return home|date=2020-02-08|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/immediately-evacuate-nepalis-from-china-national-human-rights-commission/|title=Immediately evacuate Nepalis from China: NHRC|date=2020-02-10|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/mps-flay-laxity-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-china/|title=MPs flay laxity to evacuate Nepalis from China|date=2020-02-05|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-likely-to-evacuate-nepalis-from-chinas-hubei-on-saturday/|title=Govt likely to evacuate Nepalis from China's Hubei on Saturday|date=2020-02-11|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 19 February, the Health Ministry reported that all of the evacuees had tested negative.<ref name=evac>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88095/|title=Initial tests show Wuhan evacuees free of coronavirus|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88049/|title=175 Nepali nationals evacuated from China tested negative for coronavirus, says MoHP|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February, the Chinese Embassy in Nepal criticised ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' for republishing a ''[[The Korea Herald|Korea Herald]]'' piece critical of China's handling of the pandemic, accusing editor-in-chief Anup Kaphle of anti-China bias. In response, 17 editors from Nepalese mainstream press released a joint statement expressing concern about the singling out of the editor, and reminding the Chinese Embassy of diplomatic norms and constitutionally guaranteed freedom of the Press in Nepal; ''The Kathmandu Post'' published an editorial criticising the Embassy's actions. The Chinese embassy's actions were seen as uncharacteristic and surprising as China is known for non-interference in Nepal's internal matters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/south-asia/article/3051648/nepalese-newspaper-accuses-china-veiled-threats-against-editor|title=Nepalese newspaper accuses China of 'veiled threats against editor'|date=2020-02-20|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/nepal-media-feels-chinas-wrath-in-coronavirus-fallout/|title=Nepal media feels China's wrath in coronavirus fallout|last=Dixit|first=Kunda|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/china-cannot-dictate-terms-to-a-free-media-in-nepal-can-pm-oli-resist-analysis/story-F4KTSO7XH5dqcrObjPYtsN.html|title=China cannot dictate terms to a free media in Nepal. Can PM Oli resist?{{!}} Analysis|date=2020-02-26|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of February, the health desk at Tribhuvan International Airport was screening passengers from China, South Korea, Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia, Japan and Saudi Arabia, but did not have sufficient manpower and equipment to screen all new arrivals. A total of six infrared scanners had been setup; the only thermal scanner had yet to be repaired, but plans were underway to purchase three more.<ref name=thtscan>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/samples-collected-for-second-time-from-quarantined-nepalis/|title=Samples collected for second time from quarantined Nepalis|date=2020-03-01|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Passengers were not being asked to fill locator forms that would make it possible to track them down later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/01/as-un-health-agency-raises-covid-19-outbreak-risk-to-the-highest-level-nepal-scrambles-go-step-up-measures|title=As UN health agency raises Covid-19 outbreak risk to the highest level, Nepal scrambles to step up measures|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It was also reported that the government was seeking help from the UN having failed to procure masks and protective gear due to global shortages.<ref name=tkp227/> On 29 February, the government formed a high level committee to prevent and control the spread of COVID-19 under the leadership of Deputy Prime Minister [[Ishwor Pokhrel]].<ref name=thtscan/> The government also decided to suspend promotional activities for Visit Nepal 2020.<ref name=mr31>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89188/|title=Govt urges one and all to avoid public gathering to prevent outbreak of coronavirus|last=Subedi|first=Kamal|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Nepal suspended labour migration to South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/07/as-covid-19-spreads-to-malaysia-and-the-persian-gulf-countries-uncertainty-looms-over-nepal-s-labour-migration|title=As Covid-19 spreads to Malaysia and the Persian Gulf countries, uncertainty looms over Nepal's labour migration|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> India started screening passengers from Nepal and making masks compulsory for all visiting Nepalis.<ref name=tkp227>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/02/27/as-covid-19-spreads-public-health-officials-consider-plans-for-a-worst-case-scenario|title=As Covid-19 spreads, public health officials consider plans for a worst-case scenario|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It was also screening Nepalis travelling into India by land, at various checkpoints at the border.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/88395/|title=India to start screening all air passengers from KTM starting from Monday|last=Republica|website=My Republica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n[[File:20200326 - United Nations in Nepal - CORONA PSA.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:24|Gudelines from the United Nations.]]\n\n'''1 March:''' Nepal announced suspension of [[Visa on arrival|visa-on-arrival]] service for nationals of five countries badly affected by COVID-19 \u2013 China, South Korea, Japan,Italy and Iran \u2013 to be enforced from 7 to 30 March.{{efn|The implementation date was later reported to be 10 March.<ref name=tkp33/>}}<ref name=\"Nepal suspends visa-on-arrival\">{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends visa-on-arrival for nationals of countries badly affected by COVID-19 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/02/c_138836161.htm |website=Xinhua|accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89193/|title=Nepal announces temporary suspension of visa on arrival from March 7 to prevent coronavirus outbreak|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=tkp32>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/02/all-175-nepalis-evacuated-from-hubei-province-test-negative-for-covid-19|title=All 175 Nepalis evacuated from Hubei Province test negative for Covid-19|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It also urged the general public to avoid large gatherings.<ref name=mr31/> The passengers and crew involved in the evacuation of Nepalis from Hubei were released from quarantine after all tests again came back negative following a two-week quarantine.<ref name=tkp32/>\n\n'''2 March:''' The Supreme Court issued an interim order to suspend flights to and from countries affected by the disease, in response to a public interest litigation. The government issued a travel advisory against non-essential travel to countries hardest hit by the disease, including China, Iran, South Korea, Japan and Italy.<ref name=tkp33>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/03/aviation-authority-urges-government-to-implement-stringent-travel-restrictions|title=Aviation authority urges government to implement stringent travel restrictions|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The visitors coming from or via these countries would be required to submit a health certificate. Health checkpoints were to be established at all major entry points from India and third country citizens would be allowed to cross from select border check-points only. The [[Sagarmatha Sambaad|Sagarmatha Sambad]] programme scheduled for April was also postponed.<ref name=tkp33/>\n\n'''4\u20135 March:''' Due to a severe shortage of face-masks and protective gear as well as increase in price following a ban on export in China and India, some hospitals were reported to be sewing plain clothes masks as a precaution.<ref name=tkp34>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/03/04/hospitals-urge-ministry-to-arrange-for-face-masks-gloves-and-other-protective-gear|title=Hospitals urge ministry to arrange for face masks, gloves and other protective gear|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> A shortage of hand sanitisers was also reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/04/hand-sanitisers-in-short-supply-due-to-buying-rush-sparked-by-outbreak-fears|title=Hand sanitisers in short supply due to buying rush sparked by outbreak fears|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> [[Everest Premier League]], the domestic T20 cricket tournament was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fallout-everest-premier-league-postponed|title=COVID-19 fallout: Everest Premier League postponed|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''8 March:''' Qatar imposed a temporary ban on arrivals from Nepal and other countries, affecting almost 40,000 labour migrants with valid work permits who were yet to leave.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/09/qatar-places-temporary-ban-on-entry-of-people-from-14-countries-including-nepal|title=Thousands of Nepali workers affected as Qatar imposes temporary entry ban amidst Covid-19 outbreak|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Nepal Airlines and Himalaya Airlines suspended their flights to Doha indefinitely following the ban.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/nac-and-himalaya-airlines-suspend-flights-to-doha/|title=NAC and Himalaya Airlines suspend flights to Doha|date=2020-03-11|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''9 March:''' The government expanded the suspension of visa-on-arrival service to include three additional countries \u2014 France, Germany and Spain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/89928/|title=Nepal temporarily suspends on-arrival visa for nationals of France, Germany and Spain|last=Subedi|first=Kamal|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''10 March:''' Seventy one Chinese workers employed in the construction of Pokhara Airport who had returned from China after undergoing a 14-day quarantine were put into quarantine for another 14 days. They were being closely monitored and everyone was reported to be in normal health. Previously, 36 Chinese workers working for the project had also gone through a similar quarantine upon return to work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/71-chinese-workers-in-pokhara-quarantined/|title=71 Chinese workers in Pokhara quarantined|date=2020-03-11|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n'''12\u201315 March:''' Nepal decided to suspend on-arrival tourist visa for all countries, with an exception to diplomatic and official visas, to last from 14 March till 30 April. The government closed land border entry points for third country nationals, and cancelled all mountain climbing expeditions including on [[Mount Everest]], to be enforced from 14 March to 30 April. It also declared two-week mandatory self- and home-quarantines for everyone visiting Nepal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends on arrival tourist visa, closes land routes and cancels mountain climbing expeditions |url=https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/12/nepal-government-puts-all-tourist-visas-on-hold-and-cancels-all-spring-climbing-expeditions |website=Kathmandu Post |accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/govt-announces-sweeping-travel-restrictions/|title=Govt announces sweeping travel restrictions|date=2020-03-13|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Labour permits for all countries were suspended indefinitely, including to workers who were only back home on holiday. The government also suspended issuance of no objection letters to students going for abroad study until 30 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/on-arrival-visas-scrapped-till-april-30/|title=On-arrival visas scrapped till April 30|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The [[Province No. 1]] government unveiled plans for two quarantine sites in the province, including one on a [[Koshi River]] island. It also assured plans were underway to provide additional equipment to health personnel, to set up health desks on border-crossings with India, to keep ambulances in standby and to maintain isolation wards in three major hospitals \u2013 [[B.P. Koirala Memorial Cancer Hospital|BP Koirala Institute Of Health Science]] in [[Dharan]], Koshi Hospital in [[Biratnagar]] and Mechi Hospital in [[Jhapa District|Jhapa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/two-quarantine-centres-to-be-established-in-province-1/|title=Two quarantine centres to be established in Province 1|date=2020-03-13|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/28-isolation-wards-prepared-in-province-1/|title=28 isolation wards prepared in Province 1|date=2020-03-05|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> BP Koirala Institute of Health sciences in Dharan reported that a suspected patient had refused to remain in hospital and returned home. He had promised to return the following day for testing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/2/2020/03/14/man-suspected-of-having-coronavirus-refuses-to-stay-in-isolation-ward-and-returns-home|title=Man suspected of having coronavirus refuses to stay in isolation ward and returns home|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The same day, Bihar transport department suspended Patna-Nepal bus services with immediate effect, to be enforced until 31 March, in an effort to contain the virus, after many cases emerged throughout India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/15/operation-of-patna-nepal-buses-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak-2116837.html|title=Operation of Patna-Nepal buses postponed due to coronavirus outbreak|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> India declared a suspension of all passenger movement through Indo-Nepal border, except a few designated checkpoints \u2013 Banbasa, Raxaul, Ranigunj and Sunauli<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90832/|title=Govt mulls complete closure of border with India|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> \u2013 with intensified health inspections, effective from 15 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/coronavirus-passenger-movements-through-pak-bdesh-nepal-bhutan-myanmar-border-points-suspended-55426|title=Coronavirus: Passenger movements through Pak, B'desh, Nepal, Bhutan, Myanmar border points suspended|last=Tribune News Service |website=Tribuneindia News Service |access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The land-border checkpoints with China began releasing imported goods following quarantine procedures as cases in China began to drop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/containers-stalled-at-rasuwagadi-start-entering-nepal/|title=Containers stalled at Rasuwagadi start entering Nepal|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi proposed starting the COVID-19 Emergency Fund for the SAARC region; he also said India could share a Disease Surveillance Software with SAARC partners, and hinted at the possibility of conducting coordinated research on controlling epidemic diseases in the SAARC region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90492/|title=Indian PM Modi proposes COVID-19 Emergency Fund to combat coronavirus in South Asia|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''17 March:''' A meeting of the high-level coordination committee for prevention and control of COVID-19 decided to add 115 ICU and 1,000 isolation beds in the Kathmandu Valley. It also instructed the provincial governments to setup a total of 120 ICU beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90596/|title=Govt to set up 235 ICU beds amid coronavirus fears|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''18\u201319 March:''' The government declared suspension of all classes<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90755/|title=Govt takes sweeping measures to contain spread of COVID-19|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and postponement of all academic examinations including the [[Secondary Education Examination (Nepal)|Secondary Education Examination]] until 12 April, the end of the Month of [[Chaitra]], the last month of Nepali calendar year when all schools hold the [[final examination]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/govt-postpones-all-examinations-till-12-april|title=Govt postpones all examinations till 12 April|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Tribhuvan University and the Public Service Commission also postponed all their examinations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90797/|title=Amid COVID-19 fears, PSC halts scheduled exams until further notice|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The government banned all passengers, including Nepalis, from EU and the UK, West Asia and the Middle East as well as Malaysia, South Korea and Japan, effective from 20 March until 15 April. It also decided to shut down all cinema halls, gymnasiums,museums and cultural centres, and ban gathering of more than 25 people in any public spaces including at places of worship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/18/government-bans-entry-of-all-passengers|title=Government bans entry of all passengers, including Nepalis, from midnight March 20|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Nepal began to see a significant influx of people from India to Nepal as India saw increase in new cases throughout the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/sudurpaschim-province/2020/03/18/amid-covid-19-threat-banbasa-border-sees-a-sudden-influx-of-people-returning-home-from-india|title=Amid Covid-19 threat, Banbasa border sees a sudden influx of people returning home from India|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> A noticeable outflux of people from the Kathmandu Valley was reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/number-of-people-leaving-kathmandu-valley-increases/|title=Number of people leaving Kathmandu Valley increases|date=2020-03-19|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The House of Representatives meeting was postponed until 26 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/govts-measures-to-fight-covid-19-inadequate-say-mps/|title=Govt's measures to fight COVID-19 inadequate, say MPs|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Province No. 1 government established quarantine centres throughout the province with a total capacity of 440 beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/440-bed-quarantine-centres-in-province-1/|title=440-bed quarantine centres in Province 1|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20200320 - UNDP Nepal - How to protect yourself from Coronavirus.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:02|The actress [[Rekha Thapa]] spreading precaution measures.]]\n\n'''20 March:''' The National Assembly was suspended indefinitely.<ref name=mr319>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90872/|title=National Assembly put off until further notice|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Health Ministry instructed public employees to report on weekends as well, and not leave the Kathmandu Valley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/health-ministry-bars-employees-from-leaving-kathmandu-valley|title=Health ministry bars employees from leaving Kathmandu valley|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> All weekly newspapers published from the Kathmandu Valley ceased their print editions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90891/|title=COVID-19 fear: Weekly newspapers from Kathmandu cease their print version|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The US government pledged $1.8&nbsp;million to Nepal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/us-government-pledges-1-8-million/|title=US government pledges $1.8&nbsp;million|date=2020-03-20|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Prime Minister Oli addressed the nation for the first time since the start of the pandemic and announced a list of preventative measures. All international flights would be stopped from 22 March to 31 March and vehicular movement on long routes would be closed from 23 March. All government services and private offices except those providing essential services would be closed until 3 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-southasia-idUSKBN217117|title=Sri Lanka imposes curfew as South Asia steps up coronavirus battle|date=2020-03-20|agency=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0926\u0947\u0936\u092d\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092f\u093e\u0924\u093e\u092f\u093e\u0924 \u092c\u0928\u094d\u0926, \u092d\u093e\u0930\u0924\u0940\u092f \u0938\u0940\u092e\u093e \u0928\u093e\u0915\u093e \u0916\u0941\u0932\u094d\u0932\u093e !036 |url=https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846036 |website=Onlinekhabar |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=ne |trans-title=Indian border crossing open, traffic closed within country}}</ref> A notice from Nepal Tourism Board announced the suspension of issuance of trekking permits for tourists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nepal suspends issuance of trekking permits for foreign trekkers |url=http://www.china.org.cn/world/Off_the_Wire/2020-03/20/content_75840039.htm |website=China.org.cn |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> The outflux of people from the Kathmandu Valley intensified; almost 300,000 people had left in the preceding three days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/people-leaving-kathmandu-on-the-rise-photo-feature|title=People leaving Kathmandu on the rise (Photo Feature)|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Health Ministry decided to halt non-urgent health check-ups and surgeries until 12 April in hospitals in the Kathmandu Valley with 50 or more beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/miscellany/big-hospitals-to-stop-non-urgent-health-check-up-surgeries|title=Big hospitals to stop non-urgent health check-up, surgeries|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> A full bench meeting of the Supreme Court presided over by the Chief Justice decided to halt all non-urgent proceedings in courts across the country until 4 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/supreme-court-to-halt-non-urgent-proceedings/|title=Supreme Court to halt non-urgent proceedings|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90877/|title=Courts across the country to be closed for two weeks|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Nepal government pledged Rs 100 Million to the [[SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/90907/|title=Nepal to contribute Rs 100 million to SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund|last=Republica|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''21 March:''' Kathmandu city launched a central help desk and a toll-free 24-hour hotline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/dial-1180-in-case-of-covid-19-suspicion-kmc/|title=Dial 1180 in case of COVID-19 suspicion: KMC|date=2020-03-22|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Germany pledged an additional one million Euros to its existing health programmes in Nepal to help combat the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/german-aid-to-nepal/|title=German aid to Nepal|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Around sixty passengers from COVID-19 affected countries that landed on Tribhuvan Interantional Airport were sent to quarantine at Kharipati, Bhaktapur; they had not presented any symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/63-people-sent-to-kharipati-quarantine|title=63 people sent to Kharipati Quarantine|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It was reported that Gandaki Province had set up 111 isolation beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/111-isolation-beds-in-gandaki-province|title=111 isolation beds in Gandaki province|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Metropolitan Traffic Police Division suspended breathalyser tests as well as educational classes for drivers found breaking traffic rules.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/police-put-off-drink-and-drive-operation|title=Police put off 'drink and drive' operation|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It also deployed 200 of its personnel to display placards with awareness messages about the disease by the roadside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/main-news/traffic-police-generate-awareness-about-covid-19|title=Traffic police generate awareness about Covid-19|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> [[Nepal Police]] established coronavirus response units in all its stations and decided not to make arrests for minor offences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/21/police-set-up-coronavirus-response-unit-at-every-station|title=Police set up coronavirus response unit at every station|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Health Ministry informed that private hospitals with more than 100 beds would not be allowed to refer patients to other hospitals; they were required to treat suspected patients, wait for test results and provide free treatment if the disease were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ekantipur.com/news/2020/03/21/158475695256349344.html|title=\u0938\u092f \u092c\u0947\u0921\u092e\u093e\u0925\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0905\u0938\u094d\u092a\u0924\u093e\u0932\u0932\u0947 \u092c\u093f\u0930\u093e\u092e\u0940 \u0930\u0947\u092b\u0930 \u0917\u0930\u094d\u0928 \u0928\u092a\u093e\u0909\u0928\u0947 |website=ekantipur.com |language=ne|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''22 March:''' Nepal decided to close its land border with India and China for a week effective from 23 March. The government also declared a Rs 500 million fund with contributions of a month's salary from government ministers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/22/government-to-close-down-border-with-india-and-china-for-a-week|title=Government to close down border with India and China for a week|website=Kathmandu Post |access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It also increased the allowances for health workers working at the front desks of hospitals by 50\u2013100%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onlinekhabar.com/2020/03/846585 |title=\u0938\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0938\u094d\u0925\u094d\u092f\u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0932\u093e\u0908 \u092a\u0940\u092a\u0940\u0908 \u0930 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u094b\u0924\u094d\u0938\u093e\u0939\u0928 \u092d\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093e \u0926\u093f\u0928\u0947 \u0928\u093f\u0930\u094d\u0923\u092f |work=onlinekhabar.com |access-date=22 March 2020 |language=ne}}</ref> [[Kanchanpur District|Kanchanpur]] and [[Banke District]]s declared lockdowns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/kanchanpur-nepalgunj-under-indefinite-lockdown/|title=Kanchanpur, Nepalgunj under indefinite lockdown|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''23 March:''' COVID-19 was confirmed in a 19-year-old woman who had returned from France on 17 March via Qatar, the first case in two months, second overall. She was admitted into isolation at Teku Hospital. Her family is said to be in quarantine at home.<ref>{{cite web |title=One imported case of coronavirus confirmed in Nepal |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-imported-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-nepal/ |website=The Himalayan Times |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> The Office of the attorney General was reported to have asked the Police to release people held for minor crimes under bail or parole to reduce crowding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/opinion/editorial-inadequate-testing/|title=EDITORIAL: Inadequate testing|date=2020-03-23|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The Minister of Health declared that all patients of COVID-19 would be rescued as necessary and provided free treatment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/govt-will-rescue-provide-free-treatment-to-infected-people-health-minister-dhakal|title=Govt will rescue, provide free treatment to infected people: Health minister Dhakal|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> [[Kailali District]] was reported to have declared an indefinite lock-down effective from 2&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/91136/|title=Curfew clamped in Kailali to prevent COVID-19|last=RSS|website=My Republica|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> [[Arghakhanchi District]] also declared an indefinite lock-down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/nation/arghakhanchi-district-to-be-locked-down-from-midnight|title=Arghakhanchi district to be locked down from midnight|website=GorakhaPatra|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n'''24 March:''' The country-wide lockdown came into effect.<ref name=four/>\n\n'''25 March:''' The third case in Kathmandu was confirmed. The patient had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates and was staying in a hotel in Kathmandu. They are being treated in Teku Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/third-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Third person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|date=2020-03-25|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n'''26 March:''' Rescue of tourists stranded throughout Nepal was initiated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/latest/more-stranded-tourists-evacuated-from-nepal/|title=More stranded tourists evacuated from Nepal|last=Times|first=Nepali|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> By 28 March, hundreds of tourists had been rescued and brought to Kathmandu; many were being repatriated via chartered flights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/rescue-flights-continue-on-saturday/|title=Rescue flights continue on Saturday|date=2020-03-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n'''27 March:''' Fourth case nationally, the first outside Kathmandu, was confirmed. It involved a 34-year-old man who had recently returned from the United Arab Emirates. He is being treated at Seti Provincial Hospital in Dhangadhi.<ref name=four>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/27/fourth-nepali-tests-positive-for-covid-19-case|title=Fourth Nepali tests positive for Covid-19|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n'''28 March:''' A 19-year-old woman who had recently travelled to Kathmandu from Belgium via Doha tested positive, bringing the total to five in the country. She had shared a flight from Doha with the patient who was confirmed on 23 March. She had since travelled to her home in Baglung; she was admitted for treatment at Dhaulagiri Zonal Hospital after the test came back positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://risingnepaldaily.com/mustread/covid-19-fifth-patient-moved-freely-in-her-village-for-5-days-got-admitted-to-dhaulagiri-hospital-7-hours-after-being-confirmed|title=COVID-19 fifth patient moved freely in her village for 5 days, got admitted to Dhaulagiri hospital 7 hours after being confirmed !|website=GorakhaPatra|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fifth-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-nepal/|title=Fifth person tests positive for COVID-19 in Nepal|date=2020-03-28|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n'''29 March:''' The government decided to extend the suspension of international flights to until 15 April. The country-wide lockdown was extended to until 8 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/29/nationwide-lockdown-extended-until-april-8-ban-on-international-flights-until-april-15|title=Nationwide lockdown extended until April 8, ban on international flights until April 15|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n'''2 April:''' A 65-year-old woman who recently travelled to Kathmandu from Belgium who accompanied the 19-year-old woman on 17 March tested positive bringing the total to six in the country. Health minister confirmed that she was staying at her home in Baglung. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/one-more-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-nepals-sixth-confirmed-case/|title=One more person tests positive for Covid-19, Nepal\u2019s sixth confirmed case|website=himalayantimes.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/health/2020/04/02/health-ministry-confirms-sixth-covid-19-case|title=Health Ministry confirms sixth Covid-19 case|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Impact and response==\nThe tourism sector has been reported to be suffering due to the absence of Chinese tourists, as well as the various travel restrictions imposed on travel globally. Manufacturing sector is experiencing a shortage of raw materials, most of which used to come from China. The situation is exacerbated by spread of the pandemic to the Middle-east which is the main source of remittance that makes up more than half of Nepal's [[GDP]]. Remittances were expected to sharply drop after Nepal suspended issuance of workers permit to Nepalis for all countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/15/nepal-s-remittance-dependent-economy-braces-for-upheaval-amid-covid-19-pandemic|title=Nepal's remittance-dependent economy braces for upheaval amid Covid-19 pandemic|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The wholesale and retail sector has also been affected due to fall of imports from China. The construction sector which imports most of its building materials from China has slowed down. As the Chinese contractors and workers who went home for the Chinese new year could not return, the public construction projects have also been affected.<ref name=econ>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/04/nepali-economy-starts-to-feel-the-pinch-as-coronavirus-spreads|title=Nepali economy starts to feel the pinch as coronavirus spreads|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/48830-coronavirus-chills-nepal-infrastructure-construction?v=preview|title=Coronavirus Chills Nepal Infrastructure Construction|website=www.enr.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/coronavirus-outbreak-could-shave-off-nepals-economy-by-36-78-million/|title=Coronavirus outbreak could shave off Nepal's economy by $36.78&nbsp;million|date=2020-03-07|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The domestic airlines were reported to be struggling for survival as ticket prices dropped to half or a third of normal following a sharp decline in demand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/11/domestic-airfares-hit-rock-bottom-amidst-coronavirus-travel-advisory|title=Domestic airfares hit rock bottom amidst coronavirus travel advisory|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Number of international flights to and from Nepal had decreased by more than 50% by 13 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/international-flights-drop-significantly-at-tia/|title=International flights drop significantly at TIA|date=2020-03-14|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Nepal's import-dependent economy is also vulnerable to depreciation of Indian currency to which its currency is permanently pegged, as Indian economy suffers the impact of the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/weakening-nepali-currency-to-hit-economy/|title=Weakening Nepali currency to hit economy|date=2020-03-12|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> 20,000 tour, trek and mountaineering guides lost their livelihood when mountaineering was suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/14/suspension-of-climbing-permits-and-on-arrival-visas-entails-losses-of-thousands-of-jobs-and-millions-of-dollars|title=Suspension of climbing permits and on-arrival visas entails losses of thousands of jobs and millions of dollars|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/18/experts-call-for-measures-to-ease-the-impact-of-coronavirus-on-the-economy|title=Experts call for measures to ease the impact of coronavirus on the economy|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nThe annual [[Holi]] celebrations, which fell on 9 and 10 March in 2020 saw decreased activities, low business and cancellation of organised celebrations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/coronavirus-scare-dampens-holi-spirit-businesses-hit/|title=Coronavirus scare dampens Holi spirit, businesses hit|date=2020-03-10|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\nNepal had declared 2020 as the Visit Nepal Year and aimed to bring in two million foreign tourists, almost double the figure from previous year. As the pandemic spread and Nepal had to suspend air travel to and from China, the biggest source of international tourists arriving by air, Nepal suspended its promotional campaigns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/01/c_138831984.htm|title=Nepal postpones int'l tourism promotion amid coronavirus outbreak - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nThe temporary blanket ban on animal markets imposed by China as a response to the pandemic is expected to curb wildlife poaching and trafficking through Nepal, as the Chinese traditional medicine which uses various body parts of endangered animals as its ingredients has been the biggest challenge to wildlife conservation in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/banner/coronavirus-outbreak-may-curb-wildlife-trafficking/|title=Coronavirus outbreak may curb wildlife trafficking|last=Awale|first=Sonia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211183345/https://www.nepalitimes.com/banner/coronavirus-outbreak-may-curb-wildlife-trafficking/|archive-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Market regulation===\nThe department of Commerce, Supplies and Consumer Protection conducted raids on 161 firms and fined 57 of them, a total of around four million Rupees in the month of [[Falgun]] (February\u2013March).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/03/20/government-launches-coordinated-inspections-to-curb-black-marketeering-of-essential-goods|title=Government launches coordinated inspections to curb black marketeering of essential goods|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> It inspected multiple pharmacies and surgical shops in Kathmandu on 5 March and fined a total of Rs 430,000 for hiking prices and other offences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/03/05/government-cracks-down-on-price-gouging-by-pharmacies-and-surgical-shops|title=Government cracks down on price-gouging by pharmacies and surgical shops|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> On 10 March, four pharmacies were fined a total of Rs 800,000 after they were caught charging 1000% of normal price for surgical masks. Some groceries and LPG stores were also inspected. One million units of face masks were confiscated from a warehouse in Kathmandu and the owner arrested on 18 March, bringing the total of masks confiscated in the week past to 2.3&nbsp;million. Around 50,000 units of hand-sanitisers were also confiscated from the black market. Around two dozen black marketeers had been arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/police-seize-one-million-masks/|title=Police seize one million masks|date=2020-03-19|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> As the outflux of people from Kathmandu intensified, 23 transport entrepreneurs and workers were arrested on 20 March for overcharging the passengers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/23-persons-held-for-fleecing-passengers/|title=23 persons held for fleecing passengers|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Essential drugs===\nNepal's pharmaceutical industry has been impacted due to lack of raw materials as a number of essential ingredients were previously imported from Hubei.<ref name=econ/> Nepal faced the prospect of a potential shortage of essential medicines when India imposed restrictions on export of 26 types of raw materials including of essential medicine citing disruption in the supply chain from Hubei; however India later agreed to relax restrictions in case of Nepal, and asked the Nepalese government to provide a list of names and quantities of essential medicines that it needed to supply to Nepal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/india-seeks-list-of-essential-drugs-that-nepal-needs/|title=India seeks list of essential drugs that Nepal needs|date=2020-03-06|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307141100/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/india-seeks-list-of-essential-drugs-that-nepal-needs/|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation===\nOn 21 March a 20-year-old man was arrested on charges of spreading misinformation online through an unregistered [[fake news website]] and causing public fear, after audio tapes alleging cover-up of COVID-19 cases were found circulating online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/youth-arrested-for-spreading-romours-of-covid-19-cases/|title=Youth arrested for spreading romours of COVID-19 cases|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The same day, [[Nepal Army]] dispelled rumours circulating in social media that claimed Army helicopters were being used to spray disinfectants over settlements at midnight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/army-dismisses-helicopter-spraying-disifectant-at-midnight-rumours/|title=Army dismisses 'helicopter spraying disinfectant at midnight' rumours|date=2020-03-21|website=The Himalayan Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Nepal|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Nepal]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Nepal]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Nepal]]\n", "name_user": "120.89.104.186", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eApril)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Nepal"}
